WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.970 --> 00:00:09.820
Welcome to the Jeremy’s IT Lab CCNA mega lab.

00:00:09.820 --> 00:00:15.099
In this lab, we’ll cover every configuration
topic you need to know for the CCNA exam.

00:00:15.099 --> 00:00:17.920
Just a warning: this lab is intense.

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:22.160
If you’ve studied all of the exam topics
and are getting ready to take on the CCNA

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:25.099
exam itself, you’ve come to the right place.

00:00:25.099 --> 00:00:30.179
Now, we won’t cover every single configuration
command you should know, but we will cover

00:00:30.179 --> 00:00:34.350
all configuration topics on the CCNA exam.

00:00:34.350 --> 00:00:42.230
IPv4 and IPv6, static routes, VLANs, spanning
tree, OSPF, EtherChannel, DHCP, DNS, NAT,

00:00:42.230 --> 00:00:46.660
SSH, security features, wireless, and more
– everything!

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:52.379
If you want to dive deeper into any particular
topic, such as specific OSPF configurations,

00:00:52.379 --> 00:00:57.180
you can check out the relevant videos in my
CCNA course, or the relevant chapter in my

00:00:57.180 --> 00:00:58.640
CCNA book.

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:03.059
The point of this lab is to tie everything
together, instead of focusing on each individual

00:01:03.059 --> 00:01:05.970
technology or protocol in detail.

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:10.670
And the point of this video is to demonstrate
the correct solution to this lab, rather than

00:01:10.670 --> 00:01:14.280
to explain the details of each concept again.

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:19.220
You may notice that this lab file isn’t
a typical .pkt Packet Tracer file.

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:23.620
It’s a .pka, Packet Tracer activity, file.

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:28.880
Pka files include automated grading, so after
you complete the lab, you can click Check

00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:32.540
Results here to see if you configured everything
correctly.

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:37.729
Now, by default, the instructions here are
a separate window like this, but I’ll click

00:01:37.729 --> 00:01:42.439
‘Dock’ here to dock them into the same
window as the lab topology, so we can easily

00:01:42.439 --> 00:01:46.530
see the instructions as we go through the
lab.

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:52.189
The network topology for this lab is a three-tier
LAN consisting of two offices, Office A on

00:01:52.189 --> 00:01:54.659
the left and Office B on the right.

00:01:54.659 --> 00:02:01.130
The two offices are connected via a core layer,
and R1 provides Internet access with two redundant

00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:02.469
connections.

00:02:02.469 --> 00:02:06.869
If you click on the Internet here, you can
see it simply consists of two routers that

00:02:06.869 --> 00:02:12.990
I have labeled ISP A and ISP B. You don’t
have to worry about these routers for this

00:02:12.990 --> 00:02:17.390
lab; you only need to configure the network
from the perspective of the customer of these

00:02:17.390 --> 00:02:21.080
ISPs – the enterprise connected to the Internet.

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:25.600
So, click on this back arrow here to return
to the rest of the network.

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:29.890
So, before diving in let’s read the lab
introduction here.

00:02:29.890 --> 00:02:35.190
It says this comprehensive lab covers all
configuration topics on the CCNA exam.

00:02:35.190 --> 00:02:39.660
Proceed through the steps in order and click
Check Results when you are done to check your

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:40.660
configurations.

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:44.409
So, as you can see here this is page 1 of
10.

00:02:44.409 --> 00:02:48.680
You can click next to go through the different
pages to see the different steps.

00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:53.290
But there is an important note here that says
You must save the device configurations, for

00:02:53.290 --> 00:02:59.409
example with the COPY RUNNING-CONFIG STARTUP-CONFIG
command, or you will receive no points.

00:02:59.409 --> 00:03:03.830
The grading system for most of this lab checks
the startup-config of each device to make

00:03:03.830 --> 00:03:09.349
sure it matches the one I prepared beforehand,
so make sure to save each device’s configuration

00:03:09.349 --> 00:03:11.830
or you won’t get points.

00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:16.239
And finally, at the bottom it says this lab
is quite extensive, so you should set aside

00:03:16.239 --> 00:03:19.670
at least a couple of hours to finish all of
it.

00:03:19.670 --> 00:03:24.131
Here at the start of this video I have no
idea how long the video itself will be, but

00:03:24.131 --> 00:03:27.459
I do know it’s going to be the longest video
I’ve ever made.

00:03:27.459 --> 00:03:33.150
So, enough talking, I’ll click on Next to
begin part 1 of this lab, which is Initial

00:03:33.150 --> 00:03:34.150
Setup.

00:03:34.150 --> 00:03:39.640
So, we’re going to configure four main things
in this section: in step 1 we’ll configure

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:42.439
the hostname of each router and switch.

00:03:42.439 --> 00:03:47.870
In step 2, we’ll configure an enable secret
to protect access to privileged exec mode.

00:03:47.870 --> 00:03:51.470
In step 3, we’ll configure a user account.

00:03:51.470 --> 00:03:55.110
And then in step 4 we’ll configure the console
line of each device.

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:59.379
So, let’s start with step 1, configuring
hostnames.

00:03:59.379 --> 00:04:02.420
I’ll open the CLI of R1.

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:06.620
Now, recording this video on a single screen
is a bit of a challenge.

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:12.760
Ideally, I’d like to show the instructions,
the topology, and the CLI all at once, but

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:15.140
there’s just not enough real estate on the
screen.

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:20.630
So, I’ve prioritized making the CLI larger
so you can see all of the configurations easily.

00:04:20.630 --> 00:04:26.040
I’ll show the instructions in between each
step, but while we’re doing the configurations

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:28.100
you won’t be able to see them.

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:33.600
So, first I’ll use ENABLE to enter privileged
EXEC mode here on R1.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:36.130
Then CONF T to enter global config mode.

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:40.259
And then HOSTNAME R1 to configure the router’s
hostname.

00:04:40.259 --> 00:04:43.720
The hostnames must match what’s shown in
the diagram here.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:49.139
Okay, I configured R1’s hostname, but if
I look at the lab instructions, notice that

00:04:49.139 --> 00:04:51.380
the completion rate is still 0%.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:56.881
That’s because the evaluation is checking
the device’s startup-config, but the command

00:04:56.881 --> 00:05:00.169
I just entered only changed the running-config.

00:05:00.169 --> 00:05:05.130
To copy that configuration to the startup-config,
I’ll use DO WRITE, but you could also use

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:11.810
WRITE MEMORY or COPY RUNNING-CONFIG STARTUP-CONFIG;
all three commands have the same effect.

00:05:11.810 --> 00:05:17.240
Then go back to check the completion score
again, and now we’re at 1%.

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:21.350
Because you have to configure many hundreds
of commands in this lab, don’t expect the

00:05:21.350 --> 00:05:25.780
completion score to increase after every single
new command you configure.

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:30.990
However, as you go through the lab, I recommend
saving the device configurations and checking

00:05:30.990 --> 00:05:34.800
that the score is increasing as you proceed.

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:40.270
Now I’ll configure the hostnames of the
core, distribution, and access switches.

00:05:40.270 --> 00:05:44.800
For the sake of completeness, I will show
all of these configurations in this video,

00:05:44.800 --> 00:05:48.900
but feel free to skip ahead if you don’t
want to watch these repetitive commands.

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:51.610
So, I’ll open up CSW1.

00:05:51.610 --> 00:05:52.840
ENABLE.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:57.760
CONF T. HOSTNAME CSW1.

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:01.030
And I’ll save the configuration with DO
WRITE.

00:06:01.030 --> 00:06:03.590
Next, CSW2.

00:06:03.590 --> 00:06:04.870
ENABLE.

00:06:04.870 --> 00:06:09.470
CONF T. HOSTNAME CSW2.

00:06:09.470 --> 00:06:11.730
And save the config with DO WRITE.

00:06:11.730 --> 00:06:20.150
Next up we have the distribution switches:
DSW-A1 and A2, and DSW-B1 and B2.

00:06:20.150 --> 00:06:22.660
I’ll start with DSW-A1.

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:24.140
ENABLE.

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:29.569
CONF T. HOSTNAME DSW-A1.

00:06:29.569 --> 00:06:31.599
DO WRITE.

00:06:31.599 --> 00:06:33.050
Then DSW-A2.

00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:34.310
ENABLE.

00:06:34.310 --> 00:06:38.970
CONF T. HOSTNAME DSW-A2.

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:40.100
DO WRITE.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:44.210
Next, in Office B, DSW-B1.

00:06:44.210 --> 00:06:45.419
ENABLE.

00:06:45.419 --> 00:06:50.229
CONF T. HOSTNAME DSW-B1.

00:06:50.229 --> 00:06:51.849
DO WRITE.

00:06:51.849 --> 00:06:54.699
Finally, DSW-B2.

00:06:54.699 --> 00:06:56.129
ENABLE.

00:06:56.129 --> 00:06:59.910
CONF T. HOSTNAME DSW-B2.

00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:01.030
DO WRITE.

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:06.050
Finally, the same deal on the access switches,
starting with ASW-A1.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:07.530
ENABLE.

00:07:07.530 --> 00:07:13.040
CONF T. HOSTNAME ASW-A1.

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:16.370
And save the config with DO WRITE.

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:17.790
Then ASW-A2.

00:07:17.790 --> 00:07:19.210
ENABLE.

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:23.949
CONF T. HOSTNAME ASW-A2.

00:07:23.949 --> 00:07:25.910
DO WRITE.

00:07:25.910 --> 00:07:27.150
Then A3.

00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:28.389
ENABLE.

00:07:28.389 --> 00:07:33.319
CONF T. HOSTNAME ASW-A3.

00:07:33.319 --> 00:07:35.009
DO WRITE.

00:07:35.009 --> 00:07:38.319
Then move on to office B, starting with ASW-B1.

00:07:38.319 --> 00:07:39.629
ENABLE.

00:07:39.629 --> 00:07:44.289
CONF T. HOSTNAME ASW-B1.

00:07:44.289 --> 00:07:45.819
DO WRITE.

00:07:45.819 --> 00:07:46.949
Then B2.

00:07:46.949 --> 00:07:48.090
ENABLE.

00:07:48.090 --> 00:07:52.630
CONF T. HOSTNAME ASW-B2.

00:07:52.630 --> 00:07:53.819
DO WRITE.

00:07:53.819 --> 00:07:55.930
Finally, B3.

00:07:55.930 --> 00:07:56.979
ENABLE.

00:07:56.979 --> 00:08:01.289
CONF T. HOSTNAME ASW-B3.

00:08:01.289 --> 00:08:02.289
DO WRITE.

00:08:02.289 --> 00:08:06.440
Okay, let’s take a look at the instructions
again.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.849
Take a look at the completion score: it’s
increased a lot already.

00:08:09.849 --> 00:08:13.380
Don’t get too excited – we’re just getting
started.

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:18.270
When the lab first starts, the devices all
have no startup-config, so there’s nothing

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:20.240
to evaluate.

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:24.800
But when you first save the configs, various
default configurations like interface names

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:29.669
are saved to the startup-config; that’s
why the score jumps up after just configuring

00:08:29.669 --> 00:08:32.940
the host names and saving the configs.

00:08:32.940 --> 00:08:37.640
From now on I won’t save the configs after
every single step; I’ll just save them after

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:43.219
each section of the lab to show how the score
increases as we progress.

00:08:43.219 --> 00:08:47.000
Now let’s look at steps 2, 3, and 4 together.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:53.190
Step 2 says to configure the enable secret
‘jeremysitlab’ on each router and switch.

00:08:53.190 --> 00:08:59.800
It also says to use type 9 hashing if available,
or type 5 if type 9 isn’t available.

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:03.560
Let’s hop on R1 again to demonstrate.

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:09.140
From global config mode, type ENABLE and then
a question mark to view the IOS context-sensitive

00:09:09.140 --> 00:09:10.140
help.

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:13.190
So, the options are PASSWORD and SECRET.

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:18.500
Now let’s go to a different device, CSW1,
and see the options.

00:09:18.500 --> 00:09:23.750
Again, type ENABLE and a question mark to
see the options.

00:09:23.750 --> 00:09:27.260
Notice there is a third option: ALGORITHM-TYPE.

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:31.800
This lets you specify the hashing algorithm
that is used to hide the enable secret in

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:32.829
the config.

00:09:32.829 --> 00:09:37.750
I cover this command in my book ‘Acing the
CCNA Exam’, but I haven’t covered it in

00:09:37.750 --> 00:09:41.190
my video course, so you might not be aware
of it.

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:44.170
At some point I’ll update the course and
include it.

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:51.680
Anyway, in Packet Tracer, these core and distribution
switches, which are Cisco Catalyst 3650 switches,

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:56.060
support this command, and you can use type
9 hashing on them.

00:09:56.060 --> 00:10:01.480
But the other devices, including R1 and all
of the access switches, don’t support the

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:02.480
command.

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:05.410
They only support type 5 hashing, which is
MD5.

00:10:05.410 --> 00:10:09.240
So, I’ll return to R1.

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:13.860
Configure the enable secret with ENABLE SECRET
jeremysitlab.

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:19.220
And then check with DO SHOW RUN, use the pipe
(|) to filter the output, then ‘include

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:20.220
secret’.

00:10:20.220 --> 00:10:26.060
As you can see, the secret is hashed using
type 5, which is MD5.

00:10:26.060 --> 00:10:32.610
And then on CSW1, I’ll do ENABLE ALGORITHM-TYPE,
and then use a question mark again.

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:38.300
It has the ‘scrypt’ option; this is type
9 hashing, it uses the scrypt hashing algorithm.

00:10:38.300 --> 00:10:41.320
So, let’s finish the command.

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:46.270
ENABLE ALGORITHM-TYPE SCRYPT SECRET jeremysitlab.

00:10:46.270 --> 00:10:47.720
And let’s check.

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:51.750
DO SHOW RUN | INCLUDE secret.

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:57.320
So, as this number 9 indicates before the
hash, the secret was hashed using the type

00:10:57.320 --> 00:10:58.990
9 algorithm, scrypt.

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:05.030
So, we’ll configure type 9 hashing on the
core and distribution switches, and type 5

00:11:05.030 --> 00:11:07.990
on R1 and the access switches.

00:11:07.990 --> 00:11:12.930
But before we do that, let’s check out steps
3 and 4.

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:17.731
Step 3 says to configure the user account
‘cisco’ with the secret ‘ccna’ on

00:11:17.731 --> 00:11:19.510
each device.

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:26.200
And it says the same thing about hashing:
type 9 if available, and type 5 if not.

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:30.950
Just like the enable secret, in Packet Tracer
these multilayer switches in the core and

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:36.690
distribution layer support type 9, but R1
and the access switches only support type

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:38.570
5.

00:11:38.570 --> 00:11:43.620
Once again, let me demonstrate that in the
CLI, on R1 first.

00:11:43.620 --> 00:11:48.770
First type USERNAME, then the username ‘cisco’,
and then use the question mark.

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:54.029
There is no option for ALGORITHM-TYPE, so
I’ll just type SECRET and then the password

00:11:54.029 --> 00:11:55.200
‘ccna’.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:12:01.080
Let’s check again with DO SHOW RUN | INCLUDE
secret.

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:06.410
Like the enable secret, this user account’s
secret was hashed with MD5, which is type

00:12:06.410 --> 00:12:09.040
5 in IOS.

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:11.320
Now let’s compare that with CSW1.

00:12:11.320 --> 00:12:17.120
First, type USERNAME cisco, and then use the
question mark.

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:23.360
This one has the ALGORITHM-TYPE option, so
I’ll type that, followed by SCRYPT, then

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:26.910
SECRET, and then the secret ‘ccna’.

00:12:26.910 --> 00:12:28.300
And let’s check.

00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:31.390
DO SHOW RUN | INCLUDE secret.

00:12:31.390 --> 00:12:37.280
So, both the enable secret and this account’s
secret were hashed with the scrypt, algorithm,

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:39.510
which is type 9 in IOS.

00:12:39.510 --> 00:12:45.680
So, on these multilayer switches in the core
and distribution layers we’ll use type 9,

00:12:45.680 --> 00:12:49.889
and on R1 and the access switches we’ll
use type 5.

00:12:49.889 --> 00:12:54.790
But before doing that let’s finally take
a look at step 4.

00:12:54.790 --> 00:13:00.510
Step 4 says to configure the console line
to require login with a local user account,

00:13:00.510 --> 00:13:04.750
set a 30-minute inactivity timeout, and enable
synchronous logging.

00:13:04.750 --> 00:13:10.769
So, that requires 3 configuration commands,
and these will be the same on all of the devices.

00:13:10.769 --> 00:13:13.660
I’ll show them on R1 first.

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:20.260
First, use LINE CONSOLE 0 to configure the
console line – there’s only one.

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:25.250
The first instruction was to require login
with a local user account.

00:13:25.250 --> 00:13:28.020
The command to enable that is LOGIN LOCAL.

00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:33.440
Now, when someone connects to the device console
port, they will have to log in using a user

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:38.370
account on the device, such as the ‘cisco’
account we just created.

00:13:38.370 --> 00:13:43.410
The next instruction was to set a 30-minute
inactivity timeout, meaning that the user

00:13:43.410 --> 00:13:46.580
will be logged out after 30 minutes of inactivity.

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:51.290
I’ll use the question mark, and here you
can see the command.

00:13:51.290 --> 00:13:52.290
EXEC-TIMEOUT.

00:13:52.290 --> 00:13:57.610
Type the command, and then the time in minutes,
so 30.

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:03.029
You can also specify seconds after, for example
30 minutes and 30 seconds, but we don’t

00:14:03.029 --> 00:14:04.810
need to in this case.

00:14:04.810 --> 00:14:08.500
Finally, we should enable synchronous logging.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:10.670
The command for that is LOGGING SYNCHRONOUS.

00:14:10.670 --> 00:14:16.880
With that enabled, if a Syslog message appears
while I’m in the middle of writing a command,

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:21.610
the command will be re-printed on a new line,
making it easier to see the command I’m

00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:24.570
typing; it won’t be cut off by the log message.

00:14:24.570 --> 00:14:32.320
Okay, I’ve finished steps 2, 3, and 4 on
R1, so I’ll use DO WRITE to save and EXIT

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:34.790
to return to global config mode.

00:14:34.790 --> 00:14:40.009
Now, for the rest of the devices, I’m simply
going to copy and paste the commands.

00:14:40.009 --> 00:14:45.220
When you’re doing large labs like this that
require configuring the same commands on many

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:50.870
devices, this is a great technique to speed
things up and also avoid typos and misconfigurations.

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:56.269
So, I’ve prepared the commands in a text
file, but I won’t include it in the lab

00:14:56.269 --> 00:14:57.269
files.

00:14:57.269 --> 00:15:01.980
When you do the lab, you can either type the
commands directly into the CLI, or you can

00:15:01.980 --> 00:15:07.100
do what I did: prepare the commands in a text
file like this, and then copy and paste them

00:15:07.100 --> 00:15:08.560
into the CLI.

00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:13.870
So, at the top here are the commands for R1
and the access switches.

00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:18.610
The enable secret, the user account, and the
console line configurations.

00:15:18.610 --> 00:15:23.980
I’m going to copy them with Ctrl-C, and
then paste them into the access switches,

00:15:23.980 --> 00:15:25.680
since I already configured R1.

00:15:25.680 --> 00:15:29.660
Let’s do it on ASW-A1 first.

00:15:29.660 --> 00:15:35.130
To paste commands in Packet Tracer, right
click in the terminal and then click on Paste.

00:15:35.130 --> 00:15:38.420
There we go, all of the commands were pasted
in.

00:15:38.420 --> 00:15:43.230
Finally, I’ll just save the config with
DO WRITE and return to global config mode

00:15:43.230 --> 00:15:45.360
with EXIT.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:49.140
Next, ASW-A2.

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:54.889
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:15:54.889 --> 00:15:57.420
Then A3.

00:15:57.420 --> 00:16:01.440
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:06.850
Now move on to Office B. ASW-B1 first.

00:16:06.850 --> 00:16:10.699
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:16:10.699 --> 00:16:12.910
Then B2.

00:16:12.910 --> 00:16:18.120
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:20.949
And finally ASW-B3.

00:16:20.949 --> 00:16:25.360
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:16:25.360 --> 00:16:29.410
So, R1 and the access switches are done.

00:16:29.410 --> 00:16:33.360
Now let’s take a look at that notepad again
and scroll down.

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:38.870
These switches in Packet Tracer support type
9 hashing for the enable secret and user accounts,

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:43.850
so we’ll use those commands that I showed
before on CSW1, and also configure the console

00:16:43.850 --> 00:16:44.850
line.

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:49.750
So, highlight and copy all of these commands,
and let’s go on CSW1.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:55.640
We already configured the enable secret and
user account here, but not the console line.

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:59.110
I’ll just paste all of the commands in anyway.

00:16:59.110 --> 00:17:06.380
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT to
return to global config mode.

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:09.010
Next up, CSW2.

00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:14.079
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:17:14.079 --> 00:17:18.890
Then the distribution switches, DSW-A1 first.

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:23.799
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, EXIT.

00:17:23.799 --> 00:17:26.079
Then DSW-A2.

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:31.230
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, and EXIT.

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:34.230
DSW-B1 next.

00:17:34.230 --> 00:17:39.169
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, EXIT.

00:17:39.169 --> 00:17:42.600
And finally, DSW-B2.

00:17:42.600 --> 00:17:46.960
Right click, paste, DO WRITE, EXIT.

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:50.610
Okay, we’ve finished part 1.

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:54.480
Notice that the completion score has increased
a few points.

00:17:54.480 --> 00:17:59.659
Still a long way to go, so let’s click Next
to go to part 2.

00:17:59.659 --> 00:18:02.970
Part 2 covers VLAN and Layer-2 EtherChannel
configurations.

00:18:02.970 --> 00:18:08.030
So, we’ll be focusing on the distribution
and access switches in this part.

00:18:08.030 --> 00:18:10.960
First, let’s quickly look at the instructions.

00:18:10.960 --> 00:18:18.600
Step 1 says to configure a Layer-2 EtherChannel
between DSW-A1 and A2 in Office A using a

00:18:18.600 --> 00:18:25.600
Cisco-proprietary protocol, and step 2 says
the same for DSW-B1 and B2, but says to use

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:27.419
an open standard protocol.

00:18:27.419 --> 00:18:34.160
So, a Cisco-proprietary protocol means we’ll
configure PAgP, Port Aggregation Protocol,

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:41.050
between DSW-A1 and A2, and an open standard
protocol means we’ll configure LACP, Link

00:18:41.050 --> 00:18:45.660
Aggregation Control Protocol, between DSW-B1
and B2.

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:51.940
Okay, step 3 then says to configure all links
between access and distribution switches,

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:54.100
including the EtherChannels, as trunks.

00:18:54.100 --> 00:18:57.690
So, all of these links here should be trunks.

00:18:57.690 --> 00:19:03.679
In Step 4, we’ll configure VTP on these
switches so they can sync their VLAN databases

00:19:03.679 --> 00:19:04.679
automatically.

00:19:04.679 --> 00:19:11.330
Then, in steps 5 and 6 we’ll create the
appropriate VLANs in Office A and Office B.

00:19:11.330 --> 00:19:15.710
And in steps 7 and 8 we’ll configure each
access switch’s interfaces connecting to

00:19:15.710 --> 00:19:20.280
end hosts, and finally in step 9 disable unused
ports.

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:24.990
So, that’s part 2, focused on various Layer-2
concepts.

00:19:24.990 --> 00:19:27.970
Let’s start by configuring those EtherChannels.

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:33.070
First, I’ll do step 1, focusing on DSW-A1
and A2.

00:19:33.070 --> 00:19:39.080
We already established that we’ll configure
this one using the Cisco-proprietary PAgP,

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:43.840
but notice also that it says both switches
should actively try to form an EtherChannel.

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:48.480
PAgP has two modes: desirable and auto.

00:19:48.480 --> 00:19:52.390
This means we should configure both sides
to use the desirable mode, which actively

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:54.400
tries to form an EtherChannel.

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:59.530
Auto mode will form an EtherChannel with a
neighbor in desirable mode, but doesn’t

00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:01.150
try to form an EtherChannel itself.

00:20:01.150 --> 00:20:04.919
So, I’ll go on DSW-A1 first.

00:20:04.919 --> 00:20:08.809
Now, there are no interface labels on these
devices.

00:20:08.809 --> 00:20:12.970
To see them, you can turn on interface labels
in Packet Tracer’s settings.

00:20:12.970 --> 00:20:17.429
Or you can look at the spreadsheet that I
included in the lab files – it lists all

00:20:17.429 --> 00:20:20.350
of the connections between devices.

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:27.330
You can get the lab files at this URL: jitl.jp/mega-lab.

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:34.120
But the best method is to practice your CLI
skills and use DO SHOW CDP NEIGHBORS.

00:20:34.120 --> 00:20:40.690
In the output of this command, you can see
that DSW-A1 is connected to DSW-A2 via its

00:20:40.690 --> 00:20:45.200
G1/0/4 and G1/0/5 interfaces.

00:20:45.200 --> 00:20:51.440
The ‘Local Interface’ column lists the
interface on this switch, DSW-A1.

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:55.600
And on the final column on the right, you
can see that the same interfaces are used

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:59.850
on DSW-A2: G1/0/4 and G1/0/5.

00:20:59.850 --> 00:21:07.880
So, I’ll use INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/4-5 to
configure both interfaces at the same time.

00:21:07.880 --> 00:21:15.090
Then, just use CHANNEL-GROUP 1 MODE DESIRABLE
to configure these interfaces as part of PortChannel1.

00:21:15.090 --> 00:21:19.789
Now, how do you know which group number to
use?

00:21:19.789 --> 00:21:24.920
Look carefully at the lab instructions: it
says ‘configure a Layer-2 EtherChannel named

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:26.940
‘PortChannel1’.

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:31.080
This number, the port channel number, is the
group number.

00:21:31.080 --> 00:21:33.740
Make sure to pay close attention to these
instructions.

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:37.900
If you use a different group number, it won’t
be marked correctly when you click on Check

00:21:37.900 --> 00:21:39.890
Results at the end of the lab.

00:21:39.890 --> 00:21:45.740
Okay, now let’s do the same on DSW-A2.

00:21:45.740 --> 00:21:49.950
INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/4-5.

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:53.279
CHANNEL-GROUP 1 MODE DESIRABLE.

00:21:53.279 --> 00:21:58.890
And just to make sure I’ll check its status
with DO SHOW ETHERCHANNEL SUMMARY.

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:01.559
So, here’s PortChannel1.

00:22:01.559 --> 00:22:08.390
It has the flags S and U, meaning Layer2 and
in use, so that’s good.

00:22:08.390 --> 00:22:12.110
And the member ports both have the flag P,
meaning in port-channel.

00:22:12.110 --> 00:22:14.960
So, everything looks good.

00:22:14.960 --> 00:22:21.690
Next, let’s configure the EtherChannel between
DSW-B1 and B2.

00:22:21.690 --> 00:22:28.390
LACP has two modes: active, which is like
PAgP’s desirable mode, and passive, which

00:22:28.390 --> 00:22:31.270
is like PAgP’s auto mode.

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:36.860
Like step 1, step 2 says that both switches
should actively try to form an EtherChannel,

00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:38.539
so we’ll use active mode.

00:22:38.539 --> 00:22:42.990
So, let’s go on DSW-B1.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:50.059
Like the Office A switches, these two are
connected via G1/0/4 and 5, so INTERFACE RANGE

00:22:50.059 --> 00:22:52.159
G1/0/4-5.

00:22:52.159 --> 00:22:56.140
Then, CHANNEL-GROUP 1 MODE ACTIVE.

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:57.179
That’s it.

00:22:57.179 --> 00:23:02.370
I’ll do the same on DSW-B2.

00:23:02.370 --> 00:23:05.919
INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/4-5.

00:23:05.919 --> 00:23:08.680
CHANNEL-GROUP 1 MODE ACTIVE.

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:13.789
And just to make sure it’s okay I’ll check
with DO SHOW ETHERCHANNEL SUMMARY.

00:23:13.789 --> 00:23:20.480
So, we see the SU flags on the port-channel
interface, and the P flag on the physical

00:23:20.480 --> 00:23:23.860
interfaces, so all’s good.

00:23:23.860 --> 00:23:28.169
Now let’s move on to step 3, which says
to configure all links between access and

00:23:28.169 --> 00:23:32.720
distribution switches, including the EtherChannels,
as trunks.

00:23:32.720 --> 00:23:34.320
There are a few requirements.

00:23:34.320 --> 00:23:38.530
First, it says to explicitly disable DTP on
all ports.

00:23:38.530 --> 00:23:41.820
We’ll use SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE for that.

00:23:41.820 --> 00:23:47.030
Then, it says to set each trunk’s native
VLAN to VLAN 1000, which is unused.

00:23:47.030 --> 00:23:52.890
That’s a good security measure; the native
VLAN can make the LAN vulnerable to VLAN-hopping

00:23:52.890 --> 00:23:53.890
attacks.

00:23:53.890 --> 00:24:01.370
Then, we should allow VLANs 10, 20, 40, and
99 on all trunks in Office A, and allow VLANs

00:24:01.370 --> 00:24:08.049
10, 20, 30, and 99 on all trunks in Office
B. When we configure the VLANs later, we’ll

00:24:08.049 --> 00:24:10.540
see the purpose of each of those VLANs.

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:14.539
For now, just make sure to assign the correct
VLAN numbers.

00:24:14.539 --> 00:24:20.890
Okay, first let’s focus on Office A. On
each distribution switch, we need to configure

00:24:20.890 --> 00:24:25.649
these three links to the access switches as
trunks, as well as the port channel between

00:24:25.649 --> 00:24:27.169
the distribution switches.

00:24:27.169 --> 00:24:29.970
So, I’ll hop on DSW-A1.

00:24:29.970 --> 00:24:36.740
First, let’s confirm the correct interfaces
with DO SHOW CDP NEIGHBORS.

00:24:36.740 --> 00:24:45.870
So, ASW-A1, A2, and A3 are connected to this
switch’s G1/0/1, 1/0/2, and 1/0/3 interfaces.

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:50.620
So, let’s configure those interfaces as
trunks.

00:24:50.620 --> 00:24:53.190
INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/1-3.

00:24:53.190 --> 00:24:58.850
First, use SWITCHPORT MODE TRUNK to make the
interfaces trunks.

00:24:58.850 --> 00:25:03.909
Now, the instructions said to explicitly disable
DTP on the ports.

00:25:03.909 --> 00:25:09.970
Even when manually configured in trunk or
access mode, DTP is still technically enabled,

00:25:09.970 --> 00:25:13.289
so let’s disable DTP with SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE.

00:25:13.289 --> 00:25:20.159
Next, I’ll set the native VLAN with SWITCHPORT
TRUNK NATIVE VLAN 1000.

00:25:20.159 --> 00:25:22.669
Finally, set the allowed VLANs.

00:25:22.669 --> 00:25:29.399
This is Office A, so I’ll use SWITCHPORT
TRUNK ALLOWED VLAN 10,20,40,99.

00:25:29.399 --> 00:25:35.680
Next, I’ll use the same commands on PortChannel1.

00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:37.900
INTERFACE PORT-CHANNEL1.

00:25:37.900 --> 00:25:40.399
SWITCHPORT MODE TRUNK.

00:25:40.399 --> 00:25:43.000
SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:45.520
SWITCHPORT TRUNK NATIVE VLAN 1000.

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:52.549
And SWITCHPORT TRUNK ALLOWED VLAN 10,20,40,99.

00:25:52.549 --> 00:25:53.660
And then EXIT.

00:25:53.660 --> 00:25:58.190
Okay, we’re done configuring DSW-A1.

00:25:58.190 --> 00:26:02.410
These commands will be similar on most switches,
so I’ll just copy and paste the commands

00:26:02.410 --> 00:26:04.170
on the others.

00:26:04.170 --> 00:26:09.160
Let me open up the notepad I prepared and
scroll down to Part 2, Step 3.

00:26:09.160 --> 00:26:17.770
First, I’ll copy these commands to configure
on DSW-A2, identical to the commands on DSW-A1.

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:22.350
And now let’s go to DSW-A2, right click,
and paste them.

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:25.830
Then, I’ll use EXIT to return to global
config mode.

00:26:25.830 --> 00:26:30.140
You don’t have to exit after each step by
the way, it’s just a habit of mine.

00:26:30.140 --> 00:26:35.049
Okay, now let’s go back to the notepad and
check the commands for the access switches

00:26:35.049 --> 00:26:42.800
in office A. They are connected to the distribution
switches via their G0/1 and G0/2 interfaces,

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:45.990
so the first command is INTERFACE RANGE G0/1-2.

00:26:45.990 --> 00:26:50.840
Then, the configuration commands are the same
as the other trunks.

00:26:50.840 --> 00:26:56.940
So, let me copy these commands, and first
I’ll go on ASW-A1.

00:26:56.940 --> 00:26:59.149
Right click, paste.

00:26:59.149 --> 00:27:00.260
EXIT.

00:27:00.260 --> 00:27:02.470
Then, ASW-A2.

00:27:02.470 --> 00:27:05.730
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:27:05.730 --> 00:27:07.909
Finally, ASW-A3.

00:27:07.909 --> 00:27:10.660
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:27:10.660 --> 00:27:17.480
Okay, Office A is done, now let’s go back
to the notepad for the Office B switches.

00:27:17.480 --> 00:27:21.700
The configurations for these switches are
nearly identical to Office A.

00:27:21.700 --> 00:27:27.520
The only difference is that Office B uses
VLAN 30 instead of VLAN 40.

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:34.169
Just like in Office A, we’ll make the interfaces
trunks, disable DTP with SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE,

00:27:34.169 --> 00:27:37.799
configure the native VLAN, and allow only
the required VLANs.

00:27:37.799 --> 00:27:42.480
So, let me copy the configurations for the
distribution switches.

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:46.559
Now let’s paste them into DSW-B1 first.

00:27:46.559 --> 00:27:50.190
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:27:50.190 --> 00:27:52.620
Then, DSW-B2.

00:27:52.620 --> 00:27:55.000
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:01.230
Now let’s go back to the notepad and copy
the configurations for the access switches.

00:28:01.230 --> 00:28:05.260
Then paste them into the switches, starting
with ASW-B1.

00:28:05.260 --> 00:28:08.750
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:10.470
Then B2.

00:28:10.470 --> 00:28:13.250
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

00:28:13.250 --> 00:28:15.120
And then B3.

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:18.039
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

00:28:18.039 --> 00:28:20.590
That’s all for step 3.

00:28:20.590 --> 00:28:22.880
Next, let’s look at step 4.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:28.891
It says to configure one of each office’s
Distribution switches as a VTPv2 server, using

00:28:28.891 --> 00:28:30.550
domain name JeremysITLab.

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:37.630
Then, we’ll verify that other switches join
the VTP domain, and configure all Access switches

00:28:37.630 --> 00:28:39.919
as VTP clients.

00:28:39.919 --> 00:28:44.520
These configurations won’t take too long,
so I’ll do them manually.

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:50.880
In Office A, I’ll configure VTP on DSW-A1,
and it should propagate the configurations

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:52.260
to the other switches.

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:58.160
First, I’ll use DO SHOW VTP STATUS to confirm
the default state.

00:28:58.160 --> 00:29:02.860
So, the default VTP Domain Name is null – no
domain name.

00:29:02.860 --> 00:29:07.400
The default version is 1, and the default
operating mode is server.

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:12.370
So, we just need to configure a domain name
and enable VTP version 2.

00:29:12.370 --> 00:29:16.490
VTP DOMAIN JeremysITLab.

00:29:16.490 --> 00:29:19.740
Make sure you get the capitalization correct;
these are case-sensitive.

00:29:19.740 --> 00:29:24.309
Then, VTP VERSION 2.

00:29:24.309 --> 00:29:30.309
Making these configurations should cause DSW-A1
to send VTP advertisements, and the other

00:29:30.309 --> 00:29:32.370
switches should join the domain.

00:29:32.370 --> 00:29:38.659
Let’s check on one other switch to verify,
like ASW-A3.

00:29:38.659 --> 00:29:41.150
DO SHOW VTP STATUS.

00:29:41.150 --> 00:29:48.019
Okay, ASW-A3 is running VTPv2, and has joined
the JeremysITLab domain.

00:29:48.019 --> 00:29:53.779
Now, since step 4 also said to make the access
switches VTP clients, I’ll do that now on

00:29:53.779 --> 00:29:55.049
this switch.

00:29:55.049 --> 00:29:57.760
VTP MODE CLIENT.

00:29:57.760 --> 00:30:01.559
And let’s do it on the others, I’ll go
on A2 next.

00:30:01.559 --> 00:30:04.159
VTP MODE CLIENT.

00:30:04.159 --> 00:30:05.360
And then A1.

00:30:05.360 --> 00:30:08.419
VTP MODE CLIENT.

00:30:08.419 --> 00:30:11.299
Okay, so Office A is done.

00:30:11.299 --> 00:30:17.200
But Office A’s VTP advertisements won’t
reach Office B. VTP advertisements are only

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:21.760
sent out of trunk ports, and we haven’t
configured these links between the distribution

00:30:21.760 --> 00:30:25.870
and core switches as trunks – they’re
currently all in access mode.

00:30:25.870 --> 00:30:28.750
Later, we’ll make them Layer-3 links.

00:30:28.750 --> 00:30:33.580
So, the point is that we need to activate
VTP in Office B, too.

00:30:33.580 --> 00:30:35.990
I’ll go on DSW-B1.

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:42.250
Let’s configure the domain: VTP DOMAIN JeremysITLab.

00:30:42.250 --> 00:30:47.140
And then VTPv2: VTP VERSION 2.

00:30:47.140 --> 00:30:52.090
Instead of checking on this switch, I’ll
just check on ASW-B3; it should have joined

00:30:52.090 --> 00:30:54.190
the domain already.

00:30:54.190 --> 00:30:56.820
DO SHOW VTP STATUS.

00:30:56.820 --> 00:31:01.610
Okay, VTPv2 and domain name JeremysITLab.

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:05.539
Now let’s configure these access switches
as VTP clients.

00:31:05.539 --> 00:31:07.850
VTP MODE CLIENT.

00:31:07.850 --> 00:31:10.570
Then, ASW-B2.

00:31:10.570 --> 00:31:14.149
VTP MODE CLIENT.

00:31:14.149 --> 00:31:16.429
And finally, ASW-B1.

00:31:16.429 --> 00:31:18.750
VTP MODE CLIENT.

00:31:18.750 --> 00:31:22.220
Okay, step 4 is now complete.

00:31:22.220 --> 00:31:27.640
In steps 5 and 6, we’ll create and name
the VLANs in these two LANs.

00:31:27.640 --> 00:31:37.240
In Office A, VLAN 10 is for PCs, VLAN 20 for
phones, VLAN 40 for Wi-Fi, and VLAN 99 for

00:31:37.240 --> 00:31:38.240
Management.

00:31:38.240 --> 00:31:44.399
Office B is similar, but instead of VLAN 40
for Wi-Fi it has VLAN 30 for servers.

00:31:44.399 --> 00:31:49.830
As a side note, why do you think that only
Office A has a Wi-Fi VLAN, even though Office

00:31:49.830 --> 00:31:52.240
B also has an access point?

00:31:52.240 --> 00:31:54.880
Think about that; we’ll address it later.

00:31:54.880 --> 00:32:01.720
So, thanks to VTP, we only have to do these
configurations on a single switch in each

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:04.320
VLAN; VTP should propagate the changes to
the other switches.

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:07.779
So, I’ll go on DSW-A1 again.

00:32:07.779 --> 00:32:14.610
First, I’ll make VLAN 10, and name it with
the command NAME PCs.

00:32:14.610 --> 00:32:18.140
Then, VLAN 20.

00:32:18.140 --> 00:32:19.970
Name it with NAME Phones.

00:32:19.970 --> 00:32:24.010
Then, the Wi-Fi VLAN, VLAN 40.

00:32:24.010 --> 00:32:26.139
NAME Wi-Fi.

00:32:26.139 --> 00:32:28.990
And finally, VLAN 99.

00:32:28.990 --> 00:32:30.140
NAME Management.

00:32:30.140 --> 00:32:31.289
EXIT.

00:32:31.289 --> 00:32:35.760
Let’s double check them with DO SHOW VLAN
BRIEF.

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:42.440
Okay, 10 PCs, 20 Phones, 40 Wi-Fi, and 99
Management.

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:48.320
Now let’s check on ASW-A3 again to make
sure that VTP propagated the changes.

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:52.269
Let’s use DO SHOW VLAN BRIEF here.

00:32:52.269 --> 00:32:57.519
Perfect, it has the same four VLANs with the
correct names.

00:32:57.519 --> 00:33:02.250
Now let’s do the same in Office B, I’ll
configure the VLANs on DSW-B1.

00:33:02.250 --> 00:33:06.080
First, VLAN 10.

00:33:06.080 --> 00:33:07.149
NAME PCs.

00:33:07.149 --> 00:33:10.360
Then VLAN 20.

00:33:10.360 --> 00:33:12.290
NAME Phones.

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:19.110
Office B has SRV1, so I’ll create VLAN 30
and name it with NAME Servers.

00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:22.789
Finally, VLAN 99.

00:33:22.789 --> 00:33:23.789
NAME Management.

00:33:23.789 --> 00:33:24.789
EXIT.

00:33:24.789 --> 00:33:31.270
This time, I won’t even check the VLANs
on this switch; let’s just go straight to

00:33:31.270 --> 00:33:35.860
ASW-B3 and verify that it has synced its VLAN
database.

00:33:35.860 --> 00:33:37.970
DO SHOW VLAN BRIEF.

00:33:37.970 --> 00:33:45.799
Okay, it has VLAN 10 for PCs, VLAN 20 for
Phones, VLAN 30 for Servers, and VLAN 99 for

00:33:45.799 --> 00:33:46.799
Management.

00:33:46.799 --> 00:33:50.490
That’s all for steps 5 and 6.

00:33:50.490 --> 00:33:55.100
In step 7, we’ll configure each access switch’s
access port.

00:33:55.100 --> 00:34:00.269
Of course, in a real network you can expect
many more end hosts, but in a practice lab

00:34:00.269 --> 00:34:05.300
like this there’s not much point in connecting
dozens of PCs to these switches; it just clutters

00:34:05.300 --> 00:34:06.670
up the screen.

00:34:06.670 --> 00:34:12.909
So, ASW-A1 and B1 are both connected to lightweight
Aps - LWAPs.

00:34:12.909 --> 00:34:18.330
As step 7a says, LWAPs will not use FlexConnect.

00:34:18.330 --> 00:34:24.109
That means that all traffic will be tunneled
to WLC1 in the Management VLAN – VLAN 99

00:34:24.109 --> 00:34:25.200
in this case.

00:34:25.200 --> 00:34:31.090
So, these connections to LWAPs can be access
ports; they only need to support the Management

00:34:31.090 --> 00:34:32.609
VLAN.

00:34:32.609 --> 00:34:38.089
By the way, this is also the reason why Office
B doesn’t have a Wi-Fi VLAN.

00:34:38.089 --> 00:34:44.030
Traffic from wireless clients in Office B
is tunneled to WLC1 in Office A, and only

00:34:44.030 --> 00:34:47.550
then is assigned to VLAN 40, the Wi-Fi VLAN.

00:34:47.550 --> 00:34:53.100
So, let’s configure ASW-A1 and B1 first.

00:34:53.100 --> 00:34:59.680
Before we go to ASW-A1, notice that step 7d
says to manually configure access mode and

00:34:59.680 --> 00:35:01.800
explicitly disable DTP.

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:08.010
So, these ports are in dynamic auto mode by
default and will operate as access ports,

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:12.619
but for this lab we need to manually configure
access mode and disable DTP.

00:35:12.619 --> 00:35:16.520
Okay, let’s go on ASW-A1.

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:22.050
These end hosts are connected to each access
switch’s FastEthernet0/1 interface, so I’ll

00:35:22.050 --> 00:35:24.330
configure INTERFACE F0/1.

00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:30.000
First, manually configure access mode with
SWITCHPORT MODE ACCESS.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:37.410
DTP is disabled as a side effect of this command
– it will not send or accept DTP messages.

00:35:37.410 --> 00:35:43.060
However, the instructions say to explicitly
disable DTP, and the command to do that is

00:35:43.060 --> 00:35:45.920
SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE.

00:35:45.920 --> 00:35:50.339
The command is redundant in this case, since
configuring access mode stops the port from

00:35:50.339 --> 00:35:55.800
sending or accepting DTP messages, but make
sure to read each step carefully and not miss

00:35:55.800 --> 00:36:00.270
any configurations, especially on the CCNA
exam.

00:36:00.270 --> 00:36:07.200
Finally, let’s assign this port to the management
VLAN: SWITCHPORT ACCESS VLAN 99.

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:08.200
And then EXIT.

00:36:08.200 --> 00:36:12.600
Okay, now let’s do the same on ASW-B1.

00:36:12.600 --> 00:36:14.599
INTERFACE F0/1.

00:36:14.599 --> 00:36:17.130
SWITCHPORT MODE ACCESS.

00:36:17.130 --> 00:36:21.200
SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE to explicitly disable
DTP.

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:24.420
And then SWITCHPORT ACCESS VLAN 99.

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:25.420
EXIT.

00:36:25.420 --> 00:36:27.609
Okay, these two switches are done.

00:36:27.609 --> 00:36:34.750
Next, let’s configure ASW-A2, A3, and B2,
which are connected to IP phones, in VLAN

00:36:34.750 --> 00:36:38.089
20, and PCs, in VLAN 10.

00:36:38.089 --> 00:36:42.090
Since these three switches will all have the
same configurations, let’s copy and paste

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:43.359
them.

00:36:43.359 --> 00:36:49.359
In my notepad I’ll scroll to Part 2, Step
7, and here are the commands.

00:36:49.359 --> 00:36:53.410
First configure access mode and explicitly
disable DTP.

00:36:53.410 --> 00:36:59.760
Then, configure access VLAN 10, for the PCs,
and voice VLAN 20, for the phones.

00:36:59.760 --> 00:37:02.589
So, I’ll copy these commands.

00:37:02.589 --> 00:37:06.359
And I’ll paste them into ASW-A2 first.

00:37:06.359 --> 00:37:11.880
Right click, paste, and EXIT to return to
global config mode.

00:37:11.880 --> 00:37:14.600
Then, ASW-A3.

00:37:14.600 --> 00:37:17.810
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

00:37:17.810 --> 00:37:20.690
Finally, ASW-B2.

00:37:20.690 --> 00:37:24.110
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:31.420
Finally, we also need to configure ASW-B3’s
connection to SRV1 in VLAN30, the Servers

00:37:31.420 --> 00:37:32.420
VLAN.

00:37:32.420 --> 00:37:38.440
So, on ASW-B3 configure INTERFACE F0/1.

00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:40.839
SWITCHPORT MODE ACCESS.

00:37:40.839 --> 00:37:43.319
SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE.

00:37:43.319 --> 00:37:45.900
SWITCHPORT ACCESS VLAN 30.

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:46.900
EXIT.

00:37:46.900 --> 00:37:49.280
Okay, step 7 is done.

00:37:49.280 --> 00:37:56.870
Next, let’s do step 8, which says to configure
ASW-A1’s connection to WLC1.

00:37:56.870 --> 00:38:02.600
There are three points: it must support the
Wi-Fi and management VLANs, the management

00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:06.440
VLAN should be untagged, and we must disable
DTP.

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:12.720
So, I’ll configure it as a trunk port that
allows both VLANs, assign the management VLAN

00:38:12.720 --> 00:38:17.359
as the native VLAN, and use SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE
to disable DTP.

00:38:17.359 --> 00:38:20.730
Okay, let’s go on ASW-A1.

00:38:20.730 --> 00:38:31.020
WLC1 is connected to F0/2, so INTERFACE F0/2.
Make it a trunk with SWITCHPORT MODE TRUNK.

00:38:31.020 --> 00:38:38.730
Allow only the Wi-Fi and Management VLANs:
SWITCHPORT TRUNK ALLOWED VLAN 40,99.

00:38:38.730 --> 00:38:43.550
Configure the Management VLAN as the native
VLAN: SWITCHPORT TRUNK NATIVE VLAN 99.

00:38:43.550 --> 00:38:48.480
And then disable DTP: SWITCHPORT NONEGOTIATE.

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:49.500
EXIT.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:53.000
Okay, that’s step 8.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:59.859
Finally, in step 9 we’ll administratively
disable all unused ports on access and distribution

00:38:59.859 --> 00:39:00.859
switches.

00:39:00.859 --> 00:39:05.819
So, let’s go on DSW-A1 to confirm which
ports we need to disable.

00:39:05.819 --> 00:39:09.670
To check, use DO SHOW INTERFACES STATUS.

00:39:09.670 --> 00:39:14.630
So, all of these interfaces with the status
‘notconnect’ aren’t connected to another

00:39:14.630 --> 00:39:16.930
switch and should be disabled.

00:39:16.930 --> 00:39:22.560
So, that’s G1/0/6 to 1/0/24, and G1/1/3
and 1/1/4.

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:26.540
So, let’s disable them all at once.

00:39:26.540 --> 00:39:33.180
INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/6-24, then a comma, and
G1/1/3-4.

00:39:33.180 --> 00:39:37.200
Okay, now disable them with SHUTDOWN.

00:39:37.200 --> 00:39:38.740
And then I’ll use EXIT.

00:39:38.740 --> 00:39:42.690
Let’s check with DO SHOW INTERFACES STATUS
again.

00:39:42.690 --> 00:39:47.490
Okay, all of the ‘notconnect’ interfaces
are now disabled.

00:39:47.490 --> 00:39:52.250
And because this is the last step of this
part, I’ll also use DO WRITE to save the

00:39:52.250 --> 00:39:53.420
config.

00:39:53.420 --> 00:39:59.420
Now, the other distribution switches use the
same interfaces, so to disable their unused

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:02.880
interfaces I’ll just copy and paste the
commands from my notepad.

00:40:02.880 --> 00:40:11.740
Here it is: INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/6-24,G1/1/3-4,
and then SHUTDOWN.

00:40:11.740 --> 00:40:17.579
I’ll copy these commands, and then paste
them into DSW-A2 first.

00:40:17.579 --> 00:40:21.250
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:22.990
DO WRITE.

00:40:22.990 --> 00:40:24.690
Then B1.

00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:27.800
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:40:27.800 --> 00:40:29.000
DO WRITE.

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.410
And finally B2.

00:40:31.410 --> 00:40:34.520
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:40:34.520 --> 00:40:35.849
DO WRITE.

00:40:35.849 --> 00:40:40.700
Okay, next up, we’ll disable unused interfaces
on the access switches.

00:40:40.700 --> 00:40:43.910
First, I’ll go on ASW-A1.

00:40:43.910 --> 00:40:50.000
Let’s see which interfaces are in use with
DO SHOW INTERFACES STATUS.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:59.720
So, F0/1 is connected to an LWAP and F0/2
to WLC1, and then G0/1 and 0/2 are connected

00:40:59.720 --> 00:41:01.619
to the distribution switches.

00:41:01.619 --> 00:41:08.590
So, we should disable these remaining FastEthernet
interfaces: F0/3 to 24.

00:41:08.590 --> 00:41:11.040
INTERFACE RANGE F0/3-24.

00:41:11.040 --> 00:41:12.920
SHUTDOWN.

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:14.800
EXIT.

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:17.120
And then DO WRITE to save.

00:41:17.120 --> 00:41:22.920
Now, the other access switches are a bit different:
they only have end hosts connected to their

00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:23.920
F0/1 interfaces.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:28.450
They don’t have a WLC connected like ASW-A1
does.

00:41:28.450 --> 00:41:34.230
So, instead of disabling F0/3 to 24, we’ll
disable F0/2 to 24.

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:38.780
I’ll copy and paste the configurations from
my notepad.

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:44.650
Here are the commands: INTERFACE RANGE F0/2-24,
SHUTDOWN.

00:41:44.650 --> 00:41:50.230
Copy those commands, and then I’ll paste
them into ASW-A2 first.

00:41:50.230 --> 00:41:53.819
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:41:53.819 --> 00:41:55.980
DO WRITE.

00:41:55.980 --> 00:41:57.880
Then A3.

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:01.310
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:42:01.310 --> 00:42:02.310
DO WRITE.

00:42:02.310 --> 00:42:05.760
Move on to ASW-B1 next.

00:42:05.760 --> 00:42:08.420
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:42:08.420 --> 00:42:09.920
DO WRITE.

00:42:09.920 --> 00:42:10.920
Then B2.

00:42:10.920 --> 00:42:15.200
Right click, paste, EXIT DO WRITE.

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:18.390
And finally, ASW-B3.

00:42:18.390 --> 00:42:20.559
Right click, paste, EXIT.

00:42:20.559 --> 00:42:21.559
DO WRITE.

00:42:21.559 --> 00:42:26.650
Okay that’s step 9, and now part 2 of the
lab is complete.

00:42:26.650 --> 00:42:27.890
Look at the completion score.

00:42:27.890 --> 00:42:32.680
We aren’t actually halfway through the lab
because we got a big boost after configuring

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:35.390
the first step but we’ve made some good
progress.

00:42:35.390 --> 00:42:39.050
Now let’s click next to move on to part
3.

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:47.500
Part 3 covers IP addresses, Layer-3 EtherChannel,
and HSRP, Hot Standby Router Protocol.

00:42:47.500 --> 00:42:52.339
This part has a lot of steps, most of it involving
configuring IP addresses, so I’ll do lots

00:42:52.339 --> 00:42:55.260
of copying and pasting here.

00:42:55.260 --> 00:43:00.309
All of the IP addresses are given in the instructions,
but you can also take a look at the spreadsheet

00:43:00.309 --> 00:43:05.510
in the lab files; the second tab in the spreadsheet
has a chart showing all of the IP addresses

00:43:05.510 --> 00:43:07.589
that you can refer to.

00:43:07.589 --> 00:43:12.540
But let’s get started with step 1, which
involves configuring R1’s interfaces.

00:43:12.540 --> 00:43:20.630
G0/0/0 and G0/1/0 are connected to the Internet,
and they will use DHCP to learn their IP addresses.

00:43:20.630 --> 00:43:31.190
Then, we’ll manually configure 10.0.0.33/30
on G0/0, .37/30 on G0/1, and create and configure

00:43:31.190 --> 00:43:35.079
an IP address on loopback0, 10.0.0.76/32.

00:43:35.079 --> 00:43:39.830
So, let’s go on the CLI of R1.

00:43:39.830 --> 00:43:48.790
First, I’ll configure G0/0/0 and G0/1/0
with INTERFACE RANGE G0/0/0, a comma, and

00:43:48.790 --> 00:43:49.790
then G0/1/0.

00:43:49.790 --> 00:43:57.450
Use IP ADDRESS DHCP to make them learn their
IP addresses via DHCP, and don’t forget

00:43:57.450 --> 00:44:02.110
NO SHUTDOWN to enable them; router interfaces
are disabled by default.

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:09.180
Next, let’s configure G0/0; this is the
interface connected to CSW1.

00:44:09.180 --> 00:44:10.520
INTERFACE G0/0.

00:44:10.520 --> 00:44:14.730
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.33 255.255.255.252.

00:44:14.730 --> 00:44:17.619
NO SHUTDOWN.

00:44:17.619 --> 00:44:22.589
Then G0/1, the interface connected to CSW2.

00:44:22.589 --> 00:44:24.890
INTERFACE G0/1.

00:44:24.890 --> 00:44:31.770
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.37 255.255.255.252.

00:44:31.770 --> 00:44:33.820
NO SHUTDOWN.

00:44:33.820 --> 00:44:42.190
And finally, create loopback 0 with INTERFACE
LOOPBACK0, and configure IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.76,

00:44:42.190 --> 00:44:44.599
and a /32 netmask.

00:44:44.599 --> 00:44:50.809
So, let’s check R1’s interfaces with DO
SHOW IP INTERFACE BRIEF.

00:44:50.809 --> 00:45:00.800
Okay, G0/0/0 and 0/1/0 learned IP addresses
via DHCP, and G0/0, G0/1, and loopback0 have

00:45:00.800 --> 00:45:03.270
the IP addresses we configured.

00:45:03.270 --> 00:45:08.210
This is the only step involving R1 in this
section of the lab, so I’ll use DO WRITE

00:45:08.210 --> 00:45:10.319
to save its configuration.

00:45:10.319 --> 00:45:15.250
Before moving on, let’s take a look at that
spreadsheet I mentioned a couple of times;

00:45:15.250 --> 00:45:18.109
it might be useful when you do this lab.

00:45:18.109 --> 00:45:21.980
The first tab lists each device’s physical
connections.

00:45:21.980 --> 00:45:29.770
For example, here at the top left we can see
that R1 G0/0 is connected to CSW1 G1/0/1,

00:45:29.770 --> 00:45:33.920
and G0/1 is connected to CSW2 G1/0/1.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:39.530
Feel free to refer to this chart, or use SHOW
CDP NEIGHBORS in the lab to figure out how

00:45:39.530 --> 00:45:41.440
the devices are connected.

00:45:41.440 --> 00:45:47.500
Then, in the IPv4 tab, you can see each device’s
IP addresses.

00:45:47.500 --> 00:45:55.520
For example, on the R1 to ISP A link, you
can see the subnet here, 203.0.113.0/30.

00:45:55.520 --> 00:46:00.349
Here is ISP A’s IP address, 203.0.113.1.

00:46:00.349 --> 00:46:06.510
And here is R1 G0/0/0’s address, .2, which
it learned via DHCP.

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:08.970
All of the other subnets are listed here too.

00:46:08.970 --> 00:46:17.809
R1 to ISP B, the management subnet for Office
A, the management subnet for office B, etc.

00:46:17.809 --> 00:46:22.220
Once again, feel free to refer to this chart
as needed as you configure this lab.

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:26.559
Okay, let’s return back to the lab itself.

00:46:26.559 --> 00:46:31.330
Step 1 is complete, so let’s move on to
step 2, which says to enable IPv4 routing

00:46:31.330 --> 00:46:34.569
on all core and distribution switches.

00:46:34.569 --> 00:46:38.089
That just requires a single command on each
switch: IP ROUTING.

00:46:38.089 --> 00:46:44.839
So, let’s quickly do that on each of them,
starting with CSW1: IP ROUTING.

00:46:44.839 --> 00:46:51.270
Then CSW2: IP ROUTING.

00:46:51.270 --> 00:46:53.370
DSW-A1.

00:46:53.370 --> 00:46:55.480
DSW-A2.

00:46:55.480 --> 00:46:57.580
DSW-B1.

00:46:57.580 --> 00:46:58.780
And DSW-B2.

00:46:58.780 --> 00:47:02.410
Okay, that’s all for step 2.

00:47:02.410 --> 00:47:10.250
Next, in step 3 we’ll create a Layer-3 EtherChannel
between CSW1 and CSW2 using a Cisco-proprietary

00:47:10.250 --> 00:47:16.570
protocol, so PAgP, and both should actively
try to form an EtherChannel, so we’ll use

00:47:16.570 --> 00:47:18.380
desirable mode.

00:47:18.380 --> 00:47:26.070
The subnet is 10.0.0.40/30, and CSW1 should
use .41 and CSW2 .42.

00:47:26.070 --> 00:47:29.800
Okay, let’s configure that on CSW1 first.

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:34.530
First, let’s see which interfaces are connected
to CSW2.

00:47:34.530 --> 00:47:36.560
DO SHOW CDP NEIGHBORS.

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:45.650
Okay, we can see two entries for CSW2, connected
to CSW1’s G1/0/2 and G1/0/3 interfaces.

00:47:45.650 --> 00:47:50.849
And they are connected to the same interfaces
on CSW2: G1/0/2 and 3.

00:47:50.849 --> 00:47:55.300
So, let’s configure them with INTERFACE
RANGE G1/0/2-3.

00:47:55.300 --> 00:48:00.660
First, I’ll make them routed ports with
NO SWITCHPORT.

00:48:00.660 --> 00:48:07.130
Then, make the EtherChannel with CHANNEL-GROUP
1 MODE DESIRABLE.

00:48:07.130 --> 00:48:12.349
A Layer-3 EtherChannel’s IP address must
be configured on the port channel interface,

00:48:12.349 --> 00:48:13.819
so INTERFACE PORT-CHANNEL1.

00:48:13.819 --> 00:48:21.200
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.41 and a /30 netmask.

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:24.480
Now let’s do the same on CSW2.

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:28.040
INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/2-3.

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:29.220
NO SWITCHPORT.

00:48:29.220 --> 00:48:33.119
CHANNEL-GROUP 1 MODE DESIRABLE.

00:48:33.119 --> 00:48:37.119
Then configure the port-channel: INTERFACE
PORT-CHANNEL1.

00:48:37.119 --> 00:48:43.440
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.42 and a /30 netmask.

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:49.000
Okay, let’s check the EtherChannel with
DO SHOW ETHERCHANNEL SUMMARY.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:55.970
So, on PortChannel1 RU means Layer 3 and in
use, which is good.

00:48:55.970 --> 00:49:00.080
And the member ports both have the P flag,
which is also what we want.

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:08.300
Let’s quickly test by pinging CSW1: DO PING
10.0.0.41.

00:49:08.300 --> 00:49:12.619
Because the ARP process in Packet Tracer is
slow, you might see the first ping or two

00:49:12.619 --> 00:49:15.750
time out, but then the others work.

00:49:15.750 --> 00:49:18.369
And if you ping a second time, they all work.

00:49:18.369 --> 00:49:21.609
Okay, that’s all for step 3.

00:49:21.609 --> 00:49:27.020
Next, let’s look at steps 4 and 5 together,
which involve configuring the appropriate

00:49:27.020 --> 00:49:31.140
interfaces on CSW1 and CSW2.

00:49:31.140 --> 00:49:35.980
We just configured the EtherChannel that connects
them, and now we have to configure their other

00:49:35.980 --> 00:49:39.170
interfaces, which should all be routed ports.

00:49:39.170 --> 00:49:50.040
Their G1/0/1 interfaces connect to R1: CSW1
G1/0/1 is 10.0.0.34/30 and CSW2 is .38.

00:49:50.040 --> 00:49:57.330
Then, their G1/1/1, 2, 3, and 4 interfaces
each connect to the distribution switches.

00:49:57.330 --> 00:50:01.250
Then, configure a loopback interface on each
of them.

00:50:01.250 --> 00:50:05.869
Finally, notice that it also says to disable
all unused interfaces.

00:50:05.869 --> 00:50:08.920
Remember that as a security best practice.

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:11.960
So, you can see all of the IP addresses here.

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:16.780
I don’t think you need to see me configuring
these IP addresses one by one, so let’s

00:50:16.780 --> 00:50:20.680
look at the commands in the notepad and then
I’ll just copy and paste them.

00:50:20.680 --> 00:50:26.119
So, here we are, part 3 step 4, CSW1.

00:50:26.119 --> 00:50:31.040
On each of its physical interfaces, I’ll
first use NO SWITCHPORT to make it a routed

00:50:31.040 --> 00:50:34.500
port, and then just configure the IP address.

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:40.680
Then I’ll configure loopback0, and disable
the unused interfaces, which are G1/0/4 to

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:41.680
24.

00:50:41.680 --> 00:50:45.670
So, I’ll highlight and copy all of these
commands.

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:50.809
Then I’ll go into the CLI of CSW1, right
click, and paste them.

00:50:50.809 --> 00:50:52.700
And then EXIT.

00:50:52.700 --> 00:50:57.420
This is actually the last step that involves
CSW1 in this part of the lab, so I’ll use

00:50:57.420 --> 00:50:59.970
DO WRITE to save the configuration here.

00:50:59.970 --> 00:51:02.369
Now let’s do the same for CSW2.

00:51:02.369 --> 00:51:07.770
I’ll go back to the notepad, and scroll
down to Part 3, step 5.

00:51:07.770 --> 00:51:12.940
So, the commands for CSW2 are identical, aside
from the different IP addresses.

00:51:12.940 --> 00:51:20.690
So, let’s highlight and copy these commands,
go to the CLI of CSW2, right click, and paste

00:51:20.690 --> 00:51:22.359
them in.

00:51:22.359 --> 00:51:26.020
Then I’ll EXIT and use DO WRITE to save
the config.

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:30.480
Okay, steps 4 and 5 are complete.

00:51:30.480 --> 00:51:35.390
Now let’s do steps 6, 7, 8, and 9 together,
which involve configuring IP addresses on

00:51:35.390 --> 00:51:40.400
the distribution switches’ connections to
the core switches, as well as a loopback interface

00:51:40.400 --> 00:51:43.090
on each distribution switch.

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:48.650
Like steps 4 and 5, these steps just involve
configuring IP addresses on interfaces, so

00:51:48.650 --> 00:51:50.619
I’ll copy and paste them from my notepad.

00:51:50.619 --> 00:51:56.040
First, here’s part 3 step 6, configuring
DSW-A1.

00:51:56.040 --> 00:52:05.010
On G1/1/1 and G1/1/2, the connections to CSW1
and CSW2, we’ll configure 10.0.0.46/30 and

00:52:05.010 --> 00:52:10.730
.62/30, and then we’ll create loopback0
and configure .79/32.

00:52:10.730 --> 00:52:19.010
So, I’ll copy these commands, paste them
into DSW-A1’s CLI, and then EXIT.

00:52:19.010 --> 00:52:23.670
Then I’ll go back to the notepad for step
7, configuring DSW-A2.

00:52:23.670 --> 00:52:26.500
The commands are the same, just with different
IP addresses.

00:52:26.500 --> 00:52:34.440
So, I’ll highlight and copy these commands,
go into the CLI of DSW-A2, right click, paste,

00:52:34.440 --> 00:52:35.440
and then EXIT.

00:52:35.440 --> 00:52:44.250
Okay, back to the notepad for DSW-B1, which
is step 8, configuring .54/30, .70/30, and

00:52:44.250 --> 00:52:46.579
.81/32 on the loopback.

00:52:46.579 --> 00:52:54.369
So, highlight and copy these commands, go
into the CLI of DSW-B1, right click, paste,

00:52:54.369 --> 00:52:55.950
and then EXIT.

00:52:55.950 --> 00:53:00.370
And finally go back to the notepad for step
9, configuring DSW-B2.

00:53:00.370 --> 00:53:07.950
I’ll highlight and copy these commands,
go to the CLI of DSW-B2, right click, paste,

00:53:07.950 --> 00:53:09.270
and then EXIT.

00:53:09.270 --> 00:53:15.190
Okay, steps 6, 7, 8, and 9 are done; we’ve
configured IP addresses on the distribution

00:53:15.190 --> 00:53:17.690
switches’ physical and loopback interfaces.

00:53:17.690 --> 00:53:21.260
Step 10 is a bit different.

00:53:21.260 --> 00:53:26.520
Instead of configuring IP addresses in the
IOS CLI, we’ll configure SRV1’s IP settings

00:53:26.520 --> 00:53:35.940
in the Packet Tracer GUI: default gateway
10.5.0.1, IPv4 address 10.5.0.4, with a /24

00:53:35.940 --> 00:53:36.950
subnet mask.

00:53:36.950 --> 00:53:41.450
So, after clicking on SRV1 go to the Config
tab.

00:53:41.450 --> 00:53:47.060
Here, we can configure SRV1’s IPv4 default
gateway: 10.5.0.1.

00:53:47.060 --> 00:53:55.140
Then, on the left click on FastEthernet0,
and then IPv4 address 10.5.0.4.

00:53:55.140 --> 00:53:59.910
It uses a /8 subnet mask by default because
it’s a Class A address, but change that

00:53:59.910 --> 00:54:01.040
to /24.

00:54:01.040 --> 00:54:07.610
Okay, we’ve configured SRV1’s IP settings,
so that’s all for step 10.

00:54:07.610 --> 00:54:12.490
Step 11 says to configure the following management
IP addresses on the access switches, using

00:54:12.490 --> 00:54:18.200
the VLAN 99 interface, and configure the appropriate
subnet’s first usable address as the default

00:54:18.200 --> 00:54:19.200
gateway.

00:54:19.200 --> 00:54:24.150
So, these access switches are layer 2 switches,
but we want to be able to connect to them

00:54:24.150 --> 00:54:29.470
remotely for configuration via SSH, so we
need to configure an IP address and default

00:54:29.470 --> 00:54:31.140
gateway on each of them.

00:54:31.140 --> 00:54:38.670
ASW-A1, A2, and A3 have IP addresses in the
10.0.0.0/28 subnet, so we’ll configure the

00:54:38.670 --> 00:54:43.070
first usable address of that subnet – .1
– as their default gateway.

00:54:43.070 --> 00:54:51.880
ASW-B1, B2, and B3 have IP addresses in the
10.0.0.16/28 subnet, so we’ll configure

00:54:51.880 --> 00:54:54.059
.17 as their default gateway.

00:54:54.059 --> 00:54:58.490
Let’s start in Office A with ASW-A1.

00:54:58.490 --> 00:55:03.850
To configure a layer-2 switch’s default
gateway, use IP DEFAULT-GATEWAY, and then

00:55:03.850 --> 00:55:07.480
the IP address, 10.0.0.1.

00:55:07.480 --> 00:55:11.190
Now let’s configure the VLAN 99 SVI.

00:55:11.190 --> 00:55:12.950
INTERFACE VLAN 99.

00:55:12.950 --> 00:55:21.010
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.4, and the prefix length
is /28, so 255.255.255.240.

00:55:21.010 --> 00:55:23.590
EXIT.

00:55:23.590 --> 00:55:27.980
This is the last step involving these access
switches in this part of the lab, so I’ll

00:55:27.980 --> 00:55:30.170
use DO WRITE to save the config.

00:55:30.170 --> 00:55:33.579
And now let’s move on to ASW-A2.

00:55:33.579 --> 00:55:38.890
Same default gateway, IP DEFAULT-GATEWAY 10.0.0.1.

00:55:38.890 --> 00:55:40.530
INTERFACE VLAN 99.

00:55:40.530 --> 00:55:46.450
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.5 and a /28 netmask.

00:55:46.450 --> 00:55:47.450
EXIT.

00:55:47.450 --> 00:55:49.670
And save the config with DO WRITE.

00:55:49.670 --> 00:55:52.619
And then the same on ASW-A3.

00:55:52.619 --> 00:55:57.330
IP DEFAULT-GATEWAY 10.0.0.1.

00:55:57.330 --> 00:55:59.030
INTERFACE VLAN 99.

00:55:59.030 --> 00:56:03.040
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.6 /28.

00:56:03.040 --> 00:56:04.619
EXIT.

00:56:04.619 --> 00:56:06.940
DO WRITE.

00:56:06.940 --> 00:56:13.660
Office A is done, let’s move on to Office
B, configuring the 10.0.0.16/28 subnet for

00:56:13.660 --> 00:56:21.320
management, with .20 for ASW-B1, .21 for B2,
and .22 for B3.

00:56:21.320 --> 00:56:24.000
ASW-B1 first.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:28.020
IP DEFAULT-GATEWAY 10.0.0.17.

00:56:28.020 --> 00:56:29.980
INTERFACE VLAN 99.

00:56:29.980 --> 00:56:34.160
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.20 /28.

00:56:34.160 --> 00:56:35.750
EXIT.

00:56:35.750 --> 00:56:37.260
DO WRITE.

00:56:37.260 --> 00:56:39.770
ASW-B2 next.

00:56:39.770 --> 00:56:43.530
IP DEFAULT-GATEWAY 10.0.0.17.

00:56:43.530 --> 00:56:45.220
INTERFACE VLAN99.

00:56:45.220 --> 00:56:49.750
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.21 /28.

00:56:49.750 --> 00:56:51.340
EXIT.

00:56:51.340 --> 00:56:52.660
DO WRITE.

00:56:52.660 --> 00:56:55.460
And finally, ASW-B3.

00:56:55.460 --> 00:56:59.390
IP DEFAULT-GATEWAY 10.0.0.17.

00:56:59.390 --> 00:57:01.299
INTERFACE VLAN 99.

00:57:01.299 --> 00:57:05.450
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.22 /28.

00:57:05.450 --> 00:57:07.089
EXIT.

00:57:07.089 --> 00:57:08.119
DO WRITE.

00:57:08.119 --> 00:57:12.690
Okay, we’ve configured a management IP address
on each access switch.

00:57:12.690 --> 00:57:15.000
That’s all for step 11.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:21.080
In the remaining steps for this part, steps
12 to 19, we will be configuring HSRP on each

00:57:21.080 --> 00:57:23.340
office’s distribution switches.

00:57:23.340 --> 00:57:27.420
We need to configure HSRP for 4 subnets in
each office.

00:57:27.420 --> 00:57:33.500
In Office A, we need HSRP for the management
subnet, the PCs subnet, the Phones subnet,

00:57:33.500 --> 00:57:35.470
and the Wi-Fi subnet.

00:57:35.470 --> 00:57:40.559
In Office B, we need HSRP for the management
subnet, the PCs subnet, the Phones subnet,

00:57:40.559 --> 00:57:42.160
and the Servers subnet.

00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:48.350
I’ll demonstrate the complete configuration
for DSW-A1 and A2 in Office A, but for the

00:57:48.350 --> 00:57:52.910
sake of time I’ll just copy and paste the
configurations for Office B.

00:57:52.910 --> 00:58:00.610
So, steps 12 to 15 focus on Office A. Step
12 says to configure HSRP version 2 group

00:58:00.610 --> 00:58:05.180
1 for office A’s management subnet, which
is VLAN 99.

00:58:05.180 --> 00:58:11.869
We should make DSW-A1 the active router by
increasing its priority to 5 above the default.

00:58:11.869 --> 00:58:15.650
The default is 100, so we should make it 105.

00:58:15.650 --> 00:58:19.760
And then, enable preemption on DSW-A1, the
active router.

00:58:19.760 --> 00:58:28.940
The subnet is 10.0.0.0/28, with .1 as the
virtual IP, .2 for DSW-A1, and .3 for A2.

00:58:28.940 --> 00:58:33.500
So, let’s configure that on DSW-A1 first.

00:58:33.500 --> 00:58:37.839
These distribution switches will be the default
gateway for hosts in each subnet, and they

00:58:37.839 --> 00:58:40.480
will use HSRP to provide redundancy.

00:58:40.480 --> 00:58:45.510
Okay, so on DSW-A1 configure INTERFACE VLAN
99.

00:58:45.510 --> 00:58:54.799
First, I’ll configure DSW-A1’s own IP:
IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.2 with a /28 netmask.

00:58:54.799 --> 00:59:00.200
Then I’ll enable HSRP version 2 with STANDBY
VERSION 2.

00:59:00.200 --> 00:59:06.369
Next I’ll configure the VIP with STANDBY
1 IP 10.0.0.1.

00:59:06.369 --> 00:59:12.180
Now let’s ensure that DSW-A1 becomes the
Active router by increasing the priority to

00:59:12.180 --> 00:59:16.150
105: STANDBY 1 PRIORITY 105.

00:59:16.150 --> 00:59:21.220
Finally, let’s enable preemption so this
switch will always be the active switch as

00:59:21.220 --> 00:59:23.840
long as it is up and running.

00:59:23.840 --> 00:59:26.140
STANDBY 1 PREEMPT.

00:59:26.140 --> 00:59:32.420
Next let’s configure DSW-A2’s side of
the management subnet.

00:59:32.420 --> 00:59:34.450
INTERFACE VLAN 99.

00:59:34.450 --> 00:59:42.140
DSW-A2’s IP is IP ADDRESS 10.0.0.3 and a
/28 netmask.

00:59:42.140 --> 00:59:47.220
Then, enable HSRPv2 with STANDBY VERSION 2.

00:59:47.220 --> 00:59:52.549
And finally, configure the VIP with STANDBY
1 IP 10.0.0.1.

00:59:52.549 --> 00:59:56.470
That’s all we have to configure on DSW-A2.

00:59:56.470 --> 01:00:01.890
We can leave it at the default priority since
we already raised DSW-A1’s priority.

01:00:01.890 --> 01:00:05.630
And there’s no need to configure preemption
on the standby router, although you can use

01:00:05.630 --> 01:00:08.819
the command if you want to – it won’t
do any harm.

01:00:08.819 --> 01:00:12.970
So, we’ve configured HSRP for the management
subnet.

01:00:12.970 --> 01:00:19.270
Next, let’s move on to step 13, in which
we’ll configure HSRPv2 for the PCs subnet.

01:00:19.270 --> 01:00:22.760
Once again, DSW-A1 should be the active router.

01:00:22.760 --> 01:00:27.490
However, notice that it says to configure
group 2, instead of group 1.

01:00:27.490 --> 01:00:31.789
The configurations will be nearly identical,
but we will use a different group number and

01:00:31.789 --> 01:00:42.000
different IP addresses: the subnet is 10.1.0.0/24,
with .1 as the VIP, .2 for DSW-A1, and .3

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:43.000
for A2.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:46.890
Let’s start with DSW-A1.

01:00:46.890 --> 01:00:48.569
INTERFACE VLAN 10.

01:00:48.569 --> 01:00:56.599
First, configure the interface’s IP with
IP ADDRESS 10.1.0.2 255.255.255.0.

01:00:56.599 --> 01:01:03.000
Then, enable HSRPv2 with STANDBY VERSION 2.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:08.280
Then I’ll configure the VIP with STANDBY
2 IP 10.1.0.1.

01:01:08.280 --> 01:01:10.380
Make sure to use the correct group number
here.

01:01:10.380 --> 01:01:16.440
Then, I’ll raise the priority with STANDBY
2 PRIORITY 105.

01:01:16.440 --> 01:01:19.470
And finally STANDBY 2 PREEMPT.

01:01:19.470 --> 01:01:23.930
Okay, now let’s configure DSW-A2’s side.

01:01:23.930 --> 01:01:25.490
INTERFACE VLAN 10.

01:01:25.490 --> 01:01:30.770
IP ADDRESS 10.1.0.3 /24.

01:01:30.770 --> 01:01:32.869
STANDBY VERSION 2.

01:01:32.869 --> 01:01:35.430
STANDBY 2 IP 10.1.0.1.

01:01:35.430 --> 01:01:39.230
Okay, that’s all for A2.

01:01:39.230 --> 01:01:45.309
Now we have two more HSRP groups to configure
for Office A in steps 14 and 15.

01:01:45.309 --> 01:01:49.940
For these two groups, we will make DSW-A2
the active router instead of A1.

01:01:49.940 --> 01:01:56.599
Let’s start with step 14, configuring HSRPv2
group 3 for the phones subnet.

01:01:56.599 --> 01:02:06.130
The subnet is 10.2.0.0/24, with .1 as the
VIP, .2 for DSW-A1, and .3 for DSW-A2.

01:02:06.130 --> 01:02:10.500
I’ll start with DSW-A2 this time.

01:02:10.500 --> 01:02:12.099
INTERFACE VLAN 20.

01:02:12.099 --> 01:02:16.789
IP ADDRESS 10.2.0.3 /24.

01:02:16.789 --> 01:02:21.589
Then enable HSRPv2, STANDBY VERSION 2.

01:02:21.589 --> 01:02:26.680
Configure the VIP: STANDBY 3 IP 10.2.0.1.

01:02:26.680 --> 01:02:32.460
And this switch should be the active router,
so STANDBY 3 PRIORITY 105.

01:02:32.460 --> 01:02:34.559
STANDBY 3 PREEMPT.

01:02:34.559 --> 01:02:38.029
And now, DSW-A1’s side.

01:02:38.029 --> 01:02:39.660
INTERFACE VLAN 20.

01:02:39.660 --> 01:02:44.700
IP ADDRESS 10.2.0.2 /24.

01:02:44.700 --> 01:02:46.880
STANDBY VERSION 2.

01:02:46.880 --> 01:02:50.520
STANDBY 3 IP 10.2.0.1.

01:02:50.520 --> 01:02:58.280
Finally, we have one more HSRP group to configure
for step 15: the Wi-Fi subnet, VLAN 40.

01:02:58.280 --> 01:03:01.760
Again, DSW-A2 should be the active router.

01:03:01.760 --> 01:03:12.059
The subnet is 10.6.0.0/24, with .1 as the
VIP, .2 for DSW-A1, and .3 for DSW-A2.

01:03:12.059 --> 01:03:14.900
And note that the HSRP group is 4.

01:03:14.900 --> 01:03:18.760
Let’s start on DSW-A2.

01:03:18.760 --> 01:03:20.560
INTERFACE VLAN 40.

01:03:20.560 --> 01:03:25.640
IP ADDRESS 10.6.0.3 /24.

01:03:25.640 --> 01:03:27.530
STANDBY VERSION 2.

01:03:27.530 --> 01:03:31.299
STANDBY 4 IP 10.6.0.1.

01:03:31.299 --> 01:03:34.260
STANDBY 4 PRIORITY 105.

01:03:34.260 --> 01:03:35.920
STANDBY 4 PREEMPT.

01:03:35.920 --> 01:03:41.010
And then let’s configure DSW-A1’s side.

01:03:41.010 --> 01:03:42.510
INTERFACE VLAN 40.

01:03:42.510 --> 01:03:47.940
IP ADDRESS 10.6.0.2 /24.

01:03:47.940 --> 01:03:49.890
STANDBY VERSION 2.

01:03:49.890 --> 01:03:52.670
STANDBY 4 IP 10.6.0.1.

01:03:52.670 --> 01:03:59.910
Okay, we’ve finished configuring HSRP in
Office A. DSW-A1 is the active router for

01:03:59.910 --> 01:04:04.980
groups 1 and 2, and DSW-A2 is the active router
for groups 3 and 4.

01:04:04.980 --> 01:04:11.700
Let me save the config with DO WRITE and EXIT
to return to global config mode.

01:04:11.700 --> 01:04:14.320
Then I’ll do the same on A2.

01:04:14.320 --> 01:04:16.130
DO WRITE.

01:04:16.130 --> 01:04:17.799
EXIT.

01:04:17.799 --> 01:04:24.391
Steps 16 to 19 are the same thing, but for
Office B. HSRPv2 group 1 is for the management

01:04:24.391 --> 01:04:26.230
subnet, VLAN 99.

01:04:26.230 --> 01:04:30.490
Group 2 is for the PCs subnet, VLAN 10.

01:04:30.490 --> 01:04:33.849
Group 3 is for the Phones subnet, VLAN 20.

01:04:33.849 --> 01:04:38.320
And Group 4 is for the Servers subnet, VLAN
30.

01:04:38.320 --> 01:04:44.410
DSW-B1 should be active for groups 1 and 2,
and DSW-B2 should be active for groups 3 and

01:04:44.410 --> 01:04:46.000
4.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:49.770
Instead of going through the configurations
one by one, I’ll just copy and paste them

01:04:49.770 --> 01:04:50.770
from my notepad.

01:04:50.770 --> 01:04:53.130
So, here we are.

01:04:53.130 --> 01:04:56.270
Part 3, steps 16 to 19.

01:04:56.270 --> 01:05:03.300
DSW-B1 will be primary for HSRP groups 1 and
2, and standby for groups 3 and 4.

01:05:03.300 --> 01:05:06.579
Let me highlight and copy these configurations.

01:05:06.579 --> 01:05:10.190
And then go into the CLI of DSW-B1.

01:05:10.190 --> 01:05:13.339
Right click, paste, EXIT.

01:05:13.339 --> 01:05:14.750
DO WRITE.

01:05:14.750 --> 01:05:19.060
And now DSW-B2, let’s look at the commands
in the notepad.

01:05:19.060 --> 01:05:25.180
So, this switch will be standby for groups
1 and 2, and active for groups 3 and 4.

01:05:25.180 --> 01:05:33.359
Let’s highlight and copy these commands,
go into the CLI of DSW-B2, right click, paste,

01:05:33.359 --> 01:05:34.359
EXIT.

01:05:34.359 --> 01:05:35.359
DO WRITE.

01:05:35.359 --> 01:05:38.210
Okay, we’re finally done with part 3.

01:05:38.210 --> 01:05:44.220
We configured IP addresses on R1 and all of
these switches, configured Layer-3 EtherChannel

01:05:44.220 --> 01:05:52.140
between CSW1 and CSW2, and configured various
HSRP groups among these distribution switches.

01:05:52.140 --> 01:05:56.240
Now I’ll click Next to move on to part 4.

01:05:56.240 --> 01:05:59.490
Part 4 is all about Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol.

01:05:59.490 --> 01:06:01.640
This part shouldn’t take so long.

01:06:01.640 --> 01:06:07.240
In step 1, we’ll configure Rapid PVST+ on
the access and distribution switches, and

01:06:07.240 --> 01:06:12.109
then in step 2 we’ll enable PortFast and
BPDU Guard on the appropriate ports.

01:06:12.109 --> 01:06:15.750
So, let’s get right into it with step 1.

01:06:15.750 --> 01:06:21.490
First of all, we should enable Rapid PVST+
on the distribution and access switches.

01:06:21.490 --> 01:06:27.640
By default, these switches in Packet Tracer
run standard PVST+, not the Rapid version.

01:06:27.640 --> 01:06:33.859
To prove that, I’ll go on DSW-A1 and use
DO SHOW SPANNING-TREE.

01:06:33.859 --> 01:06:38.420
Notice that it says ‘Spanning tree enabled
protocol ieee’.

01:06:38.420 --> 01:06:42.631
Note that this doesn’t mean it’s running
IEEE-standard Spanning Tree Protocol; this

01:06:42.631 --> 01:06:48.260
means it is running Cisco’s Per-VLAN Spanning
Tree Plus, PVST+.

01:06:48.260 --> 01:06:55.859
To change it to Rapid PVST+, the command is
SPANNING-TREE MODE RAPID-PVST.

01:06:55.859 --> 01:06:59.400
And let’s double check with DO SHOW SPANNING-TREE
again.

01:06:59.400 --> 01:07:05.250
Okay, now it says ‘rstp’, meaning Rapid
PVST+ is enabled.

01:07:05.250 --> 01:07:10.869
Okay, let me highlight the SPANNING-TREE MODE
RAPID-PVST command and copy it.

01:07:10.869 --> 01:07:15.569
Now I’ll quickly go on to the other switches
and paste it in.

01:07:15.569 --> 01:07:17.950
DSW-A2 first.

01:07:17.950 --> 01:07:20.410
Right click, paste.

01:07:20.410 --> 01:07:21.760
Then DSW-B1.

01:07:21.760 --> 01:07:25.070
Right click, paste.

01:07:25.070 --> 01:07:27.849
And DSW-B2.

01:07:27.849 --> 01:07:30.200
Right click, paste.

01:07:30.200 --> 01:07:32.480
Then the access switches.

01:07:32.480 --> 01:07:34.200
ASW-A1.

01:07:34.200 --> 01:07:36.089
Right click, paste.

01:07:36.089 --> 01:07:37.750
And A2.

01:07:37.750 --> 01:07:39.410
Right click, paste.

01:07:39.410 --> 01:07:41.020
And A3.

01:07:41.020 --> 01:07:42.890
Right click, paste.

01:07:42.890 --> 01:07:44.869
Then ASW-B1.

01:07:44.869 --> 01:07:46.980
Right click, paste.

01:07:46.980 --> 01:07:49.099
Then ASW-B2.

01:07:49.099 --> 01:07:50.559
Right click, paste.

01:07:50.559 --> 01:07:52.569
And finally, ASW-B3.

01:07:52.569 --> 01:07:54.029
Right click, and paste.

01:07:54.029 --> 01:08:01.240
Okay, now all of these switches are running
Rapid PVST+, instead of the classic PVST+.

01:08:01.240 --> 01:08:04.190
Now let’s look at the sub steps of step
1.

01:08:04.190 --> 01:08:10.039
1a says to ensure that the Root Bridge for
each VLAN aligns with the HSRP active router

01:08:10.039 --> 01:08:13.030
by configuring the lowest possible STP priority.

01:08:13.030 --> 01:08:15.600
So, that means a priority of 0.

01:08:15.600 --> 01:08:22.580
So, in Office A, DSW-A1 should be the root
for the Management VLAN, which is VLAN 99,

01:08:22.580 --> 01:08:25.850
and the PCs VLAN, which is VLAN 10.

01:08:25.850 --> 01:08:33.359
And DSW-A2 should be the root for the Phones
VLAN, VLAN 20, and the Wi-Fi VLAN, VLAN 40.

01:08:33.359 --> 01:08:38.270
The same applies for Office B, with the Servers
VLAN replacing the Wi-Fi VLAN.

01:08:38.270 --> 01:08:44.940
Okay, and then B says to configure the HSRP
standby router for each VLAN with an STP priority

01:08:44.940 --> 01:08:47.560
one increment above the lowest priority.

01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:49.989
So, the lowest priority is 0.

01:08:49.989 --> 01:08:52.470
What’s one increment above that?

01:08:52.470 --> 01:09:00.719
Well, STP priority is configured in increments
of 4096, so one increment above 0 is 4096.

01:09:00.719 --> 01:09:05.589
Let’s configure that on each distribution
switch, starting with DSW-A1.

01:09:05.589 --> 01:09:15.299
So, first I’ll set its priority to 0 for
VLANs 10 and 99 with SPANNING-TREE VLAN 10,99

01:09:15.299 --> 01:09:16.299
PRIORITY 0.

01:09:16.299 --> 01:09:21.850
You can also do it in two separate commands
– one for VLAN 10 and one for VLAN 99 – the

01:09:21.850 --> 01:09:24.040
effect is the same.

01:09:24.040 --> 01:09:28.380
Let me double check that it’s the root bridge
now – VLAN 10 first.

01:09:28.380 --> 01:09:31.100
DO SHOW SPANNING-TREE VLAN 10.

01:09:31.100 --> 01:09:34.420
Okay, it says ‘this bridge is the root’.

01:09:34.420 --> 01:09:36.659
And then for VLAN 99.

01:09:36.659 --> 01:09:39.420
DO SHOW SPANNING-TREE VLAN 99.

01:09:39.420 --> 01:09:41.549
Okay, same for this VLAN.

01:09:41.549 --> 01:09:48.080
Then, I’ll set its priority to 4096 for
VLANs 20 and 40 – the phones VLAN and the

01:09:48.080 --> 01:09:50.140
Wi-Fi VLAN.

01:09:50.140 --> 01:09:54.640
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 20,40 PRIORITY 4096.

01:09:54.640 --> 01:10:00.150
Okay, that’s all for this switch in this
part of the lab, so I’ll use DO WRITE to

01:10:00.150 --> 01:10:02.520
save the config.

01:10:02.520 --> 01:10:04.449
Now let’s configure DSW-A2.

01:10:04.449 --> 01:10:09.510
First, I’ll set its priority to 0 for VLANs
20 and 40.

01:10:09.510 --> 01:10:12.950
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 20,40 PRIORITY 0.

01:10:12.950 --> 01:10:18.810
Next, let’s set it to 4096 for VLANs 10
and 99.

01:10:18.810 --> 01:10:24.460
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 10,99 PRIORITY 4096.

01:10:24.460 --> 01:10:28.159
And save the config with DO WRITE.

01:10:28.159 --> 01:10:33.739
Now let’s do the same thing in Office B.
First, I’ll set DSW-B1’s priority to 0

01:10:33.739 --> 01:10:39.080
for the PCs VLAN and the Management VLAN – VLANs
10 and 99.

01:10:39.080 --> 01:10:44.030
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 10,99 PRIORITY 0.

01:10:44.030 --> 01:10:51.850
And then set it to 4096 for the Phones VLAN
and the Servers VLAN – VLANs 20 and 30.

01:10:51.850 --> 01:10:54.820
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 20,30 PRIORITY 4096.

01:10:54.820 --> 01:10:59.860
And let’s save the config with DO WRITE.

01:10:59.860 --> 01:11:01.179
And finally, DSW-B2.

01:11:01.179 --> 01:11:07.170
First, I’ll set the priority to 0 for VLANS
20 and 30.

01:11:07.170 --> 01:11:10.490
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 20,30 PRIORITY 0.

01:11:10.490 --> 01:11:15.890
And then to 4096 for VLANs 10 and 99.

01:11:15.890 --> 01:11:20.480
SPANNING-TREE VLAN 10,99 PRIORITY 4096.

01:11:20.480 --> 01:11:24.219
And then save the config with DO WRITE.

01:11:24.219 --> 01:11:28.910
Now let’s do step 2, which says to enable
PortFast and BPDU Guard on all ports connected

01:11:28.910 --> 01:11:32.120
to end hosts, including WLC1.

01:11:32.120 --> 01:11:34.800
Perform the configurations in interface config
mode.

01:11:34.800 --> 01:11:41.140
Okay, so PortFast allows ports connected to
end hosts to immediately move to the STP Forwarding

01:11:41.140 --> 01:11:46.219
state, without having to wait 30 seconds to
transition through listening and learning.

01:11:46.219 --> 01:11:50.160
You should generally configure it on ports
connected to end hosts so they don’t have

01:11:50.160 --> 01:11:54.180
to wait to access the network after physically
connecting to the switch.

01:11:54.180 --> 01:11:59.850
BPDU Guard, on the other hand, is used to
disable a port if it receives a spanning tree

01:11:59.850 --> 01:12:00.850
BPDU.

01:12:00.850 --> 01:12:05.470
You should configure it on ports connected
to end hosts to prevent users from connecting

01:12:05.470 --> 01:12:07.960
an unauthorized switch to the network.

01:12:07.960 --> 01:12:10.310
So, I’ll start on ASW-A1.

01:12:10.310 --> 01:12:18.660
First, I’ll configure PortFast and BPDU
Guard on F0/1, which is connected to LWAP1.

01:12:18.660 --> 01:12:20.639
INTERFACE F0/1.

01:12:20.639 --> 01:12:22.830
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST.

01:12:22.830 --> 01:12:25.389
SPANNING-TREE BPDUGUARD ENABLE.

01:12:25.389 --> 01:12:29.880
And now F0/2, which is connected to WLC1.

01:12:29.880 --> 01:12:30.880
INTERFACE F0/2.

01:12:30.880 --> 01:12:31.930
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST.

01:12:31.930 --> 01:12:35.679
Let’s pause for a second here.

01:12:35.679 --> 01:12:38.219
Notice the second warning message.

01:12:38.219 --> 01:12:42.730
Portfast has been configured on F0/2 but will
only have effect when the interface is in

01:12:42.730 --> 01:12:44.260
a non-trunking mode.

01:12:44.260 --> 01:12:50.380
That’s a problem: F0/2 is a trunk port,
because it’s connected to WLC1 and needs

01:12:50.380 --> 01:12:53.139
to support the Management and Wi-Fi VLANs.

01:12:53.139 --> 01:12:54.730
Here’s the solution.

01:12:54.730 --> 01:13:00.389
I’ll use the up arrow to go back to the
command, and then use the question mark.

01:13:00.389 --> 01:13:02.500
Notice the TRUNK option.

01:13:02.500 --> 01:13:07.620
As the description says, this will enable
portfast on the interface even in trunk mode.

01:13:07.620 --> 01:13:11.330
Okay, so SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST TRUNK.

01:13:11.330 --> 01:13:12.610
There we go.

01:13:12.610 --> 01:13:15.580
And now I’ll enable BPDU Guard.

01:13:15.580 --> 01:13:17.770
SPANNING-TREE BPDUGUARD ENABLE.

01:13:17.770 --> 01:13:18.770
EXIT.

01:13:18.770 --> 01:13:20.860
And save the config with DO WRITE.

01:13:20.860 --> 01:13:24.840
Okay, so we’re done with ASW-A1.

01:13:24.840 --> 01:13:27.739
It was a special case because of that trunk
port.

01:13:27.739 --> 01:13:32.510
The other access switches only have one host
connected and require the same commands to

01:13:32.510 --> 01:13:37.820
enable PortFast and BPDU Guard, so I’ll
return to my notepad.

01:13:37.820 --> 01:13:39.360
Here are the commands.

01:13:39.360 --> 01:13:41.040
INTERFACE F0/1.

01:13:41.040 --> 01:13:42.620
SPANNING-TREE PORTFAST.

01:13:42.620 --> 01:13:44.290
SPANNING-TREE BPDUGUARD ENABLE.

01:13:44.290 --> 01:13:50.020
So, I’ll copy these commands, and let’s
paste them into ASW-A2.

01:13:50.020 --> 01:13:53.239
Right click, paste, EXIT.

01:13:53.239 --> 01:13:55.840
And save with DO WRITE.

01:13:55.840 --> 01:13:57.969
Then ASW-A3.

01:13:57.969 --> 01:14:02.320
Right click, paste, EXIT, DO WRITE.

01:14:02.320 --> 01:14:04.969
And ASW-B1.

01:14:04.969 --> 01:14:09.860
Right click, paste, EXIT, DO WRITE.

01:14:09.860 --> 01:14:10.860
Then B2.

01:14:10.860 --> 01:14:15.050
Right click, paste, EXIT, DO WRITE.

01:14:15.050 --> 01:14:18.270
And finally, ASW-B3.

01:14:18.270 --> 01:14:21.400
Right click, paste, EXIT, DO WRITE.

01:14:21.400 --> 01:14:24.960
Okay, that’s all for part 4 of this lab.

01:14:24.960 --> 01:14:30.780
We enabled Rapid PVST+ on the distribution
and access switches, modified the priority

01:14:30.780 --> 01:14:36.389
values of the distribution switches for each
VLAN to align with the HSRP active and standby

01:14:36.389 --> 01:14:41.920
routers, and then configured PortFast and
BPDU Guard on the access switches.

01:14:41.920 --> 01:14:46.210
Now I’ll click Next to go to part 5.

01:14:46.210 --> 01:14:50.000
This part of the lab is all about static and
dynamic routing.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:55.390
In step 1, we’ll configure OSPF on R1 and
the core and distribution switches.

01:14:55.390 --> 01:15:00.940
Then, in step 2 we’ll configure default
routes on R1 for its Internet connections,

01:15:00.940 --> 01:15:06.540
and then make R1 an ASBR that advertises its
default route to other routers in the OSPF

01:15:06.540 --> 01:15:07.540
domain.

01:15:07.540 --> 01:15:10.020
So, let’s get started with step 1.

01:15:10.020 --> 01:15:17.070
Step 1 says to configure OSPF on R1’s LAN-facing
interfaces, so these two connected to CSW1

01:15:17.070 --> 01:15:23.150
and 2, and all Core and Distribution switches,
specifically on all Layer-3 interfaces.

01:15:23.150 --> 01:15:28.489
Now, there are a lot of specific instructions
below, so before jumping into the configurations

01:15:28.489 --> 01:15:31.370
it’s important to read all of these.

01:15:31.370 --> 01:15:35.380
A says to use process ID 1 and Area 0.

01:15:35.380 --> 01:15:40.270
B Says to manually configure each device’s
router ID to match the loopback interface

01:15:40.270 --> 01:15:41.270
IP.

01:15:41.270 --> 01:15:49.590
So, R1’s loopback is 10.0.0.76, CSW1’s
is .77, CSW2’s is .78, etc.

01:15:49.590 --> 01:15:55.179
Okay, then C says that, on switches, you should
use the NETWORK command to match the exact

01:15:55.179 --> 01:15:57.430
IP address of each interface.

01:15:57.430 --> 01:16:04.070
In other words, use the NETWORK command with
a /32 wildcard mask, which is 0.0.0.0, to

01:16:04.070 --> 01:16:06.969
enable OSPF on each interface.

01:16:06.969 --> 01:16:11.800
Then D says that you should enable OSPF in
interface config mode on R1.

01:16:11.800 --> 01:16:17.940
You can do that with the IP OSPF 1 AREA 0
command on each interface.

01:16:17.940 --> 01:16:23.679
Moving on to E, it says to make sure OSPF
is enabled on all loopback interfaces, too.

01:16:23.679 --> 01:16:26.270
And they should be passive interfaces.

01:16:26.270 --> 01:16:31.510
And F says that each distribution switch’s
SVIs, except the management VLAN SVI, should

01:16:31.510 --> 01:16:32.969
be passive too.

01:16:32.969 --> 01:16:39.659
So, by default, after enabling OSPF on the
distribution switch SVIs, they will send OSPF

01:16:39.659 --> 01:16:43.150
hello messages out of their SVIs to the LANs.

01:16:43.150 --> 01:16:46.280
And they will receive each other’s Hellos
and become OSPF neighbors.

01:16:46.280 --> 01:16:51.600
However, we don’t need them to become neighbors
four times – once for each VLAN.

01:16:51.600 --> 01:16:56.889
We’ll make all SVIs except the Management
SVI passive, so they will only send hellos

01:16:56.889 --> 01:16:58.800
out of the Management SVI.

01:16:58.800 --> 01:17:04.510
Finally, G says to configure all physical
connections between OSPF neighbors to use

01:17:04.510 --> 01:17:07.679
a network type that doesn’t elect a DR and
BDR.

01:17:07.679 --> 01:17:13.679
In other words, you should configure the point-to-point
network type on the interfaces.

01:17:13.679 --> 01:17:18.429
Note that, in packet tracer, the necessary
command isn’t available on the Layer-3 PortChannel

01:17:18.429 --> 01:17:21.230
interface between CSW1 and CSW2.

01:17:21.230 --> 01:17:24.780
So, we’ll leave this link as the default
network type.

01:17:24.780 --> 01:17:27.949
Okay, so we have a lot of configurations to
do.

01:17:27.949 --> 01:17:32.570
I’ll configure the first couple of devices
one command at a time in the CLI to walk you

01:17:32.570 --> 01:17:36.489
through the process, but after that I’ll
just copy and paste the commands.

01:17:36.489 --> 01:17:40.449
So, let’s open the CLI of R1 and get started.

01:17:40.449 --> 01:17:45.130
First, I’ll create the OSPF process with
ROUTER OSPF 1.

01:17:45.130 --> 01:17:48.320
Now, let’s specify R1’s router ID.

01:17:48.320 --> 01:17:54.429
Actually, if I check the current router ID
with DO SHOW IP OSPF, you can see that the

01:17:54.429 --> 01:17:59.520
ID is 10.0.0.76 – the IP address of its
loopback interface.

01:17:59.520 --> 01:18:05.710
However, step 1b said to manually configure
each device’s router ID, so I will do that

01:18:05.710 --> 01:18:09.300
with ROUTER-ID 10.0.0.76.

01:18:09.300 --> 01:18:17.320
Okay, there is only one more command to configure
in this mode, which is PASSIVE-INTERFACE LOOPBACK0.

01:18:17.320 --> 01:18:22.100
We haven’t enabled OSPF on loopback0 yet,
but let’s do that next.

01:18:22.100 --> 01:18:27.860
The instructions said to activate OSPF in
interface config mode on R1, so INTERFACE

01:18:27.860 --> 01:18:29.510
LOOPBACK0.

01:18:29.510 --> 01:18:34.620
And then activate OSPF with IP OSPF 1 AREA
0.

01:18:34.620 --> 01:18:41.840
And now we just have to activate OSPF on R1’s
two LAN-facing interfaces, connected to CSW1

01:18:41.840 --> 01:18:42.840
and CSW2.

01:18:42.840 --> 01:18:49.010
Those are G0/0 and 0/1, so INTERFACE RANGE
G0/0-1.

01:18:49.010 --> 01:18:50.540
Let’s activate OSPF.

01:18:50.540 --> 01:18:55.460
IP OSPF 1 AREA 0.

01:18:55.460 --> 01:18:58.530
And then also configure the point-to-point
network type.

01:18:58.530 --> 01:19:01.190
IP OSPF NETWORK POINT-TO-POINT.

01:19:01.190 --> 01:19:04.310
Okay that’s all for R1.

01:19:04.310 --> 01:19:10.170
We configured its router ID, made its loopback
interface passive, activated OSPF on the appropriate

01:19:10.170 --> 01:19:14.000
interfaces, and configured the point-to-point
network type.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:17.070
Next, I’ll go on CSW1.

01:19:17.070 --> 01:19:22.850
First, create the OSPF process with ROUTER
OSPF 1.

01:19:22.850 --> 01:19:28.449
And like on R1, I’ll first configure the
router ID with ROUTER-ID 10.0.0.77 – the

01:19:28.449 --> 01:19:32.330
IP address of its loopback interface.

01:19:32.330 --> 01:19:37.280
And let’s make the loopback passive: PASSIVE-INTERFACE
LOOPBACK0.

01:19:37.280 --> 01:19:43.210
Now, for the switches, the instructions say
to activate OSPF using the NETWORK command

01:19:43.210 --> 01:19:45.650
with a /32 wildcard mask.

01:19:45.650 --> 01:19:50.380
So, let’s see the IP addresses of CSW1’s
interfaces.

01:19:50.380 --> 01:19:55.980
If I use DO SHOW IP INTERFACE BRIEF like this,
the output is full of these interfaces without

01:19:55.980 --> 01:19:57.980
any IP address.

01:19:57.980 --> 01:20:03.550
To filter out these interfaces from the output,
let me add a pipe to the end of the command,

01:20:03.550 --> 01:20:09.040
EXCLUDE, and then ‘un’ to filter any lines
that include ‘unassigned’.

01:20:09.040 --> 01:20:13.430
There we go; now we can only see the interfaces
that have an IP address.

01:20:13.430 --> 01:20:19.800
So, let’s activate OSPF on these interfaces
in order, starting with port-channel 1.

01:20:19.800 --> 01:20:25.700
NETWORK 10.0.0.41 0.0.0.0 AREA 0.

01:20:25.700 --> 01:20:31.100
And now I can simply hit the up arrow to return
to that command, and then change the IP address

01:20:31.100 --> 01:20:34.630
to .34 for the G1/0/1 interface.

01:20:34.630 --> 01:20:40.580
And then up arrow again, change it to .45
for G1/1/1.

01:20:40.580 --> 01:20:44.860
Up arrow again, .49 for G1/1/2.

01:20:44.860 --> 01:20:47.360
Then again for G1/1/3, .53.

01:20:47.360 --> 01:20:54.139
Up arrow again, change it to .57 for G1/1/4.

01:20:54.139 --> 01:20:58.150
And one more time, change it to .77 for loopback0.

01:20:58.150 --> 01:21:03.460
Okay, we’ve activated OSPF on all of CSW1’s
interfaces.

01:21:03.460 --> 01:21:07.950
But there’s one more thing to configure
on CSW1: we need to configure the point-to-point

01:21:07.950 --> 01:21:14.610
network type on its physical ports: G1/0/1,
and G1/1/1, 2, 3, and 4.

01:21:14.610 --> 01:21:21.739
So, INTERFACE RANGE G1/0/1, a comma, and then
G1/1/1-4.

01:21:21.739 --> 01:21:25.679
And configure the network type with IP OSPF
NETWORK POINT-TO-POINT.

01:21:25.679 --> 01:21:28.630
Okay, that’s all for CSW1.

01:21:28.630 --> 01:21:34.489
Finally, I’ll EXIT and use DO WRITE to save
the config.

01:21:34.489 --> 01:21:38.550
The configurations for the rest of the switches
are similar, so I’ll just copy them from

01:21:38.550 --> 01:21:42.220
the notepad and then paste them into each
device.

01:21:42.220 --> 01:21:46.361
To repeat what I said before, when you are
doing this lab yourself, it’s important

01:21:46.361 --> 01:21:50.740
that you prepare all of these configurations
yourself – otherwise, it’s not practice.

01:21:50.740 --> 01:21:55.260
But, for the sake of the video, let’s do
this to speed things up – the video is long

01:21:55.260 --> 01:21:56.820
enough as is.

01:21:56.820 --> 01:22:02.370
So, CSW2’s configurations are identical
to CSW1’s, just with different IP addresses.

01:22:02.370 --> 01:22:10.190
So, I’ll copy them, go into the CLI of CSW2,
and paste them in.

01:22:10.190 --> 01:22:15.050
Then I’ll EXIT and save the config with
DO WRITE.

01:22:15.050 --> 01:22:18.860
Now let’s return to the notepad and look
at the commands for DSW-A1.

01:22:18.860 --> 01:22:25.739
We’ll set its router ID, make its loopback
interface passive, and also make its SVIs

01:22:25.739 --> 01:22:32.310
passive for VLANs 10, 20, and 40 – but not
for the management VLAN, VLAN 99.

01:22:32.310 --> 01:22:35.280
Then activate OSPF on each interface.

01:22:35.280 --> 01:22:40.840
And finally configure the point-to-point network
type on G1/1/1 and 1/1/2 – those are the

01:22:40.840 --> 01:22:44.110
physical links connecting to CSW1 and 2.

01:22:44.110 --> 01:22:51.219
So, I’ll highlight and copy these commands,
go to the CLI of DSW-A1, and paste them.

01:22:51.219 --> 01:22:53.790
Then, EXIT and DO WRITE.

01:22:53.790 --> 01:22:59.290
Okay, and now let’s return to the notepad
and look at DSW-A2’s configurations.

01:22:59.290 --> 01:23:03.510
These are identical to DSW-A1’s, just with
different IP addresses.

01:23:03.510 --> 01:23:10.090
So, I’ll copy them, go into the CLI of DSW-A2,
and paste them.

01:23:10.090 --> 01:23:12.090
Then EXIT and DO WRITE.

01:23:12.090 --> 01:23:16.760
Now, before moving on let’s check its OSPF
neighbors.

01:23:16.760 --> 01:23:19.159
DO SHOW IP OSPF NEIGHBOR.

01:23:19.159 --> 01:23:22.130
So, it has three neighbors.

01:23:22.130 --> 01:23:25.410
10.0.0.79 is DSW-A1.

01:23:25.410 --> 01:23:28.380
Notice that the interface is VLAN 99.

01:23:28.380 --> 01:23:35.360
If we didn’t make the VLAN 10, 20 and 40
SVIs passive, DSW-A1 and A2 would become OSPF

01:23:35.360 --> 01:23:40.920
neighbors with each other four times – once
for each SVI – that isn’t necessary.

01:23:40.920 --> 01:23:47.230
And notice that, because we made G1/1/1 and
1/1/2 point-to-point, no DR or BDR are elected

01:23:47.230 --> 01:23:54.000
for the connections with CSW1 and CSW2: 10.0.0.77
and 78 here.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:24:02.969
Okay, now let’s do the same for DSW-B1 and
B2 in Office B. So, I’ll return to the notepad.

01:24:02.969 --> 01:24:07.820
The configurations are basically identical,
with different IP addresses of course.

01:24:07.820 --> 01:24:11.530
And instead of VLAN 40, Office B has VLAN
30.

01:24:11.530 --> 01:24:12.700
But that’s it.

01:24:12.700 --> 01:24:20.610
So, I’ll copy these commands for DSW-B1,
open its CLI, and paste them.

01:24:20.610 --> 01:24:23.489
Then I’ll EXIT and DO WRITE.

01:24:23.489 --> 01:24:28.680
And finally, let’s return to the notepad
and copy the commands for DSW-B2.

01:24:28.680 --> 01:24:33.550
Once again, these commands are identical,
just with different IP addresses.

01:24:33.550 --> 01:24:39.750
Open the CLI of DSW-B2, paste the commands,
and EXIT, DO WRITE.

01:24:39.750 --> 01:24:44.000
Okay, we’re done with step 1, configuring
OSPF.

01:24:44.000 --> 01:24:46.580
Now let’s move on to step 2.

01:24:46.580 --> 01:24:51.260
It says to configure one static default route
for each of R1s Internet connections.

01:24:51.260 --> 01:24:55.719
They should be recursive routes, meaning they
should specify a next hop IP address, but

01:24:55.719 --> 01:24:58.290
not an exit interface.

01:24:58.290 --> 01:25:03.730
For review, recursive routes specify only
the next hop IP, directly connected routes

01:25:03.730 --> 01:25:09.420
specify only the exit interface, and fully
specified routes specify both.

01:25:09.420 --> 01:25:16.969
2a says to make the route via G0/1/0 a floating
static route by configuring an AD value 1

01:25:16.969 --> 01:25:22.520
greater than the default, and then B says
that R1 should function as an ASBR, advertising

01:25:22.520 --> 01:25:25.989
its default route to other routers in the
OSPF domain.

01:25:25.989 --> 01:25:29.330
Okay, let’s go back to the CLI of R1.

01:25:29.330 --> 01:25:32.909
So, R1 has two Internet connections.

01:25:32.909 --> 01:25:34.200
Let’s see.

01:25:34.200 --> 01:25:36.280
DO SHOW IP INTERFACE BRIEF.

01:25:36.280 --> 01:25:41.340
There they are: G0/0/0 and G0/1/0.

01:25:41.340 --> 01:25:44.469
Both of them have a /30 prefix length.

01:25:44.469 --> 01:25:50.480
You can confirm that with DO SHOW IP INTERFACE
G0/0/0.

01:25:50.480 --> 01:25:54.239
You can see that here in the second line,
Internet address is 203.0.113.2/30.

01:25:54.239 --> 01:26:04.860
A /30 subnet only has two usable addresses,
.1 and .2 in this case, so that means the

01:26:04.860 --> 01:26:08.340
ISP’s IP address must be 203.0.113.1.

01:26:08.340 --> 01:26:12.780
Let’s check with DO PING 203.0.113.1.

01:26:12.780 --> 01:26:17.900
Okay, so that should be the next hop IP of
one of the routes.

01:26:17.900 --> 01:26:20.150
And let’s verify the other one.

01:26:20.150 --> 01:26:23.500
DO SHOW IP INTERFACE G0/1/0.

01:26:23.500 --> 01:26:29.990
Okay, Internet address is 203.0.113.6/30.

01:26:29.990 --> 01:26:36.240
This is the .4/30 subnet, and the other usable
address is .5, which should be the ISP’s

01:26:36.240 --> 01:26:37.240
address.

01:26:37.240 --> 01:26:38.590
Let’s ping it.

01:26:38.590 --> 01:26:40.800
DO PING 203.0.113.5.

01:26:40.800 --> 01:26:43.940
Okay, it works.

01:26:43.940 --> 01:26:46.929
That should be the next hop IP of the other
default route.

01:26:46.929 --> 01:26:49.580
So, let’s configure those routes.

01:26:49.580 --> 01:26:52.290
The first one, via 203.0.113.1.

01:26:52.290 --> 01:26:59.110
IP ROUTE 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 203.0.113.1.

01:26:59.110 --> 01:27:01.940
Okay, that’s it.

01:27:01.940 --> 01:27:06.850
Now let’s configure the second one via .5
and make it a floating static route.

01:27:06.850 --> 01:27:12.450
IP ROUTE 0.0.0.0 0.0.0.0 203.0.113.5.

01:27:12.450 --> 01:27:17.969
Now, the instructions say to make the AD 1
higher than the default.

01:27:17.969 --> 01:27:22.270
What’s the default administrative distance
of a static route in Cisco IOS?

01:27:22.270 --> 01:27:25.739
It’s 1, so let’s specify 2 here.

01:27:25.739 --> 01:27:28.369
So, we configured two default routes.

01:27:28.369 --> 01:27:32.310
Let’s verify that only one is active in
the routing table.

01:27:32.310 --> 01:27:33.840
DO SHOW IP ROUTE.

01:27:33.840 --> 01:27:37.880
Look down at the bottom, and there it is.

01:27:37.880 --> 01:27:40.690
0.0.0.0/0, via 203.0.113.1.

01:27:40.690 --> 01:27:41.960
Perfect.

01:27:41.960 --> 01:27:49.940
Finally, let’s do step 2b, in which we’ll
make R1 an OSPF ASBR so it advertises its

01:27:49.940 --> 01:27:51.510
default route.

01:27:51.510 --> 01:27:56.800
To do that, go back to OSPF config mode with
ROUTER OSPF 1.

01:27:56.800 --> 01:28:00.139
And then use DEFAULT-INFORMATION ORIGINATE.

01:28:00.139 --> 01:28:01.440
And that’s it.

01:28:01.440 --> 01:28:05.050
Finally, I’ll use EXIT and DO WRITE.

01:28:05.050 --> 01:28:11.682
Now, if I go to any of the layer-3 switches,
such as DSW-B2, and use DO SHOW IP ROUTE,

01:28:11.682 --> 01:28:15.670
I should see the default route.

01:28:15.670 --> 01:28:18.830
You can see it down at the bottom of the routing
table.

01:28:18.830 --> 01:28:24.770
Notice it has two routes installed: one with
CSW1 as the next hop, and one with CSW2 as

01:28:24.770 --> 01:28:25.920
the next hop.

01:28:25.920 --> 01:28:31.020
Now, if I ping R1’s internet IP from this
switch, it should work.

01:28:31.020 --> 01:28:34.040
DO PING 203.0.113.2.

01:28:34.040 --> 01:28:37.850
Okay, the ping works.

01:28:37.850 --> 01:28:41.040
Now, what about the ISP’s IP address?

01:28:41.040 --> 01:28:42.360
Let’s try.

01:28:42.360 --> 01:28:44.790
DO PING 203.0.113.1.

01:28:44.790 --> 01:28:50.400
It gets five Us in reply, meaning ‘unreachable’.

01:28:50.400 --> 01:28:56.630
The reason for that is DSW-B2 is pinging from
a private IP address, which the ISP’s router

01:28:56.630 --> 01:28:57.630
doesn’t accept.

01:28:57.630 --> 01:29:02.260
To solve that, we need to configure NAT, network
address translation.

01:29:02.260 --> 01:29:08.780
So, let’s click Next in the lab instructions
to move on to Part 6.

01:29:08.780 --> 01:29:14.030
In part 6 of this lab, we’ll configure various
network services like DHCP, DNS, NTP, SNMP,

01:29:14.030 --> 01:29:17.580
Syslog, FTP, SSH, and NAT.

01:29:17.580 --> 01:29:23.510
We’ve got a lot of configurations to do
in this section, so let’s get started with

01:29:23.510 --> 01:29:30.120
step 1, which says to configure the following
DHCP pools on R1 to make it serve as the DHCP

01:29:30.120 --> 01:29:36.250
server for hosts in Offices A and B. Also,
we must exclude the first ten usable addresses

01:29:36.250 --> 01:29:37.490
of each pool.

01:29:37.490 --> 01:29:39.659
So, which pools do we need to configure?

01:29:39.659 --> 01:29:43.480
First, a pool for Office A’s management
subnet.

01:29:43.480 --> 01:29:46.580
LWAP1 will lease an IP address from this pool.

01:29:46.580 --> 01:29:49.170
Then, a pool for Office A’s PCs.

01:29:49.170 --> 01:29:51.960
PC1 and PC2 will use this pool.

01:29:51.960 --> 01:29:56.250
And then a pool for Office A’s phones, which
Phone1 and Phone2 will use.

01:29:56.250 --> 01:30:01.940
Then, we will configure the equivalent management,
PC, and phone pools for Office B, and finally

01:30:01.940 --> 01:30:04.310
a single pool for wireless clients.

01:30:04.310 --> 01:30:09.080
So, all of these pools will use similar commands,
just with different IP addresses.

01:30:09.080 --> 01:30:14.679
I’ll configure the first one manually, but
then copy and paste the others.

01:30:14.679 --> 01:30:18.889
But before we configure the pools, let’s
configure the excluded address ranges: the

01:30:18.889 --> 01:30:21.860
first ten addresses of each subnet.

01:30:21.860 --> 01:30:24.260
To do that, I’ll open up my notepad again.

01:30:24.260 --> 01:30:27.369
So, here’s part 6 step 1.

01:30:27.369 --> 01:30:32.520
These are the seven ranges of addresses we’ll
exclude, in the same order as the instructions.

01:30:32.520 --> 01:30:35.870
Office A’s management, PC, and phone subnets.

01:30:35.870 --> 01:30:39.360
Then Office B’s management, PC, and phone
subnets.

01:30:39.360 --> 01:30:41.480
And finally, the Wi-Fi subnet.

01:30:41.480 --> 01:30:47.730
The command is IP DHCP EXCLUDED-ADDRESS, followed
by the first address in the range, and then

01:30:47.730 --> 01:30:49.679
the last address in the range.

01:30:49.679 --> 01:30:55.489
So, these commands exclude the first 10 usable
host addresses of each subnet, so R1 won’t

01:30:55.489 --> 01:30:56.969
assign them to clients.

01:30:56.969 --> 01:31:02.340
I’ll highlight and copy these commands,
and then go into the CLI of R1, and paste

01:31:02.340 --> 01:31:04.070
them.

01:31:04.070 --> 01:31:05.850
Now let’s configure the DHCP pools.

01:31:05.850 --> 01:31:10.409
Like I said, I’ll do the first one, for
Office A’s management subnet, manually.

01:31:10.409 --> 01:31:13.280
Let’s look at the info again.

01:31:13.280 --> 01:31:21.860
The subnet is 10.0.0.0/28, and the default
gateway is 10.0.0.1, which is the HSRP VIP

01:31:21.860 --> 01:31:25.389
that we configured on DSW-A1 and A2.

01:31:25.389 --> 01:31:33.159
The domain name is jeremysitlab.com, the DNS
server is 10.5.0.4, which is SRV1, and then

01:31:33.159 --> 01:31:38.050
the WLC is 10.0.0.7, WLC1.

01:31:38.050 --> 01:31:41.650
And note that name: A-Mgmt.

01:31:41.650 --> 01:31:45.739
This has to match or it won’t be marked
correctly when you click ‘Check Results’.

01:31:45.739 --> 01:31:55.480
So, let’s go back to the CLI of R1, and
use IP DHCP POOL A-Mgmt to create the pool.

01:31:55.480 --> 01:32:05.489
Then, use NETWORK 10.0.0.0 255.255.255.240
to specify the 10.0.0.0/28 subnet.

01:32:05.489 --> 01:32:11.280
And DEFAULT-ROUTER 10.0.0.1 to specify the
default gateway.

01:32:11.280 --> 01:32:17.179
Next, configure the domain name with DOMAIN-NAME
jeremysitlab.com.

01:32:17.179 --> 01:32:23.360
And then I’ll specify SRV1 as the DNS server
with DNS-SERVER 10.5.0.4.

01:32:23.360 --> 01:32:29.300
Finally, we need to specify the WLC address
for lightweight access points.

01:32:29.300 --> 01:32:32.600
Actually, take another look at the network.

01:32:32.600 --> 01:32:39.469
In office A, when LWAP1 sends a broadcast
message to identify any WLCs in the network,

01:32:39.469 --> 01:32:42.630
WLC1 will receive that broadcast and respond.

01:32:42.630 --> 01:32:48.840
So, we technically don’t need to specify
the WLC address in this DHCP pool.

01:32:48.840 --> 01:32:53.910
However, for Office B’s management DHCP
pool, it is necessary.

01:32:53.910 --> 01:32:59.890
When LWAP2 sends a broadcast message, it won’t
reach WLC1, so we should specify WLC1’s

01:32:59.890 --> 01:33:06.719
IP address in the DHCP pool, so LWAP2 can
send a unicast message directly to WLC1 to

01:33:06.719 --> 01:33:07.739
connect.

01:33:07.739 --> 01:33:13.260
However, the lab instructions say to configure
the WLC address for this pool, so let’s

01:33:13.260 --> 01:33:14.739
go back to the CLI.

01:33:14.739 --> 01:33:18.960
I’ll use the question mark to see the available
commands.

01:33:18.960 --> 01:33:23.690
To specify a WLC address, we have to use the
OPTION keyword.

01:33:23.690 --> 01:33:26.490
After that, specify the option number.

01:33:26.490 --> 01:33:33.270
The correct number here is option 43, then
IP, and then the IP address: 10.0.0.7.

01:33:33.270 --> 01:33:38.940
So, that’s the command: OPTION 43 IP 10.0.0.7.

01:33:38.940 --> 01:33:44.880
Okay, so that’s the first pool, and the
rest will use basically the same commands,

01:33:44.880 --> 01:33:47.430
so let’s go back to the notepad.

01:33:47.430 --> 01:33:53.969
Here are the commands for the rest of the
pools: A-PC, A-Phone, B-Mgmt, B-PC, B-Phone,

01:33:53.969 --> 01:33:55.580
and Wi-Fi.

01:33:55.580 --> 01:34:02.639
I’ll highlight and copy these commands,
return to the CLI of R1, right click, and

01:34:02.639 --> 01:34:03.639
paste.

01:34:03.639 --> 01:34:04.639
And EXIT.

01:34:04.639 --> 01:34:07.310
Okay, so step 1 is done.

01:34:07.310 --> 01:34:14.470
But if I use DO SHOW IP DHCP BINDING on R1
it won’t show any DHCP leases.

01:34:14.470 --> 01:34:19.460
The reason for that is that clients’ broadcast
DHCP requests won’t reach R1.

01:34:19.460 --> 01:34:26.030
So, in step 2 we’ll configure the distribution
switches to function as DHCP relay agents,

01:34:26.030 --> 01:34:34.239
forwarding clients’ broadcast messages to
R1’s loopback0 IP address, which is 10.0.0.76.

01:34:34.239 --> 01:34:39.130
To do that, we need to use the IP HELPER-ADDRESS
command on the interfaces that receive clients’

01:34:39.130 --> 01:34:41.670
broadcast DHCP messages.

01:34:41.670 --> 01:34:45.790
In this case, those are the various SVIs on
each switch.

01:34:45.790 --> 01:34:49.670
I’ll go back to the notepad to see the commands.

01:34:49.670 --> 01:35:00.780
On DSW-A1 and A2, we’ll use IP HELPER-ADDRESS
10.0.0.76 on the VLAN 10, 20, 40, and 99 SVIs.

01:35:00.780 --> 01:35:06.980
And then on B1 and B2 it’ll be for VLANs
10, 20, 30, and 99.

01:35:06.980 --> 01:35:11.400
The thing to note here is that this command
must be configured on the correct interface:

01:35:11.400 --> 01:35:15.300
the interface that receives the broadcast
DHCP messages from clients.

01:35:15.300 --> 01:35:21.520
More specifically, the layer-3 interface:
each SVI in this case, not the physical layer

01:35:21.520 --> 01:35:23.330
2 switch port.

01:35:23.330 --> 01:35:29.960
Okay, let’s copy the commands for Office
A, then open the CLI of DSW-A1.

01:35:29.960 --> 01:35:31.640
And paste the commands in.

01:35:31.640 --> 01:35:32.640
EXIT.

01:35:32.640 --> 01:35:39.449
Okay, DSW-A2 needs the same commands, so let’s
open its CLI, and paste the commands in.

01:35:39.449 --> 01:35:40.449
EXIT.

01:35:40.449 --> 01:35:45.389
Then, I’ll return to the notepad and copy
these commands for Office B.

01:35:45.389 --> 01:35:50.090
The only difference is that it uses VLAN 30
instead of VLAN 40.

01:35:50.090 --> 01:35:52.550
Now I’ll go on to DSW-B1.

01:35:52.550 --> 01:35:54.330
And paste the commands in.

01:35:54.330 --> 01:35:55.330
EXIT.

01:35:55.330 --> 01:35:57.130
Finally, DSW-B2.

01:35:57.130 --> 01:36:00.230
Let’s paste the commands in here, and EXIT.

01:36:00.230 --> 01:36:03.250
Okay, we’re done with step 2.

01:36:03.250 --> 01:36:06.950
Now hosts should be able to lease IP addresses.

01:36:06.950 --> 01:36:10.400
To test, I’ll go on PC1.

01:36:10.400 --> 01:36:14.120
From the Desktop tab, click on Command Prompt.

01:36:14.120 --> 01:36:21.389
And then use IPCONFIG /RENEW to send a DHCP
DISCOVER and lease an IP address.

01:36:21.389 --> 01:36:24.030
And a few seconds later, it works.

01:36:24.030 --> 01:36:26.090
Let’s try some pings now.

01:36:26.090 --> 01:36:29.520
How about pinging R1’s loopback interface?

01:36:29.520 --> 01:36:31.480
PING 10.0.0.76.

01:36:31.480 --> 01:36:35.469
Okay, the ping works.

01:36:35.469 --> 01:36:38.890
And how about one of R1’s internet interfaces?

01:36:38.890 --> 01:36:42.300
PING 203.0.113.2.

01:36:42.300 --> 01:36:43.800
That ping works as well.

01:36:43.800 --> 01:36:50.060
However, what if I ping the ISP router at
PING 203.0.113.1.

01:36:50.060 --> 01:36:52.670
As you can see, this ping doesn’t work.

01:36:52.670 --> 01:36:55.610
Once again, this is because we need to configure
NAT on R1.

01:36:55.610 --> 01:36:59.820
That’ll be later in a later step.

01:36:59.820 --> 01:37:02.199
But now, let’s move on to step 3.

01:37:02.199 --> 01:37:09.429
In this step, we’ll configure some DNS entries
on SRV1: one for google.com, one for youtube.com,

01:37:09.429 --> 01:37:11.630
and one for jeremysitlab.com.

01:37:11.630 --> 01:37:14.070
The three most popular sites on the web.

01:37:14.070 --> 01:37:20.500
And then we’ll create another entry mapping
www.jeremysitlab.com to jeremysitlab.com.

01:37:20.500 --> 01:37:24.739
So, let’s open up SRV1 again.

01:37:24.739 --> 01:37:28.090
And from the services tab, click on DNS.

01:37:28.090 --> 01:37:34.460
First, make sure to turn on the DNS service
here, or SRV1 won’t respond to DNS queries.

01:37:34.460 --> 01:37:38.360
Now let’s create those three IP address
mappings.

01:37:38.360 --> 01:37:43.510
To map a domain name to an IPv4 address, we
need to make an A record, which is the default

01:37:43.510 --> 01:37:44.510
here.

01:37:44.510 --> 01:37:49.449
So, I’ll type google.com for the name, and
then let’s check that address.

01:37:49.449 --> 01:37:50.469
172.253.62.100.

01:37:50.469 --> 01:37:57.780
Okay, so I’ll just highlight the address
here, left click and copy, and then paste

01:37:57.780 --> 01:38:01.360
it here and click Add to add the entry.

01:38:01.360 --> 01:38:04.690
Next, type youtube.com for the name.

01:38:04.690 --> 01:38:08.570
And let’s copy the address here.

01:38:08.570 --> 01:38:11.020
152.250.31.93.

01:38:11.020 --> 01:38:14.630
And paste it in the address box, and add the
entry.

01:38:14.630 --> 01:38:21.090
Finally, type jeremysitlab.com for the domain
name, and let’s copy the address.

01:38:21.090 --> 01:38:22.550
66.235.200.145.

01:38:22.550 --> 01:38:26.760
And then paste it in the address bar.

01:38:26.760 --> 01:38:32.080
Okay, so we’ve created three A records mapping
names to IP addresses.

01:38:32.080 --> 01:38:37.429
Now we have to map a name to another name,
and for that we need a CNAME, canonical name,

01:38:37.429 --> 01:38:38.429
record.

01:38:38.429 --> 01:38:43.570
So, in the ‘name’ box type www.jeremysitlab.com.

01:38:43.570 --> 01:38:46.320
And then in the host name box type jeremysitlab.com.

01:38:46.320 --> 01:38:50.690
Okay, we’ve created the DNS records.

01:38:50.690 --> 01:38:52.849
Now let’s test if DNS works.

01:38:52.849 --> 01:38:59.610
I’ll go back to PC1, and first let’s ping
SRV1 to make sure that PC1 can reach it.

01:38:59.610 --> 01:39:02.880
PING 10.5.0.4.

01:39:02.880 --> 01:39:10.739
Okay, PC1 can reach SRV1.

01:39:10.739 --> 01:39:12.750
Now let’s try one of those entries we created.

01:39:12.750 --> 01:39:13.750
PING google.com.

01:39:13.750 --> 01:39:18.440
Okay, the ping failed because we still haven’t
configured NAT, but notice that DNS itself

01:39:18.440 --> 01:39:19.440
worked.

01:39:19.440 --> 01:39:24.349
Using DNS, PC1 was able to translate google.com
into this IP address.

01:39:24.349 --> 01:39:28.630
And how about PING jeremysitlab.com.

01:39:28.630 --> 01:39:33.550
Same thing, the ping doesn’t work, but DNS
resolution does work.

01:39:33.550 --> 01:39:39.150
And one more: PING www.jeremysitlab.com.

01:39:39.150 --> 01:39:40.219
Same thing.

01:39:40.219 --> 01:39:45.909
Notice that it was translated to the same
IP address as jeremysitlab.com.

01:39:45.909 --> 01:39:53.989
www.jeremysitlab.com was translated into jeremysitlab.com,
which was then translated into this IP address.

01:39:53.989 --> 01:40:00.820
Next, in step 4, we’ll configure all routers
and switches to use the domain name jeremysitlab.com

01:40:00.820 --> 01:40:04.450
and to use SRV1 as their DNS server.

01:40:04.450 --> 01:40:08.909
This requires the same two commands on all
devices, so once again I’ll just copy and

01:40:08.909 --> 01:40:10.870
paste the commands from the notepad.

01:40:10.870 --> 01:40:18.850
Those two commands are IP DOMAIN NAME jeremysitlab.com
and IP NAME-SERVER 10.5.0.4.

01:40:18.850 --> 01:40:24.060
I’ll copy these commands, and then paste
them into each device.

01:40:24.060 --> 01:40:26.560
Feel free to skip ahead in the video.

01:40:26.560 --> 01:40:29.210
So, R1 first.

01:40:29.210 --> 01:40:31.790
Right click, paste.

01:40:31.790 --> 01:40:34.099
And CSW1.

01:40:34.099 --> 01:40:36.320
Right click and paste.

01:40:36.320 --> 01:40:40.130
And then CSW2.

01:40:40.130 --> 01:40:43.969
Moving on to the distribution switches.

01:40:43.969 --> 01:40:46.570
DSW-A1.

01:40:46.570 --> 01:40:49.170
DSW-A2.

01:40:49.170 --> 01:40:53.570
And then DSW-B1.

01:40:53.570 --> 01:40:55.130
And DSW-B2.

01:40:55.130 --> 01:40:58.949
And then the access switches.

01:40:58.949 --> 01:41:02.190
ASW-A1 first.

01:41:02.190 --> 01:41:03.590
Then ASW-A2.

01:41:03.590 --> 01:41:07.790
And then A3.

01:41:07.790 --> 01:41:14.850
And then Office B. ASW-B1.

01:41:14.850 --> 01:41:17.400
ASW-B2.

01:41:17.400 --> 01:41:19.880
And ASW-B3.

01:41:19.880 --> 01:41:27.550
And just to test that DNS works on these devices,
first let’s ping SRV1 from here on ASW-B3.

01:41:27.550 --> 01:41:31.210
DO PING 10.5.0.4.

01:41:31.210 --> 01:41:35.599
Okay, the ping works.

01:41:35.599 --> 01:41:38.370
And now let’s try DO PING google.com.

01:41:38.370 --> 01:41:44.219
Okay, once again the ping itself doesn’t
work, but DNS was able to translate the name

01:41:44.219 --> 01:41:45.739
into an IP address.

01:41:45.739 --> 01:41:50.380
Now let’s move on to step 5, in which we’ll
configure NTP.

01:41:50.380 --> 01:41:54.830
5a says to make R1 a stratum 5 NTP server.

01:41:54.830 --> 01:41:57.760
We can do that with the NTP MASTER command.

01:41:57.760 --> 01:42:03.670
And then 5b says that R1 should learn the
time from NTP server 216.239.35.0.

01:42:03.670 --> 01:42:09.810
5c is just a note saying that you don’t
need to wait for NTP to sync – it can take

01:42:09.810 --> 01:42:14.270
a very long time, so once you’ve done the
configurations you can just move on.

01:42:14.270 --> 01:42:17.740
So, let’s go on the CLI of R1.

01:42:17.740 --> 01:42:24.659
To make R1 an NTP server with a specific stratum
level, use NTP MASTER, followed by the stratum,

01:42:24.659 --> 01:42:26.310
which should be 5 in this case.

01:42:26.310 --> 01:42:28.790
So, that’s the first half.

01:42:28.790 --> 01:42:37.099
Next, to make R1 sync to an external NTP server,
use NTP SERVER, followed by the IP address,

01:42:37.099 --> 01:42:39.989
which is 216.239.35.0.

01:42:39.989 --> 01:42:45.390
And that’s all for step 5 – like I said,
NTP takes a very long time to sync, so let’s

01:42:45.390 --> 01:42:46.560
just move on.

01:42:46.560 --> 01:42:50.619
Step 6 is a continuation of step 5.

01:42:50.619 --> 01:42:57.540
We’ll configure NTP on all core, distribution,
and access switches, making them sync to R1.

01:42:57.540 --> 01:43:02.360
Specifically, they should use the IP address
of R1’s loopback interface.

01:43:02.360 --> 01:43:09.139
Additionally, these clients should authenticate
R1 using key number 1 and the password ‘ccna’.

01:43:09.139 --> 01:43:15.660
So, first I’ll create the authentication
key on R1, and then configure the clients.

01:43:15.660 --> 01:43:22.520
To create the key, the command is NTP AUTHENTICATION-KEY,
followed by the key number, which should be

01:43:22.520 --> 01:43:26.889
1, MD5, and then the key itself, ccna.

01:43:26.889 --> 01:43:33.600
However, that’s not enough; we need to specify
it as a “trusted key” with NTP TRUSTED-KEY

01:43:33.600 --> 01:43:34.600
1.

01:43:34.600 --> 01:43:37.489
Okay, that’s all for R1.

01:43:37.489 --> 01:43:40.699
Now let’s do the clients: all of the switches.

01:43:40.699 --> 01:43:46.090
The configurations are identical on all switches,
so I’ll do one manually and then copy and

01:43:46.090 --> 01:43:47.190
paste the rest.

01:43:47.190 --> 01:43:50.030
So, let’s go on CSW1.

01:43:50.030 --> 01:43:54.230
First, use the same two commands we just configured
on R1.

01:43:54.230 --> 01:43:57.800
NTP AUTHENTICATION-KEY 1 MD5 ccna.

01:43:57.800 --> 01:44:03.690
And then NTP TRUSTED-KEY 1.

01:44:03.690 --> 01:44:08.000
So, we’ve created the authentication key
and trusted it.

01:44:08.000 --> 01:44:14.179
Next, let’s tell CSW1 to sync to R1, while
using key number 1 for authentication.

01:44:14.179 --> 01:44:17.790
The command is NTP SERVER 10.0.0.76 KEY 1.

01:44:17.790 --> 01:44:19.619
And that’s it.

01:44:19.619 --> 01:44:25.699
As I said, NTP takes forever to sync, so we
won’t wait for that.

01:44:25.699 --> 01:44:27.770
Let’s just configure the other switches.

01:44:27.770 --> 01:44:34.080
So, I’ll go to the notepad, and here it
is: part 6, step 6.

01:44:34.080 --> 01:44:40.320
I’ll highlight and copy those three commands,
and let’s go to CSW2 next, and paste them

01:44:40.320 --> 01:44:42.290
in.

01:44:42.290 --> 01:44:44.989
And now the distribution and access switches.

01:44:44.989 --> 01:44:53.869
Again, feel free to skip ahead in 
the video.

01:44:53.869 --> 01:44:55.540
DSW-A1.

01:44:55.540 --> 01:44:57.210
DSW-A2.

01:44:57.210 --> 01:44:58.880
DSW-B1.

01:44:58.880 --> 01:45:00.550
DSW-B2.

01:45:00.550 --> 01:45:06.920
And then the access switches, starting with
A1.

01:45:06.920 --> 01:45:10.500
Then ASW-A2.

01:45:10.500 --> 01:45:14.080
ASW-A3.

01:45:14.080 --> 01:45:17.660
ASW-B1.

01:45:17.660 --> 01:45:21.239
ASW-B2.

01:45:21.239 --> 01:45:22.280
And ASW-B3.

01:45:22.280 --> 01:45:25.900
Okay, that’s all for NTP.

01:45:25.900 --> 01:45:30.910
Next, in steps 7 and 8, we’ll configure
SNMP and Syslog.

01:45:30.910 --> 01:45:35.830
I’ll do these two steps together because
all devices need the same commands, so I can

01:45:35.830 --> 01:45:37.650
just copy and paste them together.

01:45:37.650 --> 01:45:40.219
Let’s see the requirements.

01:45:40.219 --> 01:45:47.140
Step 7 says to configure the SNMP community
string SNMPSTRING on all routers and switches.

01:45:47.140 --> 01:45:50.190
It should allow GET messages, but not SET
messages.

01:45:50.190 --> 01:45:55.130
So, that means it should be a read only string,
rather than a read-write string.

01:45:55.130 --> 01:45:59.860
Let’s configure that on R1 before looking
at the Syslog requirements.

01:45:59.860 --> 01:46:05.590
The command to configure an SNMP community
string is SNMP-SERVER COMMUNITY, followed

01:46:05.590 --> 01:46:12.030
by the string, SNMPSTRING in this case, and
then RO for read only.

01:46:12.030 --> 01:46:13.650
That’s it.

01:46:13.650 --> 01:46:18.840
With that configured, an SNMP server should
be able to send SNMP GET messages to read

01:46:18.840 --> 01:46:21.739
information from this router.

01:46:21.739 --> 01:46:25.760
Now let’s go back to see the Syslog requirements
in step 8.

01:46:25.760 --> 01:46:31.310
It says to send Syslog messages to SRV1, and
messages of all severity levels should be

01:46:31.310 --> 01:46:32.310
logged.

01:46:32.310 --> 01:46:39.530
Then 8b says to enable logging to the buffer,
and reserve 8192 bytes of memory for the buffer.

01:46:39.530 --> 01:46:44.030
So, let’s go into R1 and configure that.

01:46:44.030 --> 01:46:47.510
First we need to send Syslog message to SRV1.

01:46:47.510 --> 01:46:52.250
To enable that, just use LOGGING 10.5.0.4.

01:46:52.250 --> 01:46:55.750
And we need to ensure that messages of all
severity levels are sent.

01:46:55.750 --> 01:47:00.640
So, levels 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, and 0.

01:47:00.640 --> 01:47:04.300
To configure that, use LOGGING TRAP DEBUGGING.

01:47:04.300 --> 01:47:08.230
That enables logging at the debugging level,
level 7, and below.

01:47:08.230 --> 01:47:13.050
Finally, we need to enable logging to the
buffer, which is stored in local memory on

01:47:13.050 --> 01:47:14.460
the device.

01:47:14.460 --> 01:47:19.520
The command to do that is LOGGING BUFFERED,
but the instructions also specify that the

01:47:19.520 --> 01:47:26.659
buffer’s size should be 8192 bytes, so add
8192 to the end of this command.

01:47:26.659 --> 01:47:27.659
There we go.

01:47:27.659 --> 01:47:32.040
Let’s quickly check that everything is correct
with DO SHOW LOGGING.

01:47:32.040 --> 01:47:38.239
So, logging to the console, monitor, and buffer
are all enabled at level debugging.

01:47:38.239 --> 01:47:45.560
And if I scroll to the bottom, you can see
that the buffer is 8192 bytes in size.

01:47:45.560 --> 01:47:50.219
The rest of the devices all need the exact
same commands as R1, so let me open up the

01:47:50.219 --> 01:47:55.349
notepad and copy these commands under part
6, steps 7 and 8.

01:47:55.349 --> 01:48:02.869
And now let’s paste them into the remaining
devices, CSW1 first.

01:48:02.869 --> 01:48:06.310
Then CSW2.

01:48:06.310 --> 01:48:09.640
DSW-A1.

01:48:09.640 --> 01:48:12.969
DSW-A2.

01:48:12.969 --> 01:48:16.300
DSW-B1.

01:48:16.300 --> 01:48:19.630
DSW-B2.

01:48:19.630 --> 01:48:24.850
And the access switches, starting with ASW-A1.

01:48:24.850 --> 01:48:28.150
A2.

01:48:28.150 --> 01:48:31.460
A3.

01:48:31.460 --> 01:48:34.760
ASW-B1.

01:48:34.760 --> 01:48:38.070
ASW-B2.

01:48:38.070 --> 01:48:40.550
And finally, ASW-B3.

01:48:40.550 --> 01:48:46.560
So, we’ve configured SNMP and Syslog on
all of these devices.

01:48:46.560 --> 01:48:49.550
Now let’s move on to step 9.

01:48:49.550 --> 01:48:55.430
In step 9, we’ll use FTP on R1 to download
a new IOS version from SRV1.

01:48:55.430 --> 01:49:01.850
To do so, well first configure R1’s default
FTP credentials in 9a, copy the file from

01:49:01.850 --> 01:49:07.139
SRV1 in 9b, and then reboot R1 using the new
IOS version in 9c.

01:49:07.139 --> 01:49:13.920
So, let’s do 9a first, which says to configure
username and password cisco on R1.

01:49:13.920 --> 01:49:19.940
To configure the username, the command is
IP FTP USERNAME, and in this case the username

01:49:19.940 --> 01:49:22.050
should be cisco.

01:49:22.050 --> 01:49:26.620
And then to configure the password it’s
IP FTP PASSWORD cisco.

01:49:26.620 --> 01:49:28.810
That’s it.

01:49:28.810 --> 01:49:31.760
Next let’s look closer at step 9b.

01:49:31.760 --> 01:49:36.710
We should use FTP to copy this file from SRV1
to R1’s flash drive.

01:49:36.710 --> 01:49:41.219
So, you can copy the file name right here
from the instructions, but let’s go find

01:49:41.219 --> 01:49:43.310
it on SRV1.

01:49:43.310 --> 01:49:50.850
From the services tab on SRV1, click on FTP,
and you can see the available files here.

01:49:50.850 --> 01:49:54.540
Look for c2900 universal, there it is.

01:49:54.540 --> 01:50:01.469
So, click on the file name here, use ctrl-c
to copy, and now let’s go back to R1.

01:50:01.469 --> 01:50:06.110
First, let’s verify that R1 can ping SRV1.

01:50:06.110 --> 01:50:08.389
DO PING 10.5.0.4.

01:50:08.389 --> 01:50:11.320
Okay, connectivity is fine.

01:50:11.320 --> 01:50:16.909
Now let’s copy the file to flash with DO
COPY FTP: FLASH:.

01:50:16.909 --> 01:50:20.670
First, it asks for the address of the remote
host.

01:50:20.670 --> 01:50:24.540
Enter 10.5.0.4 for SRV1.

01:50:24.540 --> 01:50:27.820
Then the source filename, the name of the
file on SRV1.

01:50:27.820 --> 01:50:31.949
So, I’ll paste that filename that I just
copied here.

01:50:31.949 --> 01:50:34.639
And finally, the destination filename.

01:50:34.639 --> 01:50:38.760
Just hit enter here to accept the default,
which is the same as the source filename.

01:50:38.760 --> 01:50:42.060
Now, it’ll start copying the file.

01:50:42.060 --> 01:50:44.679
Just a warning, this is going to take a very
long time.

01:50:44.679 --> 01:50:48.980
It’ll take so long that you’ll think it’s
not working, but it is.

01:50:48.980 --> 01:50:53.500
So if you’re doing the lab now, get up,
grab a drink, take a break, and come back

01:50:53.500 --> 01:50:54.500
later.

01:50:54.500 --> 01:50:58.730
I’ll stop the video here and return when
the download is complete.

01:50:58.730 --> 01:51:01.159
Okay, the download is done.

01:51:01.159 --> 01:51:04.090
I’ll use DO SHOW FLASH: to view the file.

01:51:04.090 --> 01:51:05.090
There it is.

01:51:05.090 --> 01:51:09.010
Now let’s configure R1 to boot using this
new IOS image.

01:51:09.010 --> 01:51:12.150
First, highlight and copy the filename if
you need to.

01:51:12.150 --> 01:51:19.349
Then, to tell R1 to boot from this file, use
BOOT SYSTEM FLASH:, and then paste the filename.

01:51:19.349 --> 01:51:24.429
Now, before rebooting the router it’s very
important to save the config; otherwise, the

01:51:24.429 --> 01:51:26.830
BOOT SYSTEM command won’t take effect.

01:51:26.830 --> 01:51:28.820
So, use DO WRITE.

01:51:28.820 --> 01:51:33.670
And before rebooting, let’s also use DO
SHOW VERSION, and look at the top line of

01:51:33.670 --> 01:51:34.870
the output.

01:51:34.870 --> 01:51:35.870
Version 15.1.

01:51:35.870 --> 01:51:39.540
After rebooting, we’ll check to make sure
that it changes.

01:51:39.540 --> 01:51:44.590
So, I’ll use DO RELOAD to reboot the router.

01:51:44.590 --> 01:51:49.111
This can take quite a few minutes on a real
device, but fortunately these routers in Packet

01:51:49.111 --> 01:51:55.989
Tracer only take about 10 or 15 seconds.

01:51:55.989 --> 01:52:01.880
Once it has booted up, log in with cisco and
password ccna.

01:52:01.880 --> 01:52:06.510
Then ENABLE and password jeremysitlab.

01:52:06.510 --> 01:52:09.780
And now let’s check the version again with
SHOW VERSION.

01:52:09.780 --> 01:52:17.170
So, look at the top line, and there it is:
version 15.5, upgraded from the previous 15.1.

01:52:17.170 --> 01:52:21.730
Now let’s look at the instructions one more
time.

01:52:21.730 --> 01:52:26.750
At the end of step 9c it says to delete the
old IOS file from flash.

01:52:26.750 --> 01:52:31.570
So, let’s view the contents of flash again
with SHOW FLASH.

01:52:31.570 --> 01:52:36.550
And then highlight the filename of the old
version, right click and copy the name.

01:52:36.550 --> 01:52:42.429
And then delete it with DELETE FLASH, with
a colon, and then paste the filename here.

01:52:42.429 --> 01:52:47.440
So, delete the file, and let’s double check
with SHOW FLASH once more.

01:52:47.440 --> 01:52:48.869
Okay, now it’s gone.

01:52:48.869 --> 01:52:50.880
So, we’re done with step 9.

01:52:50.880 --> 01:52:54.500
Let’s take a look at step 10 next.

01:52:54.500 --> 01:52:59.550
It says to configure SSH for secure remote
access on all routers and switches.

01:52:59.550 --> 01:53:03.010
Okay, let’s read through the requirements.

01:53:03.010 --> 01:53:08.080
10a says to use the largest modulus size for
the RSA keys.

01:53:08.080 --> 01:53:12.290
10b says to allow SSH version 2 connections
only.

01:53:12.290 --> 01:53:17.880
10c says to create and apply a standard ACL
that allows only packets sourced from Office

01:53:17.880 --> 01:53:19.970
A’s PCs subnet.

01:53:19.970 --> 01:53:25.400
So only PCs in that subnet will be able to
use SSH to configure these devices.

01:53:25.400 --> 01:53:31.570
10d says we should only allow SSH connections
to the VTY lines – no Telnet.

01:53:31.570 --> 01:53:38.219
E says to require users to log in with a local
user account when connecting via SSH.

01:53:38.219 --> 01:53:42.070
And then finally we must configure synchronous
logging on the VTY lines.

01:53:42.070 --> 01:53:46.989
So, this is another step where we have to
configure the same thing on all of these devices.

01:53:46.989 --> 01:53:50.960
First, let’s go on R1 and walk through each
step.

01:53:50.960 --> 01:53:57.909
First, I’ll return to global config mode
with CONF T. To use SSH, we need to create

01:53:57.909 --> 01:53:59.780
an RSA key pair.

01:53:59.780 --> 01:54:03.960
Let’s do that with CRYPTO KEY GENERATE RSA.

01:54:03.960 --> 01:54:07.000
Now it asks for the key modulus size.

01:54:07.000 --> 01:54:12.880
This plays a big role in determining the security
of the keys; a larger size is more secure.

01:54:12.880 --> 01:54:17.630
The instructions said to use the largest size
available, and as you can see here that is

01:54:17.630 --> 01:54:19.190
4096 bits.

01:54:19.190 --> 01:54:23.750
So, enter 4096 here and press enter.

01:54:23.750 --> 01:54:28.969
Now I’ll use DO SHOW IP SSH to check the
SSH version.

01:54:28.969 --> 01:54:35.390
Notice that SSH version 1.99 is enabled. 1.99
isn’t actually a version of SSH.

01:54:35.390 --> 01:54:41.610
It just means that R1 accepts both SSH version
1 and version 2 connections.

01:54:41.610 --> 01:54:45.969
Let’s change that with IP SSH VERSION 2.

01:54:45.969 --> 01:54:49.060
And confirm with DO SHOW IP SSH again.

01:54:49.060 --> 01:54:53.390
So, now R1 will only accept SSHv2 connections.

01:54:53.390 --> 01:54:59.420
Next, before we configure the VTY lines, let’s
create that ACL that allows only the Office

01:54:59.420 --> 01:55:01.450
A PCs subnet.

01:55:01.450 --> 01:55:12.560
The subnet is 10.1.0.0/24, so ACCESS-LIST
1 PERMIT 10.1.0.0 0.0.0.255.

01:55:12.560 --> 01:55:15.280
And that’s it, we just need that one entry.

01:55:15.280 --> 01:55:18.060
The implicit deny will block all other traffic.

01:55:18.060 --> 01:55:23.830
Now let’s configure the VTY lines with LINE
VTY 0 15.

01:55:23.830 --> 01:55:27.230
First, I’ll apply that ACL.

01:55:27.230 --> 01:55:32.370
To apply an ACL to an interface, the command
is IP ACCESS-GROUP, but for the VTY lines

01:55:32.370 --> 01:55:38.579
it’s ACCESS-CLASS, then the ACL name or
number, 1 in this case, and IN.

01:55:38.579 --> 01:55:45.130
Next, I’ll allow only SSH connections – no
Telnet, since it isn’t secure.

01:55:45.130 --> 01:55:48.230
TRANSPORT INPUT SSH.

01:55:48.230 --> 01:55:52.520
And let’s require users to log in with a
local user account, just like we configured

01:55:52.520 --> 01:55:55.420
on the console line at the beginning of this
lab.

01:55:55.420 --> 01:55:57.330
LOGIN LOCAL.

01:55:57.330 --> 01:56:00.190
And then enable synchronous logging with LOGGING
SYNCHRONOUS.

01:56:00.190 --> 01:56:03.000
Okay, that’s all for R1.

01:56:03.000 --> 01:56:07.469
I’ll EXIT back to global config mode.

01:56:07.469 --> 01:56:11.920
The other devices require the same commands,
so once again I’ll copy and paste them from

01:56:11.920 --> 01:56:13.199
the notepad.

01:56:13.199 --> 01:56:19.640
First, generating the keys with CRYPTO KEY
GENERATE RSA, and then 4096 to specify the

01:56:19.640 --> 01:56:21.840
modulus size.

01:56:21.840 --> 01:56:26.670
Enabling SSH version 2, configuring an ACL
and applying it to the VTY lines.

01:56:26.670 --> 01:56:32.370
Allowing only SSH, requiring login with a
local user account, and enabling synchronous

01:56:32.370 --> 01:56:33.370
logging.

01:56:33.370 --> 01:56:37.820
Let’s copy these commands, and then paste
them into the other devices.

01:56:37.820 --> 01:56:40.050
CSW1 first.

01:56:40.050 --> 01:56:42.600
Paste in the commands, and EXIT.

01:56:42.600 --> 01:56:44.790
Then CSW2.

01:56:44.790 --> 01:56:47.989
Right click and paste, and then EXIT.

01:56:47.989 --> 01:56:49.099
DSW-A1.

01:56:49.099 --> 01:56:53.540
Right click, paste, EXIT.

01:56:53.540 --> 01:56:54.650
DSW-A2.

01:56:54.650 --> 01:56:57.960
Right click, paste, exit.

01:56:57.960 --> 01:56:59.060
DSW-B1.

01:56:59.060 --> 01:57:01.840
Right click, paste, EXIT.

01:57:01.840 --> 01:57:03.150
And B2.

01:57:03.150 --> 01:57:05.699
Right click, paste, exit.

01:57:05.699 --> 01:57:09.739
Finally, the access switches, starting with
A1.

01:57:09.739 --> 01:57:12.560
Paste the commands, EXIT.

01:57:12.560 --> 01:57:14.140
Then A2.

01:57:14.140 --> 01:57:16.739
Paste the commands, EXIT.

01:57:16.739 --> 01:57:18.360
And A3.

01:57:18.360 --> 01:57:21.290
Right click, paste, EXIT.

01:57:21.290 --> 01:57:23.350
Then ASW-B1.

01:57:23.350 --> 01:57:25.510
Paste the commands, EXIT.

01:57:25.510 --> 01:57:27.520
And B2.

01:57:27.520 --> 01:57:29.660
Paste the commands, EXIT.

01:57:29.660 --> 01:57:32.550
And finally ASW-B3.

01:57:32.550 --> 01:57:35.640
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

01:57:35.640 --> 01:57:41.530
Okay, now before moving on let’s test SSH
by connecting to one of the devices.

01:57:41.530 --> 01:57:44.360
I’ll go on PC1.

01:57:44.360 --> 01:57:48.639
From the command prompt, I’ll try to ping
R1’s loopback.

01:57:48.639 --> 01:57:50.910
PING 10.0.0.76.

01:57:50.910 --> 01:57:54.369
Okay, PC1 can reach R1.

01:57:54.369 --> 01:57:56.989
Now let’s SSH.

01:57:56.989 --> 01:58:02.270
SSH -l cisco 10.0.0.76.

01:58:02.270 --> 01:58:05.349
Enter the password ‘ccna’, and we’re
in.

01:58:05.349 --> 01:58:08.230
So, SSH works from PC1.

01:58:08.230 --> 01:58:10.989
Now I’ll EXIT out of there.

01:58:10.989 --> 01:58:15.659
Next I’ll try from PC3, let’s open its
command prompt.

01:58:15.659 --> 01:58:20.750
Because of the ACL we applied, SSH shouldn’t
work from PC3 – it’s not in the Office

01:58:20.750 --> 01:58:23.240
A PCs subnet.

01:58:23.240 --> 01:58:28.830
First I’ll just use IPCONFIG /RENEW to make
sure that PC3 got an IP address, since we

01:58:28.830 --> 01:58:32.120
just configured DHCP in this part of the lab.

01:58:32.120 --> 01:58:36.449
Okay, and next I’ll ping R1 with PING 10.0.0.76.

01:58:36.449 --> 01:58:38.690
Okay, the ping works.

01:58:38.690 --> 01:58:42.020
Finally, let’s try SSH.

01:58:42.020 --> 01:58:47.010
SSH -l cisco 10.0.0.76.

01:58:47.010 --> 01:58:50.429
Connection refused by remote host, so the
ACL is working.

01:58:50.429 --> 01:58:53.770
That’s all for step 10.

01:58:53.770 --> 01:58:57.750
Steps 11 and 12 focus on NAT, Network Address
Translation.

01:58:57.750 --> 01:59:04.680
We’ll configure static NAT in step 11, and
then pool-based dynamic PAT in step 12.

01:59:04.680 --> 01:59:07.150
So let’s read step 11 first.

01:59:07.150 --> 01:59:13.051
It says to configure static NAT on R1 to enable
hosts on the Internet to access SRV1 via the

01:59:13.051 --> 01:59:15.640
IP address 203.0.113.113.

01:59:15.640 --> 01:59:23.440
So, we just need to configure a static NAT
statement mapping SRV1’s inside local address,

01:59:23.440 --> 01:59:29.440
10.5.0.4, to the inside global address 203.0.113.113.

01:59:29.440 --> 01:59:31.500
It only takes a single command.

01:59:31.500 --> 01:59:39.291
Let’s open up the CLI of R1, and configure
it with IP NAT INSIDE SOURCE STATIC, then

01:59:39.291 --> 01:59:45.980
the inside local address, which is 10.5.0.4,
followed by the inside global address, which

01:59:45.980 --> 01:59:47.790
is 203.0.113.113.

01:59:47.790 --> 01:59:54.201
Now, we’ve configured the static NAT statement,
but there’s still something missing; we

01:59:54.201 --> 01:59:57.770
need to specify the inside and outside interfaces.

01:59:57.770 --> 02:00:04.650
R1 G0/0/0 and G0/1/0 are connected to the
Internet, so I’ll make them the outside

02:00:04.650 --> 02:00:06.020
interfaces.

02:00:06.020 --> 02:00:09.670
INTERFACE RANGE g0/0/0 and g0/1/0.

02:00:09.670 --> 02:00:11.720
IP NAT OUTSIDE.

02:00:11.720 --> 02:00:20.900
And then the inside interfaces are G0/0 and
G0/1, connected to CSW1 and CSW2.

02:00:20.900 --> 02:00:22.530
INTERFACE RANGE G0/0-1.

02:00:22.530 --> 02:00:25.430
IP NAT INSIDE.

02:00:25.430 --> 02:00:26.849
And EXIT.

02:00:26.849 --> 02:00:31.090
Okay, so we’ve configured static NAT for
SRV1.

02:00:31.090 --> 02:00:35.989
That should allow hosts on the Internet to
communicate with SRV1 by sending their packets

02:00:35.989 --> 02:00:39.239
to 203.0.113.113.

02:00:39.239 --> 02:00:43.260
It should also allow SRV1 to ping hosts on
the Internet, so let’s test that.

02:00:43.260 --> 02:00:50.849
I’ll go back to SRV1, and let’s open up
the command prompt, and then try PING google.com.

02:00:50.849 --> 02:00:53.579
Okay, the ping doesn’t work.

02:00:53.579 --> 02:00:59.079
Even though SRV1 is a DNS server, we have
to specify itself as its own DNS server in

02:00:59.079 --> 02:01:00.389
Packet Tracer.

02:01:00.389 --> 02:01:06.420
So go to the config tab, and add 10.5.0.4
as the DNS server here.

02:01:06.420 --> 02:01:08.460
This isn’t part of the lab steps by the
way.

02:01:08.460 --> 02:01:10.590
I’m just doing it to test.

02:01:10.590 --> 02:01:15.610
Next, return to the command prompt, and let’s
try PING google.com again.

02:01:15.610 --> 02:01:17.300
Okay, now the ping works.

02:01:17.300 --> 02:01:20.230
So, step 11 is done.

02:01:20.230 --> 02:01:25.550
In step 12, we’ll configure dynamic PAT,
port address translation, to enable the other

02:01:25.550 --> 02:01:29.250
hosts in these LANs to communicate over the
Internet.

02:01:29.250 --> 02:01:34.270
We will configure pool-based dynamic NAT,
so we’ll need an ACL to define the appropriate

02:01:34.270 --> 02:01:40.449
inside local addresses, a NAT pool to define
a range of inside global addresses, and then

02:01:40.449 --> 02:01:42.860
we’ll map them to each other with a NAT
statement.

02:01:42.860 --> 02:01:48.139
So, let’s first create the ACL, looking
at step 12a.

02:01:48.139 --> 02:01:52.770
It says to use standard ACL 2 to define the
appropriate inside local address ranges in

02:01:52.770 --> 02:01:54.389
the following order.

02:01:54.389 --> 02:02:00.190
Office A PCs, Office A phones, Office B PCs,
Office B Phones, and then Wi-Fi.

02:02:00.190 --> 02:02:04.290
I’ll open the CLI of R1 again, and let’s
make that ACL.

02:02:04.290 --> 02:02:08.489
First, I’ll permit the Office A PCs subnet.

02:02:08.489 --> 02:02:15.410
ACCESS-LIST 2 PERMIT 10.1.0.0 0.0.0.255.

02:02:15.410 --> 02:02:20.849
Then I’ll hit the up arrow, and let’s
change that to 10.2.0.0 for the Office A Phones

02:02:20.849 --> 02:02:21.889
subnet.

02:02:21.889 --> 02:02:27.330
And then do it again, permitting 10.3.0.0
for the Office B PCs.

02:02:27.330 --> 02:02:31.980
And then again, configure 10.4.0.0 for the
Office B Phones.

02:02:31.980 --> 02:02:36.790
And finally permit 10.6.0.0/24 for the Wi-Fi
subnet.

02:02:36.790 --> 02:02:42.730
So, that ACL defines the range of inside local
addresses that will be translated when communicating

02:02:42.730 --> 02:02:44.429
over the Internet.

02:02:44.429 --> 02:02:46.680
Now let’s look at step 12b.

02:02:46.680 --> 02:02:51.550
We need to define the pool of inside local
addresses – the public IP addresses.

02:02:51.550 --> 02:02:59.460
The pool’s name should be POOL1, with a
range from 203.0.113.200 to .207 and a /29

02:02:59.460 --> 02:03:00.460
netmask.

02:03:00.460 --> 02:03:03.380
So, let’s go back on to R1.

02:03:03.380 --> 02:03:12.239
And create the pool with IP NAT POOL POOL1,
and then the starting IP address, 203.0.113.200.

02:03:12.239 --> 02:03:16.460
And then the ending IP address, 203.0.113.207.

02:03:16.460 --> 02:03:22.120
NETMASK, and then 255.255.255.248 for /29.

02:03:22.120 --> 02:03:27.099
Okay, we’ve created the ACL and the pool.

02:03:27.099 --> 02:03:33.440
Now let’s do step 12c, which says to map
ACL 2 to POOL1 and enable PAT, and then confirm

02:03:33.440 --> 02:03:35.500
that hosts can access the Internet.

02:03:35.500 --> 02:03:39.270
So, let’s go back to R1 and configure the
NAT statement.

02:03:39.270 --> 02:03:47.790
IP NAT INSIDE SOURCE LIST 2 POOL POOL1, and
then don’t forget OVERLOAD to make it PAT,

02:03:47.790 --> 02:03:49.570
instead of regular dynamic NAT.

02:03:49.570 --> 02:03:54.989
Okay, the NAT configuration is done, so let’s
test it out on PC1.

02:03:54.989 --> 02:03:58.580
From PC1, let’s do PING jeremysitlab.com.

02:03:58.580 --> 02:04:00.949
Okay, the ping works.

02:04:00.949 --> 02:04:04.690
So, our dynamic PAT configuration was correct.

02:04:04.690 --> 02:04:12.280
Now, step 12d says to verify that Internet
link failover works by disabling R1 G0/0/0

02:04:12.280 --> 02:04:13.670
and pinging again.

02:04:13.670 --> 02:04:19.460
However, note the paragraph here: you will
need to remove and re-configure the DEFAULT-INFORMATION

02:04:19.460 --> 02:04:22.100
ORIGINATE command on R1 for this to work.

02:04:22.100 --> 02:04:27.280
When R1 loses its primary default route and
inserts the floating default route into the

02:04:27.280 --> 02:04:32.630
routing table, it won’t automatically advertise
the new route into OSPF.

02:04:32.630 --> 02:04:38.470
As this explanation says, you can use DEFAULT-INFORMATION
ORIGINATE ALWAYS to work around this, but

02:04:38.470 --> 02:04:40.360
it’s not available in Packet Tracer.

02:04:40.360 --> 02:04:43.250
So, let’s go on R1 now.

02:04:43.250 --> 02:04:45.760
I’ll disable its G0/0/0 interface.

02:04:45.760 --> 02:04:47.960
INTERFACE G0/0/0.

02:04:47.960 --> 02:04:50.160
SHUTDOWN.

02:04:50.160 --> 02:04:54.639
Now R1 should remove its main default route
from the routing table, and insert the floating

02:04:54.639 --> 02:04:55.929
default route instead.

02:04:55.929 --> 02:04:59.840
Next let’s go into OSPF config mode.

02:04:59.840 --> 02:05:01.849
ROUTER OSPF 1.

02:05:01.849 --> 02:05:07.210
And then use NO DEFAULT-INFORMATION ORIGINATE
to remove the command, and then reconfigure

02:05:07.210 --> 02:05:08.409
it again.

02:05:08.409 --> 02:05:10.050
DEFAULT-INFORMATION ORIGINATE.

02:05:10.050 --> 02:05:15.349
So, R1 should now advertise its new default
route to other OSPF routers.

02:05:15.349 --> 02:05:19.349
Let’s just double check that the floating
static route actually entered the routing

02:05:19.349 --> 02:05:20.360
table.

02:05:20.360 --> 02:05:22.199
DO SHOW IP ROUTE.

02:05:22.199 --> 02:05:26.719
Okay, so down at the bottom of the output
you can see that R1’s default route has

02:05:26.719 --> 02:05:31.280
an AD of 2 – this is the floating route
we configured earlier in the lab.

02:05:31.280 --> 02:05:35.739
I’ll go on PC1 now and try that ping again.

02:05:35.739 --> 02:05:38.440
PING jeremysitlab.com.

02:05:38.440 --> 02:05:39.590
And it works again.

02:05:39.590 --> 02:05:41.780
So, the failover worked.

02:05:41.780 --> 02:05:44.679
Now let’s go back on R1 and undo that.

02:05:44.679 --> 02:05:48.170
First, I’ll re-enable G0/0/0.

02:05:48.170 --> 02:05:49.699
INTERFACE G0/0/0.

02:05:49.699 --> 02:05:51.110
NO SHUTDOWN.

02:05:51.110 --> 02:05:53.309
And then configure OSPF.

02:05:53.309 --> 02:05:55.290
ROUTER OSPF 1.

02:05:55.290 --> 02:05:58.150
NO DEFAULT-INFORMATION ORIGINATE.

02:05:58.150 --> 02:06:00.260
DEFAULT-INFORMATION ORIGINATE.

02:06:00.260 --> 02:06:01.980
And now I’ll EXIT.

02:06:01.980 --> 02:06:06.370
Okay, we have one last step before wrapping
up this part of the lab.

02:06:06.370 --> 02:06:12.190
In step 13, we’ll disable CDP on all devices
and enable LLDP instead.

02:06:12.190 --> 02:06:19.460
We also must disable LLDP Tx, that’s transmission,
on each access switch’s access port, which

02:06:19.460 --> 02:06:20.790
is F0/1.

02:06:20.790 --> 02:06:25.810
So, since this is a fairly simple step, I’ll
go straight to showing the commands in the

02:06:25.810 --> 02:06:27.340
notepad.

02:06:27.340 --> 02:06:33.849
On R1, and the core and distribution switches,
we just need to use NO CDP RUN to disable

02:06:33.849 --> 02:06:38.619
CDP, and then LLDP RUN to enable LLDP instead.

02:06:38.619 --> 02:06:44.900
We’ll use the same commands on the access
switches, but also use NO LLDP TRANSMIT on

02:06:44.900 --> 02:06:47.309
each switch’s F0/1 interface.

02:06:47.309 --> 02:06:52.510
So, I’ll copy these commands for R1 and
the core and distribution switches.

02:06:52.510 --> 02:06:55.170
And let’s go on R1 now.

02:06:55.170 --> 02:07:00.610
Right click, paste, and since this is the
final step for this part of the lab I’ll

02:07:00.610 --> 02:07:03.219
use DO WRITE to save the config.

02:07:03.219 --> 02:07:05.200
Then CSW1.

02:07:05.200 --> 02:07:08.250
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:07:08.250 --> 02:07:10.260
And CSW2.

02:07:10.260 --> 02:07:13.719
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:07:13.719 --> 02:07:15.170
DSW-A1.

02:07:15.170 --> 02:07:18.230
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:07:18.230 --> 02:07:20.090
Then A2.

02:07:20.090 --> 02:07:22.970
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:07:22.970 --> 02:07:25.400
DSW-B1 next.

02:07:25.400 --> 02:07:28.340
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:07:28.340 --> 02:07:29.909
And then B2.

02:07:29.909 --> 02:07:32.849
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:07:32.849 --> 02:07:37.469
Now let’s go back to the notepad and copy
the commands for the access switches, disabling

02:07:37.469 --> 02:07:41.150
LLDP transmission on their F0/1 interfaces.

02:07:41.150 --> 02:07:45.199
Let’s paste them into ASW-A1 first.

02:07:45.199 --> 02:07:48.130
Right click, paste and DO WRITE.

02:07:48.130 --> 02:07:50.250
Then A2.

02:07:50.250 --> 02:07:53.139
Right click, paste, and DO WRITE.

02:07:53.139 --> 02:07:54.219
And A3.

02:07:54.219 --> 02:07:57.320
Paste the commands, and save with DO WRITE.

02:07:57.320 --> 02:07:59.449
Okay, three more.

02:07:59.449 --> 02:08:04.349
On B1, right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:08:04.349 --> 02:08:05.969
ASW-B2.

02:08:05.969 --> 02:08:09.150
Paste the commands in, DO WRITE.

02:08:09.150 --> 02:08:12.340
And finally, ASW-B3.

02:08:12.340 --> 02:08:14.110
Right click, paste, DO WRITE.

02:08:14.110 --> 02:08:18.829
Okay, looking at the completion score, you
can see that we’re almost done with this

02:08:18.829 --> 02:08:19.969
lab.

02:08:19.969 --> 02:08:23.550
There are still three sections remaining,
but they will be shorter than this one.

02:08:23.550 --> 02:08:28.020
So, let’s click on Next to move on to part
7.

02:08:28.020 --> 02:08:30.710
In part 7, our focus is security.

02:08:30.710 --> 02:08:36.329
We’ll configure and apply an extended ACL
to limit traffic from Office A’s PCs to

02:08:36.329 --> 02:08:43.160
Office B’s PCs in step 1, and then configure
Port Security, DHCP Snooping, and DAI on the

02:08:43.160 --> 02:08:44.160
access switches.

02:08:44.160 --> 02:08:47.730
So, let’s get started with step 1.

02:08:47.730 --> 02:08:53.219
It says to configure extended ACL OfficeA_to_OfficeB
where appropriate.

02:08:53.219 --> 02:08:58.930
It should allow ICMP messages from the Office
A PCs to the Office B PCs, block all other

02:08:58.930 --> 02:09:04.640
traffic from the Office A PCs to the Office
B PCs, but permit all other traffic.

02:09:04.640 --> 02:09:12.159
Step 1d says to apply the ACL according to
general best practice for extended ACLs.

02:09:12.159 --> 02:09:16.940
That general best practice is that extended
ACLs should be applied as close to the source

02:09:16.940 --> 02:09:18.180
as possible.

02:09:18.180 --> 02:09:23.670
Standard ACLs, on the other hand, should generally
be applied as close to the destination as

02:09:23.670 --> 02:09:25.620
possible.

02:09:25.620 --> 02:09:31.239
In this case, we are filtering traffic from
Office A’s PCs to Office B’s PCs, so the

02:09:31.239 --> 02:09:33.900
source is Office A.

02:09:33.900 --> 02:09:39.360
The access switches are layer 2, so we can’t
apply IP ACLs to their interfaces.

02:09:39.360 --> 02:09:47.620
So, the closest location to the source is
the VLAN 10 SVI of DSW-A1 and DSW-A2 - the

02:09:47.620 --> 02:09:50.250
default gateway for the Office A PCs.

02:09:50.250 --> 02:09:56.820
Currently, DSW-A1 is the HSRP active router,
but we should configure and apply the ACL

02:09:56.820 --> 02:10:03.650
on DSW-A2’s VLAN 10 SVI as well, since it
must be ready to take over if DSW-A1 fails.

02:10:03.650 --> 02:10:10.099
So, let’s configure and apply it on DSW-A1
first, and then we’ll do the same on A2.

02:10:10.099 --> 02:10:17.659
First, let’s create the ACL with IP ACCESS-LIST
EXTENDED OfficeA_to_OfficeB.

02:10:17.659 --> 02:10:21.030
Now, we need to create three entries.

02:10:21.030 --> 02:10:27.409
One to permit ICMP traffic from the Office
A PCs to the Office B PCs, one to deny other

02:10:27.409 --> 02:10:34.360
traffic from the Office A PCs to the Office
B PCs, and then one to permit all other traffic.

02:10:34.360 --> 02:10:42.410
The Office A PC subnet is 10.1.0.0/24, and
the Office B PC subnet is 10.3.0.0/24.

02:10:42.410 --> 02:10:46.890
So, let’s configure the first entry.

02:10:46.890 --> 02:10:58.449
PERMIT ICMP 10.1.0.0 0.0.0.255, that’s the
Office A subnet, 10.3.0.0 0.0.0.255, that’s

02:10:58.449 --> 02:11:00.309
the Office B subnet.

02:11:00.309 --> 02:11:05.800
For the second entry, it’s DENY IP, and
then the same subnets.

02:11:05.800 --> 02:11:12.739
10.1.0.0 0.0.0.255 10.3.0.0 0.0.0.255.

02:11:12.739 --> 02:11:18.730
And for the final entry, PERMIT IP ANY ANY
to allow all other traffic.

02:11:18.730 --> 02:11:24.199
Now let’s apply it as close to the source
as possible, which is the VLAN 10 SVI – the

02:11:24.199 --> 02:11:30.110
layer 3 interface that receives packets from
hosts in the Office A PC subnet.

02:11:30.110 --> 02:11:31.960
INTERFACE VLAN 10.

02:11:31.960 --> 02:11:35.660
IP ACCESS-GROUP OfficeA_to_OfficeB IN.

02:11:35.660 --> 02:11:38.800
Okay, that’s all for DSW-A1.

02:11:38.800 --> 02:11:42.820
I’ll use EXIT and then DO WRITE to save
the config.

02:11:42.820 --> 02:11:47.349
Now I’ll go on DSW-A2 and configure the
same.

02:11:47.349 --> 02:11:50.150
So, first create the ACL.

02:11:50.150 --> 02:11:53.880
IP ACCESS-LIST EXTENDED OfficeA_to_OfficeB.

02:11:53.880 --> 02:11:58.969
Then the first entry, permitting ICMP.

02:11:58.969 --> 02:12:08.489
PERMIT ICMP 10.1.0.0 0.0.0.255 10.3.0.0 0.0.0.255.

02:12:08.489 --> 02:12:10.290
Then deny other traffic.

02:12:10.290 --> 02:12:19.880
DENY IP 10.1.0.0 0.0.0.255 10.3.0.0 0.0.0.255.

02:12:19.880 --> 02:12:21.500
And permit all other traffic.

02:12:21.500 --> 02:12:23.969
PERMIT IP ANY ANY.

02:12:23.969 --> 02:12:27.719
And then apply it to the VLAN 10 SVI.

02:12:27.719 --> 02:12:29.610
INTERFACE VLAN 10.

02:12:29.610 --> 02:12:34.219
IP ACCESS-GROUP OfficeA_to_OfficeB IN.

02:12:34.219 --> 02:12:37.460
Finally, EXIT and DO WRITE.

02:12:37.460 --> 02:12:40.010
So, we’re done with step 1.

02:12:40.010 --> 02:12:45.280
We created and applied an extended ACL as
close to the source as possible, filtering

02:12:45.280 --> 02:12:51.239
traffic from the Office A PC subnet to the
Office B PC subnet.

02:12:51.239 --> 02:12:55.989
Now let’s move on to step 2, in which we’ll
configure Port Security on the F0/1 port of

02:12:55.989 --> 02:12:57.320
each access switch.

02:12:57.320 --> 02:12:59.489
Let’s read the instructions.

02:12:59.489 --> 02:13:05.389
2a says to allow the minimum necessary number
of MAC addresses on each port.

02:13:05.389 --> 02:13:10.550
For example, for these ports with a phone
and a PC, two MAC addresses are needed: one

02:13:10.550 --> 02:13:13.730
for the phone, and one for the PC.

02:13:13.730 --> 02:13:17.660
The ports connected to LWAPs only need one
MAC address.

02:13:17.660 --> 02:13:22.810
The LWAP tunnels all client traffic, so the
switch should only see the LWAP’s own MAC

02:13:22.810 --> 02:13:24.230
address.

02:13:24.230 --> 02:13:29.250
And this note mentions that SRV1 doesn’t
use virtualization, so it uses only a single

02:13:29.250 --> 02:13:30.489
MAC address.

02:13:30.489 --> 02:13:36.159
If it had virtual machines running on it,
each VM would have its own MAC address.

02:13:36.159 --> 02:13:43.070
Okay, then step 2b says to configure a violation
mode that blocks invalid traffic without affecting

02:13:43.070 --> 02:13:44.940
valid traffic.

02:13:44.940 --> 02:13:50.560
And the switches should send notifications,
such as Syslog messages or SNMP traps, when

02:13:50.560 --> 02:13:52.210
invalid traffic is detected.

02:13:52.210 --> 02:13:56.400
So, that’s referring to the ‘restrict’
violation mode.

02:13:56.400 --> 02:14:02.320
Finally, 2c says that switches should automatically
save the secure MAC addresses they learn to

02:14:02.320 --> 02:14:04.010
the running-config.

02:14:04.010 --> 02:14:07.119
In other words, we must enable sticky MAC
address learning.

02:14:07.119 --> 02:14:14.340
So, let’s configure ASW-A1 manually and
then copy and paste the commands for the others.

02:14:14.340 --> 02:14:19.300
Port Security is configured directly on the
interface, so INTERFACE F0/1.

02:14:19.300 --> 02:14:24.050
First, enable it with SWITCHPORT PORT-SECURITY.

02:14:24.050 --> 02:14:29.370
And then enable the ‘restrict’ violation
mode with SWITCHPORT PORT-SECURITY VIOLATION

02:14:29.370 --> 02:14:30.980
RESTRICT.

02:14:30.980 --> 02:14:36.090
And finally, enable sticky MAC address learning
with SWITCHPORT PORT-SECURITY MAC-ADDRESS

02:14:36.090 --> 02:14:37.090
STICKY.

02:14:37.090 --> 02:14:39.920
Okay, that’s all for ASW-A1.

02:14:39.920 --> 02:14:44.219
I’ll EXIT to return to global config mode.

02:14:44.219 --> 02:14:48.070
ASW-B1 and ASW-B3 also need the same commands.

02:14:48.070 --> 02:14:52.059
So, I’ll go to the notepad, and here are
the commands.

02:14:52.059 --> 02:14:58.380
Highlight and copy them, and then I’ll open
the CLI of ASW-B1 and paste them.

02:14:58.380 --> 02:15:00.520
And then EXIT.

02:15:00.520 --> 02:15:03.239
Then ASW-B3.

02:15:03.239 --> 02:15:06.500
Paste the commands in, and EXIT.

02:15:06.500 --> 02:15:10.410
Now let’s configure ASW-A2, A3, and B2.

02:15:10.410 --> 02:15:12.909
They require an additional command.

02:15:12.909 --> 02:15:15.310
Let’s open up the notepad again.

02:15:15.310 --> 02:15:20.750
Because these switches connect to a phone
and a PC, we need to use the SWITCHPORT PORT-SECURITY

02:15:20.750 --> 02:15:26.670
MAXIMUM 2 command to allow two MAC addresses:
the PC’s MAC address and the phone’s MAC

02:15:26.670 --> 02:15:27.670
address.

02:15:27.670 --> 02:15:33.630
I didn’t configure this command on ASW-A1,
B1, or B3, because the default number of allowed

02:15:33.630 --> 02:15:37.520
addresses is 1, and that’s all that’s
needed on those ports.

02:15:37.520 --> 02:15:45.679
So, I’ll highlight and copy these commands,
and now go on to ASW-A2 and paste them in.

02:15:45.679 --> 02:15:47.409
And then EXIT.

02:15:47.409 --> 02:15:50.090
Then ASW-A3.

02:15:50.090 --> 02:15:53.430
Paste the commands, and EXIT.

02:15:53.430 --> 02:15:56.040
And ASW-B2.

02:15:56.040 --> 02:15:57.739
Paste the commands, and EXIT.

02:15:57.739 --> 02:16:03.130
Okay, we’ve enabled Port Security on the
access switches, allowed the minimum necessary

02:16:03.130 --> 02:16:09.930
number of MAC addresses, and configured the
restrict violation mode and sticky learning.

02:16:09.930 --> 02:16:15.500
Now let’s move on to step 3, in which we’ll
configure DHCP Snooping on these switches.

02:16:15.500 --> 02:16:17.180
There are a few requirements.

02:16:17.180 --> 02:16:22.400
3a says to enable DHCP Snooping for all active
VLANs in each LAN.

02:16:22.400 --> 02:16:31.179
So, VLANs 10, 20, 40, and 99 in Office A,
and VLANs 10, 20, 30, and 99 in Office B.

02:16:31.179 --> 02:16:37.319
Then, we must trust the appropriate ports,
which are those pointing toward the DHCP server,

02:16:37.319 --> 02:16:38.319
R1.

02:16:38.319 --> 02:16:43.840
In other words, we must trust the G0/1 and
G0/2 uplinks that connect to the distribution

02:16:43.840 --> 02:16:44.840
layer.

02:16:44.840 --> 02:16:51.670
Then, in 3c we must disable insertion of option
82, also known as the relay agent information

02:16:51.670 --> 02:16:52.670
option.

02:16:52.670 --> 02:17:00.160
Then, we’ll set a DHCP rate limit of 15
pps, packets per second, on untrusted ports.

02:17:00.160 --> 02:17:06.450
However, ASW-A1’s connection to WLC1 should
have a 100 pps limit.

02:17:06.450 --> 02:17:11.301
Once again, I’ll manually configure ASW-A1
and then paste the configurations for the

02:17:11.301 --> 02:17:12.819
other switches.

02:17:12.819 --> 02:17:20.340
So, on ASW-A1 I’ll first enable DHCP Snooping
with IP DHCP SNOOPING.

02:17:20.340 --> 02:17:28.359
However, we also need to enable it on a per-VLAN
basis, and the command is IP DHCP SNOOPING

02:17:28.359 --> 02:17:30.540
VLAN 10,20,40,99.

02:17:30.540 --> 02:17:38.420
Next, I’ll disable option 82 insertion with
NO IP DHCP SNOOPING INFORMATION OPTION.

02:17:38.420 --> 02:17:44.750
That’s a step that people often forget;
it can prevent DHCP from working properly.

02:17:44.750 --> 02:17:49.080
Okay, next I’ll trust the uplinks to the
distribution layer.

02:17:49.080 --> 02:17:50.920
INTERFACE RANGE G0/1-2.

02:17:50.920 --> 02:17:54.639
IP DHCP SNOOPING TRUST.

02:17:54.639 --> 02:18:00.569
Next, let’s set rate limits for DHCP messages
on untrusted ports.

02:18:00.569 --> 02:18:02.760
F0/1 first.

02:18:02.760 --> 02:18:03.760
INTERFACE F0/1.

02:18:03.760 --> 02:18:07.819
IP DHCP SNOOPING LIMIT RATE 15.

02:18:07.819 --> 02:18:14.859
So, if ASW-A1 receives DHCP messages on this
interface at a rate greater than 15 packets

02:18:14.859 --> 02:18:19.219
per second, the interface will be error-disabled.

02:18:19.219 --> 02:18:23.710
And now F0/2, which is connected to WLC1.

02:18:23.710 --> 02:18:24.710
INTERFACE F0/2.

02:18:24.710 --> 02:18:28.880
IP DHCP SNOOPING LIMIT RATE 100.

02:18:28.880 --> 02:18:31.399
Okay, that’s all.

02:18:31.399 --> 02:18:32.399
EXIT.

02:18:32.399 --> 02:18:36.179
Now let’s open the notepad and see the configurations
for the other switches.

02:18:36.179 --> 02:18:40.310
I’ll highlight and copy the commands for
ASW-A2 and A3.

02:18:40.310 --> 02:18:46.639
They are the same as A1, minus the F0/2 interface,
which is disabled on these two switches.

02:18:46.639 --> 02:18:50.210
Okay, I’ll paste these commands into ASW-A2.

02:18:50.210 --> 02:18:55.200
And then return to global config mode with
EXIT.

02:18:55.200 --> 02:18:58.050
Next, ASW-A3.

02:18:58.050 --> 02:19:00.830
Right click, paste, and EXIT.

02:19:00.830 --> 02:19:05.519
Okay, let’s return to the notepad for the
Office B switches.

02:19:05.519 --> 02:19:10.750
The commands here are almost identical, just
replacing VLAN 40 with VLAN 30, the Servers

02:19:10.750 --> 02:19:11.750
VLAN.

02:19:11.750 --> 02:19:17.610
So, after copying these commands, let’s
paste them into ASW-B1.

02:19:17.610 --> 02:19:18.870
And then EXIT.

02:19:18.870 --> 02:19:21.050
Then B2.

02:19:21.050 --> 02:19:22.139
EXIT.

02:19:22.139 --> 02:19:24.010
And finally, B3.

02:19:24.010 --> 02:19:25.010
EXIT.

02:19:25.010 --> 02:19:31.840
Okay, step 3 is done, now let’s move on
to step 4, in which we’ll configure DAI,

02:19:31.840 --> 02:19:34.010
Dynamic ARP Inspection.

02:19:34.010 --> 02:19:39.050
We need to enable it for all active VLANs,
trust the appropriate ports, and enable all

02:19:39.050 --> 02:19:41.719
optional validation checks.

02:19:41.719 --> 02:19:44.880
Once again, let’s configure ASW-A1 first.

02:19:44.880 --> 02:19:48.990
Unlike DHCP Snooping, DAI only needs to be
enabled per-VLAN.

02:19:48.990 --> 02:19:51.620
You don’t need to enable it globally.

02:19:51.620 --> 02:19:58.700
So, first I’ll use IP ARP INSPECTION VLAN
10,20,40,99 to enable it.

02:19:58.700 --> 02:20:01.870
Next, let’s enable the optional checks.

02:20:01.870 --> 02:20:07.780
Usually, DAI checks to make sure a matching
entry exists in the DHCP Snooping binding

02:20:07.780 --> 02:20:08.920
table.

02:20:08.920 --> 02:20:13.340
But you can enable these checks to make it
perform a more thorough inspection of ARP

02:20:13.340 --> 02:20:14.380
messages.

02:20:14.380 --> 02:20:21.290
The command is IP ARP INSPECTION DST-MAC SRC-MAC
IP.

02:20:21.290 --> 02:20:24.720
And finally, I’ll trust the two uplink ports.

02:20:24.720 --> 02:20:26.560
INTERFACE RANGE G0/1-2.

02:20:26.560 --> 02:20:29.149
IP ARP INSPECTION TRUST.

02:20:29.149 --> 02:20:30.899
Okay, that’s all.

02:20:30.899 --> 02:20:36.540
I’ll use EXIT and then save with DO WRITE
since this is the last step for this part.

02:20:36.540 --> 02:20:41.410
Now I’ll open up the notepad and go to part
7 step 4.

02:20:41.410 --> 02:20:44.760
So, here are the commands we just configured
on ASW-A1.

02:20:44.760 --> 02:20:50.560
I’ll copy them, and then let’s paste them
into ASW-A2 and A3.

02:20:50.560 --> 02:20:52.720
A2 first.

02:20:52.720 --> 02:20:54.010
Paste the commands.

02:20:54.010 --> 02:20:57.470
EXIT, and save with DO WRITE.

02:20:57.470 --> 02:20:59.220
Then A3.

02:20:59.220 --> 02:21:00.220
Paste the commands.

02:21:00.220 --> 02:21:02.060
EXIT, and DO WRITE.

02:21:02.060 --> 02:21:06.939
Now let’s go back to the notepad, and copy
the commands for Office B.

02:21:06.939 --> 02:21:11.630
The commands are the same, just replacing
VLAN 40 with VLAN 30.

02:21:11.630 --> 02:21:18.149
Enable DAI on each VLAN, enable the optional
checks, and then trust G0/1 and 2.

02:21:18.149 --> 02:21:23.050
So, I’ll go on ASW-B1 first and paste the
commands in.

02:21:23.050 --> 02:21:27.470
And then EXIT and save the config with DO
WRITE.

02:21:27.470 --> 02:21:28.470
Then B2.

02:21:28.470 --> 02:21:32.240
Copy the commands, EXIT and DO WRITE.

02:21:32.240 --> 02:21:34.399
And finally, B3.

02:21:34.399 --> 02:21:37.970
Copy the commands, EXIT, and DO WRITE.

02:21:37.970 --> 02:21:41.971
Okay, we’re done with the security section
of this lab.

02:21:41.971 --> 02:21:47.380
We configured and applied an extended ACL,
and then configured the layer-2 security features

02:21:47.380 --> 02:21:51.590
Port Security, DHCP Snooping, and Dynamic
ARP Inspection.

02:21:51.590 --> 02:21:56.630
I’ll click Next to move on to part 8.

02:21:56.630 --> 02:21:58.670
Part 8 is all about IPv6.

02:21:58.670 --> 02:22:05.420
However, we’re not going to do a full IPv6
configuration, just some IP addresses on R1,

02:22:05.420 --> 02:22:10.420
CSW1, and CSW2, and a couple of routes on
R1.

02:22:10.420 --> 02:22:15.700
Since this lab is already long enough, let’s
just test that you know the basic IPv6 configuration

02:22:15.700 --> 02:22:18.000
commands for the CCNA exam.

02:22:18.000 --> 02:22:26.010
So, in step 1 we’ll enable IPv6 routing
and configure IPv6 addresses on R1, CSW1,

02:22:26.010 --> 02:22:28.170
and CSW2.

02:22:28.170 --> 02:22:37.590
On R1 G0/0/0, which is connected to the Internet,
we’ll configure 2001:db8:a::2/64, and then

02:22:37.590 --> 02:22:43.590
:b::2/64 on G0/1/0, which is also connected
to the Internet.

02:22:43.590 --> 02:22:48.700
Then, for the connections between R1 and the
core switches, we’ll use these specified

02:22:48.700 --> 02:22:58.260
prefixes, 2001:db8:a1::/64 and a2::/64, and
use EUI-64 to automatically generate interface

02:22:58.260 --> 02:22:59.260
IDs.

02:22:59.260 --> 02:23:05.840
Finally, for the EtherChannel connection between
CSW1 and CSW2, we’ll enable IPv6 on the

02:23:05.840 --> 02:23:09.689
interfaces without using the IPV6 ADDRESS
command.

02:23:09.689 --> 02:23:15.350
In other words, we’ll use the IPV6 ENABLE
command, which enables IPv6 and generates

02:23:15.350 --> 02:23:16.760
a link-local address.

02:23:16.760 --> 02:23:20.550
Okay, let’s get started by configuring R1.

02:23:20.550 --> 02:23:27.950
Now, before configuring the interfaces, don’t
forget to enable IPv6 routing with IPV6 UNICAST-ROUTING.

02:23:27.950 --> 02:23:31.521
That’s a common command to forget.

02:23:31.521 --> 02:23:35.900
Now I’ll configure G0/0/0, connected to
the Internet.

02:23:35.900 --> 02:23:37.550
INTERFACE G0/0/0.

02:23:37.550 --> 02:23:44.180
IPV6 ADDRESS 2001:db8:a::2/64.

02:23:44.180 --> 02:23:46.930
And then G0/1/0.

02:23:46.930 --> 02:23:48.560
INTERFACE G0/1/0.

02:23:48.560 --> 02:23:52.180
IPV6 ADDRESS 2001:db8:b::2/64.

02:23:52.180 --> 02:24:00.590
Okay, we’ve configured R1’s Internet-connected
interfaces, now let’s do the LAN-facing

02:24:00.590 --> 02:24:01.840
interfaces.

02:24:01.840 --> 02:24:08.300
Looking back at the instructions again, I
need to use this prefix with EUI-64 for G0/0,

02:24:08.300 --> 02:24:10.260
and this prefix for G0/1.

02:24:10.260 --> 02:24:14.229
Let’s return to the CLI and do that.

02:24:14.229 --> 02:24:15.800
INTERFACE G0/0.

02:24:15.800 --> 02:24:24.189
IPV6 ADDRESS 2001:db8:a1::/64 EUI-64.

02:24:24.189 --> 02:24:26.550
And then G0/1.

02:24:26.550 --> 02:24:28.000
INTERFACE G0/1.

02:24:28.000 --> 02:24:32.920
IPV6 ADDRESS 2001:db8:a2::/64 EUI-64.

02:24:32.920 --> 02:24:38.859
Alright, we’ve configured R1’s interfaces.

02:24:38.859 --> 02:24:43.260
Now let’s quickly confirm with DO SHOW IPV6
INTERFACE BRIEF.

02:24:43.260 --> 02:24:48.490
Okay, there are the four interfaces we just
configured, each with a link-local address

02:24:48.490 --> 02:24:52.420
as well as the global unicast address we configured.

02:24:52.420 --> 02:24:57.779
Now let’s configure CSW1 and CSW2’s G1/0/1
interfaces.

02:24:57.779 --> 02:25:01.740
For both of them, we’ll use EUI-64 just
like we did on R1.

02:25:01.740 --> 02:25:05.450
I’ll go on CSW1 first.

02:25:05.450 --> 02:25:11.950
Before configuring the IP address, let’s
use IPV6 UNICAST-ROUTING to enable IPv6 routing.

02:25:11.950 --> 02:25:16.300
You should make a habit of configuring that
first so you don’t forget.

02:25:16.300 --> 02:25:18.970
Next, INTERFACE G1/0/1.

02:25:18.970 --> 02:25:24.390
IPV6 ADDRESS 2001:db8:a1::/64 EUI-64.

02:25:24.390 --> 02:25:29.760
Okay, that’s CSW1.

02:25:29.760 --> 02:25:31.560
Next I’ll go on CSW2.

02:25:31.560 --> 02:25:35.109
First, enable IPv6 routing.

02:25:35.109 --> 02:25:37.310
IPV6 UNICAST-ROUTING.

02:25:37.310 --> 02:25:39.840
And then configure the interface.

02:25:39.840 --> 02:25:41.330
INTERFACE G1/0/1.

02:25:41.330 --> 02:25:47.609
IPV6 ADDRESS 2001:db8:a2::/64 EUI-64.

02:25:47.609 --> 02:25:54.470
Okay, finally let’s do the EtherChannel
between CSW1 and CSW2.

02:25:54.470 --> 02:25:58.360
Since I’m already on CSW2, I’ll start
here.

02:25:58.360 --> 02:26:00.479
INTERFACE PORT-CHANNEL1.

02:26:00.479 --> 02:26:06.340
The instructions said to enable IPv6 without
using the IPV6 ADDRESS command, so the command

02:26:06.340 --> 02:26:09.029
to use here is IPV6 ENABLE.

02:26:09.029 --> 02:26:12.300
Let’s verify the effect of that command.

02:26:12.300 --> 02:26:14.960
DO SHOW IPV6 INTERFACE BRIEF.

02:26:14.960 --> 02:26:18.630
So, look at the port-channel1 interface.

02:26:18.630 --> 02:26:24.229
Enabling IPv6 with IPV6 ENABLE automatically
generates a link-local address like this.

02:26:24.229 --> 02:26:31.380
Okay, now I’ll save the config with DO WRITE
since this was the last configuration on CSW2.

02:26:31.380 --> 02:26:34.569
And now I’ll go on to CSW1.

02:26:34.569 --> 02:26:35.569
INTERFACE PORT-CHANNEL1.

02:26:35.569 --> 02:26:36.990
IPV6 ENABLE.

02:26:36.990 --> 02:26:39.450
And then save the config.

02:26:39.450 --> 02:26:40.779
DO WRITE.

02:26:40.779 --> 02:26:43.080
So, step 1 is done.

02:26:43.080 --> 02:26:49.140
We configured IPv6 addresses in three different
ways: configuring the exact address, configuring

02:26:49.140 --> 02:26:55.490
a /64 prefix and using EUI-64, and then using
IPV6 ENABLE.

02:26:55.490 --> 02:27:01.630
Now in step 2, we’ll configure two default
static routes on R1, pointing to the Internet.

02:27:01.630 --> 02:27:08.970
We’ll configure a recursive static route
via next hop 2001:db8:a::1, the ISP connected

02:27:08.970 --> 02:27:11.220
to G0/0/0.

02:27:11.220 --> 02:27:18.779
And then a fully-specified route via next
hop 2001:db8:b::1, the ISP connected to G0/1/0.

02:27:18.779 --> 02:27:23.939
This second route should be a floating route,
with an AD 1 higher than the default.

02:27:23.939 --> 02:27:28.350
Okay, let’s return to R1 to configure those
routes.

02:27:28.350 --> 02:27:32.470
The instructions say the first route should
be a recursive route, meaning it should only

02:27:32.470 --> 02:27:35.340
specify the next-hop IP address.

02:27:35.340 --> 02:27:45.100
So, IPV6 ROUTE ::/0, that’s equivalent to
0.0.0.0/0 in IPv4, and then the next hop is

02:27:45.100 --> 02:27:49.870
2001:db8:a::1.

02:27:49.870 --> 02:27:55.029
Now the next route, which must be fully specified,
meaning it should specify both the exit interface

02:27:55.029 --> 02:27:57.420
and the next-hop IP address.

02:27:57.420 --> 02:27:59.860
It should also be a floating route.

02:27:59.860 --> 02:28:10.920
So, IPV6 ROUTE ::/0 G0/1/0 2001:db8:b::1,
and then set the AD to 2 to make it a floating

02:28:10.920 --> 02:28:11.920
route.

02:28:11.920 --> 02:28:15.370
Okay that’s it, let’s save with DO WRITE.

02:28:15.370 --> 02:28:17.100
And that’s all for part 8.

02:28:17.100 --> 02:28:23.880
We configured IPv6 addresses on R1, CSW1,
and CSW2, and then configured a couple of

02:28:23.880 --> 02:28:25.569
default routes on R1.

02:28:25.569 --> 02:28:28.870
I’ll click next to move on to part 9.

02:28:28.870 --> 02:28:34.200
Finally, we’ve reached last part of this
lab, in which we’ll configure a wireless

02:28:34.200 --> 02:28:36.800
LAN using the GUI of WLC1.

02:28:36.800 --> 02:28:39.620
Let’s take a look at the steps.

02:28:39.620 --> 02:28:47.370
First, of course, we have to access the GUI
of WLC1, which has the IP address 10.0.0.7.

02:28:47.370 --> 02:28:52.260
The login is admin with the password adminPW12.

02:28:52.260 --> 02:28:57.510
In step 2 we’ll create a dynamic interface
for the Wi-Fi WLAN.

02:28:57.510 --> 02:29:00.479
Then in step 3 create a wireless LAN.

02:29:00.479 --> 02:29:04.880
And then finally we’ll verify that both
LWAPs have associated with WLC1.

02:29:04.880 --> 02:29:10.520
There’s also a note saying that, due to
packet tracer’s limitations, wireless clients

02:29:10.520 --> 02:29:15.260
won’t be able to properly lease an IP address
from the Wi-Fi DHCP pool.

02:29:15.260 --> 02:29:20.000
In my experience, they always lease an IP
address from the management DHCP pool in Packet

02:29:20.000 --> 02:29:21.000
Tracer.

02:29:21.000 --> 02:29:23.970
Don’t worry about it – it’s just an
issue with packet tracer.

02:29:23.970 --> 02:29:26.380
So, let’s get started.

02:29:26.380 --> 02:29:30.279
I’ll access WLC1 from PC1.

02:29:30.279 --> 02:29:35.500
First I’ll open up the command prompt and
ping WLC1 just to make sure PC1 can reach

02:29:35.500 --> 02:29:36.500
it.

02:29:36.500 --> 02:29:38.860
PING 10.0.0.7.

02:29:38.860 --> 02:29:43.210
This should also ensure that all devices have
the correct ARP entries – it can be quite

02:29:43.210 --> 02:29:45.060
slow in packet tracer.

02:29:45.060 --> 02:29:50.560
Okay, next I’m going to leave the command
prompt and open up PC1’s web browser.

02:29:50.560 --> 02:29:52.970
It can take a few seconds.

02:29:52.970 --> 02:30:01.170
Once the browser opens up, use HTTPS to access
WLC1 by typing in the address bar.

02:30:01.170 --> 02:30:03.390
HTTPS://10.0.0.7.

02:30:03.390 --> 02:30:07.180
Here’s the login screen.

02:30:07.180 --> 02:30:12.400
Click on Login, and then enter the username
admin and the password adminPW12.

02:30:12.400 --> 02:30:14.990
Okay, we’re in.

02:30:14.990 --> 02:30:18.670
Now let’s look closer at step 2.

02:30:18.670 --> 02:30:25.840
We need to configure a dynamic interface for
the Wi-Fi WLAN, which is 10.6.0.0/24.

02:30:25.840 --> 02:30:30.130
The name should simply be Wi-Fi, with VLAN
number 40.

02:30:30.130 --> 02:30:36.550
It should use port number 1 on WLC1, its IP
address should be .2 of its subnet and default

02:30:36.550 --> 02:30:38.160
gateway .1.

02:30:38.160 --> 02:30:42.250
Finally, its DHCP server should be 10.0.0.76.

02:30:42.250 --> 02:30:46.850
Okay, let’s configure that on WLC1.

02:30:46.850 --> 02:30:53.729
To configure the WLC’s interfaces, open
the CONTROLLER tab.

02:30:53.729 --> 02:30:58.550
Once it loads, click on Interfaces on the
left.

02:30:58.550 --> 02:31:05.030
By default, the WLC has two interfaces: the
management interface and the virtual interface.

02:31:05.030 --> 02:31:07.859
Let’s create a dynamic interface.

02:31:07.859 --> 02:31:13.230
Scroll to the right of this page and click
on “New…”.

02:31:13.230 --> 02:31:16.670
The first menu has the interface name and
VLAN ID.

02:31:16.670 --> 02:31:21.340
So, let’s name the interface Wi-Fi, and
set the VLAN to 40.

02:31:21.340 --> 02:31:25.720
Then, click Apply to move to the next menu.

02:31:25.720 --> 02:31:27.740
We need to configure a few things here.

02:31:27.740 --> 02:31:32.779
Scroll down to Physical Information and set
the port number to 1.

02:31:32.779 --> 02:31:42.930
Then, under Interface Address set the IP to
10.6.0.2, the netmask to 255.255.255.0, and

02:31:42.930 --> 02:31:45.439
the gateway to 10.6.0.1.

02:31:45.439 --> 02:31:52.880
Finally, set the primary DHCP server to 10.0.0.76,
R1’s loopback interface.

02:31:52.880 --> 02:31:54.860
Okay, that’s it.

02:31:54.860 --> 02:32:00.630
Scroll up and click apply, and then click
Okay on the popup.

02:32:00.630 --> 02:32:01.630
And we’re done.

02:32:01.630 --> 02:32:06.899
I’ll click on Interfaces again to go back
to the list of interfaces, and as you can

02:32:06.899 --> 02:32:10.540
see in the list, the interface has been created.

02:32:10.540 --> 02:32:13.950
Next, let’s look at step 3.

02:32:13.950 --> 02:32:20.750
We need to create a WLAN with the name and
SSID Wi-Fi, and ID number of 1.

02:32:20.750 --> 02:32:27.510
We need to enable it, and set WPA2 with AES
encryption, and a pre shared key of cisco123.

02:32:27.510 --> 02:32:32.479
Okay, let’s go back to WLC1 and configure
it.

02:32:32.479 --> 02:32:37.510
WLANs are configured from the WLAN tab, of
course.

02:32:37.510 --> 02:32:42.431
To create a new WLAN, just click on Go here
on the right.

02:32:42.431 --> 02:32:48.260
In the first menu, we can set the profile
name, SSID and ID number.

02:32:48.260 --> 02:32:53.341
Both of these should simply be Wi-Fi, and
the ID should be 1, so we don’t have to

02:32:53.341 --> 02:32:54.840
change that.

02:32:54.840 --> 02:32:59.470
Okay, click on Apply to move on to the next
screen.

02:32:59.470 --> 02:33:03.979
On this next page, we need to configure a
couple of things.

02:33:03.979 --> 02:33:07.780
First, click the checkbox here to enable the
WLAN.

02:33:07.780 --> 02:33:14.279
Then, we should configure the interface; this
WLAN should use the Wi-Fi interface, not the

02:33:14.279 --> 02:33:15.540
management interface.

02:33:15.540 --> 02:33:20.330
Okay, after configuring that, click on the
Security tab.

02:33:20.330 --> 02:33:23.930
Let’s enable WPA2.

02:33:23.930 --> 02:33:30.090
From the layer 2 security drop-down, select
WPA+WPA2.

02:33:30.090 --> 02:33:33.820
Then click on WPA2 policy.

02:33:33.820 --> 02:33:39.590
For the encryption, AES is selected by default,
so we don’t have to change that.

02:33:39.590 --> 02:33:44.189
Then click on PSK to enable pre-shared key
authentication.

02:33:44.189 --> 02:33:47.260
And configure the PSK as cisco123.

02:33:47.260 --> 02:33:49.689
And that’s it.

02:33:49.689 --> 02:33:54.430
There are additional tabs here, but we don’t
have to configure them for this lab.

02:33:54.430 --> 02:33:57.580
Most of the remaining settings don’t work
in packet tracer, anyway.

02:33:57.580 --> 02:34:02.260
So, just click on apply in the top right to
apply the settings.

02:34:02.260 --> 02:34:04.050
All configurations are done!

02:34:04.050 --> 02:34:08.420
I’ll just click on Save Configuration to
save them.

02:34:08.420 --> 02:34:16.410
After saving the configurations, click on
MONITOR to return to the first screen.

02:34:16.410 --> 02:34:21.689
If you scroll down, you can see the access
points associated with WLC1.

02:34:21.689 --> 02:34:25.220
There should be two: LWAP1 and LWAP2.

02:34:25.220 --> 02:34:29.101
Click here to see a list, and here they are.

02:34:29.101 --> 02:34:32.570
Okay, I’ll do one more thing before finishing
up.

02:34:32.570 --> 02:34:35.770
Let’s open up Laptop1.

02:34:35.770 --> 02:34:39.820
From the Config tab, click on the Wireless0
interface.

02:34:39.820 --> 02:34:42.779
Let’s make it associate with LWAP1.

02:34:42.779 --> 02:34:47.740
So, specify the SSID ‘Wi-Fi’ that we just
configured.

02:34:47.740 --> 02:34:56.859
Under authentication, click on WPA2-PSK and
enter the PSK ‘cisco123’.

02:34:56.859 --> 02:35:02.260
Finally, select the correct encryption type:
AES.

02:35:02.260 --> 02:35:06.250
After a few seconds, Laptop 1 should associate
with LWAP1.

02:35:06.250 --> 02:35:11.390
However, look back at the note under step
4 in the instructions once more.

02:35:11.390 --> 02:35:16.250
Wireless clients won’t be able to lease
an IP address from the Wi-Fi DHCP pool.

02:35:16.250 --> 02:35:20.710
The Wi-Fi subnet is 10.6.0.0/24.

02:35:20.710 --> 02:35:27.090
But look at the IP address Laptop1 leased:
it’s in the 10.0.0.0/28 subnet: the Office

02:35:27.090 --> 02:35:29.310
A management subnet.

02:35:29.310 --> 02:35:31.450
But as I said, don’t worry about it.

02:35:31.450 --> 02:35:33.700
The configurations we did here are correct.

02:35:33.700 --> 02:35:36.010
It’s just a problem with packet tracer.

02:35:36.010 --> 02:35:39.601
So, we’re finally done.

02:35:39.601 --> 02:35:44.520
As the completion score of 100% here shows,
we did all of the steps correctly.

02:35:44.520 --> 02:35:50.359
To be honest, if you’re studying for the
CCNA exam, I’d be surprised if you got 100%

02:35:50.359 --> 02:35:56.189
on the first attempt – this is a huge lab
so you will most likely get a few things wrong.

02:35:56.189 --> 02:36:01.690
If your score isn’t 100%, click on Check
Results and then assessment items, and then

02:36:01.690 --> 02:36:04.790
click on ‘show incorrect items’.

02:36:04.790 --> 02:36:09.010
This will show you which commands you got
wrong, so you can go back and fix them.

02:36:09.010 --> 02:36:13.260
Okay, this video has gone on long enough,
so let’s end it here.

02:36:13.260 --> 02:36:16.830
This was the Jeremy’s IT Lab CCNA Mega Lab.

02:36:16.830 --> 02:36:20.560
I hope this lab and video were both challenging
and helpful.

02:36:20.560 --> 02:36:22.880
Thanks for watching.

